{"primary-runtime-update-jitter-ms":806725,"electron-persisted-atom-state":{"electron:onboarding-workspace-experiment-assignment":{"arm":"control","assignedAtMs":1778118078215,"experimentName":"93537254"},"electron:onboarding-primary-runtime-install-ready":true,"electron:onboarding-primary-runtime-install-requested":true,"electron:onboarding-welcome-pending":false,"electron:onboarding-welcome-v2-role-state":{"roles":["default"],"personalizedSuggestionsEnabled":false,"workMode":"coding"},"composer-permission-mode-visibility":{"guardian-approvals":true,"full-access":true},"electron:onboarding-override":"auto","electron:onboarding-projectless-completed":true,"electron:onboarding-hide-first-new-thread-promos":false,"electron:onboarding-plugin-checklist-active":true,"last_completed_onboarding":1778118096,"environment":null,"fast-mode-personalized-estimate":{"estimatedSavedMs":3552228,"rolloutCountWithCompletedTurns":12,"computedAtMs":1778907794029},"agent-mode-by-host-id":{"local":"custom"},"seen-model-upgrade-list":["gpt-5.5"],"prompt-history":{"global":["break down the current uncommited into a few focused commits","Deep dive into Cola's agent module — the execution core that owns sessions, prompt construction, subagent orchestration, work tracking, memory, and the tool surface.\n\n## Phase 1: Read the Docs\n\nThree docs build the mental model every agent-layer task needs. Read them in order.\n\n1. `docs/agent/README.md` — Session model, MODs, skills, memory, tools, cron, prompt queue, announce buffering. This is the map of the entire agent layer.\n2. `docs/agent/subagents.md` — Multi-turn child sessions with interactive control (idle state, session_send/wait/close), agent definitions, lifecycle, context inheritance, announce delivery and batching. Subagent delegation is the primary orchestration primitive.\n3. `docs/agent/memory.md` — Memory system map: global memory storage and write paths, voice overlay, awareness, nightly three-stage authoring pipeline, tools, read-on-demand vs inherited-inline design.\n\n### Invariants To Keep In Mind\n\nThese are the load-bearing behaviors that shape any code change in the agent layer. You don't need the deep-dive docs to respect them — the detail docs live in Phase 3 and are read when the task requires them.\n\n- **Main agent's system prompt is static.** Runtime-varying context (memory, work state, voice, reminders, caring notes) rides in message-side `<system-context>`, never the system prompt. Adding dynamic content to the static prompt invalidates cache on every turn. Subagents are short-lived and inherit memory inline instead.\n- **Compaction is automatic and cache-preserving.** Don't pre-optimize the session by truncating history or skipping messages — the summarizer handles it and manual truncation will break cache. L1 stacks new \"eras\" without rewriting old ones; L2 merges when the user is idle.\n- **Delegate large reads to subagents.** Image inspection, bulk file scans, and verbose commands belong in child sessions via `session_spawn`, returning textual summaries. Keeping the main session's context lean is the agent's responsibility, enforced through prompt rules.\n- **Single-flight per scope.** One prompt runs at a time per scope. Additional user input goes through the prompt queue with `steer` / `followUp` / `collect` modes.\n- **Post-turn sequence drains in a fixed order:** deferred session updates → prompt queue → announce flush → awareness delivery → compaction check → cron drain → idle timer restart. New post-turn hooks land in this sequence.\n\nWhen to go deeper: `docs/agent/prompt-system.md` for block architecture, `docs/agent/prompt-flow.md` for message lifecycle, `docs/agent/context-management.md` for compaction and cache behavior. All three are Phase 3 — read when your work requires them.\n\nFor an intuitive sense of the assembled prompt, browse `data.local/system-prompt-*.md` — generated snapshots of the main agent and all ten subagent prompts, refreshed by `scripts/show-system-prompt.ts`.\n\n## Dive into awareness and proactive systems\n\nNow you have a good understanding of the overall system, lets focus on the thing we will be improving and debugging this session, the awareness system and the awareness system.\n\n### Proactive Systems\n\nEverything Cola does without being asked, plus the plumbing that gets background results to the user. We're mainly going to be working to debug some user-reported issues for the awareness system in this session. It is essential that you have a good understanding of awareness, what it is, and the overall system.\n\n- **Proactive behavior map**: Read `docs/agent/proactive-scheduling.md` — caring, user-created crons, awareness delivery, internal maintenance crons; TTS suppression for non-user prompts.\n- **Delivery mechanics**: Read `docs/agent/proactive-delivery.md` — shared gate primitives (structured skip reasons, delivery mutex, soft-timer arm/fire-gate split, conversational quiet threshold), awareness delivery state machine (`pending | in_flight | delivered | unannounced | expired`), single-note newest-first selection, teaser via `PromptDecoration`, deterministic jitter for maintenance crons. Key files: `server/agent/awareness-delivery.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-index.ts`, `server/cron/internal-maintenance-jitter.ts`.\n- **Awareness**: Read `docs/agent/awareness.md` — reflective note authoring (instant `awareness_update` drafts + nightly publication), archive reconciliation, motif rotation, Imprints reader and `seenAt` read state. Key files: `server/agent/tools/awareness.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-archive.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-index.ts`, `server/cron/memory-cron.ts`, `electron/awareness-notes.ts`.\n- **Caring**: Read `docs/agent/caring.md` — idle-triggered subagent; notes (injected into next user message as `<system-context>`, not proactively delivered) vs reminders (one-shot crons via standard cron scheduler). Key dir: `server/agent/caring/`.\n- **Cron scheduling**: Read `docs/agent/cron.md` — global vs MOD sources, scheduling model, pause/resume/expiry, `catchUp` policy + checkpoint, isolated root-session execution with one-per-cronKey guard, direct announce delivery. Key files: `server/cron/cron-scheduler.ts`, `server/cron/cron-store.ts`.\n- **Autonomous guardrails**: Read `docs/agent/autonomous-guardrails.md` when touching Caring/internal maintenance budget caps, runtime timeouts, sleep-drift aborts, side-effect tool loop detection, or purpose-aware cache policy.\n\n## After Onboarding\n\nReport back when you have a thorough understanding of the agent module. Then you're ready for implementation tasks.","As I mentioned, in this session we are mostly going to be investigating user reports regarding our awareness system. Specifically, we'll look at a subset of reports where users can't see awareness or have concerns about the quality.\n\nI don't necessarily think these are all bugs. For example:\n1. The quality might degrade because they chose a less competent model.\n2. They might not see an awareness because none was generated for the day, even though the workflow itself was successful.\n\nYou should also be mindful of timeline issues. In the past week, we have been fixing several bugs regarding failed awareness generation and workflow errors. If the user logs show the issue was generated in an older version before those fixes were implemented, there is probably nothing for us to do at this point.\n\nfollow .claude/skills/github-issue-analyze/SKILL.md to investigate the following 3 issues \n\n- #1720: user reports no awareness generated\n- #1721: user thinks awareness quality degradation\n- #1714: again awareness did not update \n\nI have downloaded all the artifcats for you already, so you can focus on analyzing\n\n```\nssues.local/\n  ├── 1714-awareness-did-not-update/        (v0.7.4, mac, 2026-05-06, daqian.li43@gmail.com)\n  │   ├── issue.md\n  │   ├── cola-logs.zip\n  │   ├── screenshot-20260506-212735.png    ← user-attached screenshot\n  │   └── extracted/                        (3 days of logs, 96 sessions, 38 trace files)\n  ├── 1720-no-awareness-generated/           (v0.7.7, mac, 2026-05-07, k@marswave.ai)\n  │   ├── issue.md\n  │   ├── cola-logs.zip\n  │   └── extracted/                        (3 days of logs, 51 sessions, 21 trace files)\n  └── 1721-awareness-quality-degradation/    (v0.7.7, mac, 2026-05-07, linnahjl@outlook.com)\n      ├── issue.md\n      ├── cola-logs.zip\n      └── extracted/                        (3 days of logs, 7 sessions, 1 trace file)\n```\n\nthe latest version of cola is 0.7.7\n\nDO NOT CHANGE ANY CODE YET. Step back and reason about the module/feature holistically before proposing any fix.\n\n1. State the real problem and the underlying UX goal in your own words. If my framing seems off, push back before going further.\n2. Evaluate the current design against that goal — where does it fall short, and is the issue local or structural?\n3. From first principles, present 2–3 approaches with concrete tradeoffs (complexity, blast radius, UX impact, future flexibility). Recommend one and explain why.ed design with another patch. Don't shy away from large-scale changes when they're justified — but be explicit about what they cost.\n","A senior engineer reviewed your analysis and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct.\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\nRead it carefully. Here's where they sharpened my analysis, where I think they're missing pieces, and what the combined recommendation should be.\n\n## Where they're stronger than me\n\n1. **The five-state taxonomy.** I had three states; they have five. The one I missed that matters most: *\"a raw moment was captured but not published yet.\"* That's the actual frame on #1714's screenshot — the user is being told by Cola itself that the raw capture happened and \"background reflection\" must run. This is a *first-class* confusion that I rolled into \"silence.\" It's not. It's \"I did do a thing, but I told you about a different thing and now you can't see either.\"\n\n2. **The agent-honesty axis.** They flagged that the main agent overstates `awareness_update` as if it wrote a 心迹, when it only appended to a draft. I treated this as a pipeline/UX question; they correctly identified it as a *prompt-design* failure that runs in parallel to the pipeline. The screenshot for #1714 is exactly this: the agent gives a half-explanation of the system instead of either telling the truth (\"I appended a draft; whether anything ships tonight depends on tonight's reflection\") or acknowledging it can't see the state. That's a fix in `awareness_update`'s tool guidelines and the main agent's `awarenessSurfaceBlock`, not in the pipeline.\n\n3. **\"Read model\" is the right shape.** I proposed a `pipelineRuns` map glued onto `index.json`. They proposed a single status read model that both the renderer *and* the agent can query — last successful pipeline, pending raw moments, last failure, today's outcome. That's the better abstraction: it gives the agent a tool to *answer* \"why no 心迹 today?\" instead of guessing or making it up. Without that, even with my UI surface, the conversational answer would still be hallucinated.\n\n4. **Feedback-bundle inclusion.** This is a real one I missed. My #1721 investigation hit a wall because the feedback zip has no `index.json` and no note bodies. Adding awareness state to feedback packages is a small change that pays for itself the next time a quality complaint lands.\n\n## Where I think they're wrong or thin\n\n1. **They lump #1714 into \"old-version pipeline failure plus bad expectation management.\"** The expectation-management piece is right; the version claim isn't. The `eager_input_streaming` errors *were* the old-version bug fixed in 0.7.2, but the `reasoning_content` 400s are dated **2026-04-30 and 2026-05-04** — both after 0.7.4 shipped. This is a *current* deterministic failure on DeepSeek `fast`-tier models, not legacy noise. Misclassifying it means their \"retry transient failures\" path is the wrong tool.\n\n2. **\"Retry transient maintenance failures\" conflates two failure classes.** `Connection error.` is transient — retry helps. `400 reasoning_content must be passed back` is a provider-contract violation — retry will fail identically every time and waste budget. The fix shape differs: transient → retry with backoff; deterministic → pin/fall-back/file-upstream. Their approach 1 wording would let the deterministic case keep burning autonomous budget every night for users on DeepSeek.\n\n3. **They don't address the model-tier reliability gap at all.** Pure UX surface tells the DeepSeek user \"we tried 7 nights in a row and failed\" — better than silence, but doesn't actually deliver them a note. Their approach is necessary but not sufficient for #1714. The pinning piece I proposed (or, equivalently, classifying the awareness pipeline as needing an Anthropic-schema model) is what actually closes the user's loop.\n\n4. **Stage 1 / Stage 3 evidence asymmetry isn't in their analysis.** For #1720's catch-up, Stage 1 (full chronicle) said yes, Stage 3 (style sample) said no entry. They diagnosed Stage 3 as \"correctly returned no entry\" and stopped. I think it's worth one more layer: if Stage 1 voted yes specifically to gate Opus runtime, but Stage 3 vetoes anyway based on a thinner view, the gate did no work that day. This is small but worth a look — at minimum, when verdict=yes the chronicle (or the digest) should reach Stage 3, otherwise we paid for the Haiku gate run for nothing.\n\n## Synthesized recommendation\n\nTheir Approach 2 is the right backbone, with three pieces of mine bolted on:\n\n1. **Awareness status read model** (their core idea). One source of truth, queryable by both renderer and agent. Replaces `index.json` ad-hoc fields with: per-day pipeline outcome (`skipped_no_activity` | `ran_no_entry` | `failed_<reason>` | `published`), last successful run timestamp, pending draft count, last failure summary. Renderer shows it as low-key annotations in Imprints; agent gets a `awareness_status_read` tool (or pre-injection in the surface block) so it can answer truthfully.\n\n2. **Tool-guideline + surface-block honesty fix.** `awareness_update` description should be unambiguous that it writes a *draft*, and the main-agent `awarenessSurfaceBlock` should remind the agent that it can't author finished notes on demand and should defer to \"tonight's reflection\" rather than narrate the system. Tiny prompt change, big trust win.\n\n3. **Failure classification, then act per class.** Transient (`Connection error.`, 5xx, `terminated` from sleep) → retry with backoff inside the cron's catch-up window. Deterministic provider-contract (`reasoning_content`, `eager_input_streaming`) → pin awareness-pipeline agents to Anthropic-schema models regardless of user's `fast/default/sota` mapping. File the pi-ai upstream issue but don't block on it.\n\n4. **Stage 1 / Stage 3 alignment.** Pass the episode digest contents (or a richer chronicle) into Stage 3 when the gate voted yes. Eliminates the \"gate did no work\" case and makes #1720-style catch-up runs cheaper to debug.\n\n5. **Feedback bundle includes awareness state** — `index.json` + most-recent N note bodies + last 7 days of `[memory-cron]` + `[awareness-delivery:metric]` lines. Future quality complaints become evaluable.\n\n**What's still out of scope:** the two-tier queue. We agree.\n\n**Net delta from my original recommendation:** I'm adopting their five-state framing and read-model abstraction, adding the agent-honesty prompt fix and feedback-bundle inclusion, and keeping the model-pinning + Stage 1/3 alignment that they didn't address. The combined patch is a bit larger than what I proposed alone, but it's still all observability + classification + a one-line model pin — no architectural rewrite, no two-tier queue, no product-feel change to \"scarcity is normal.\"","Based on our discussion, I've drafted a spec for this feature. Review it critically.\n\nFor each point:\n- If you agree: add technical suggestions, caveats, or risks worth flagging.\n- If you disagree: give reasons and a concrete alternative. If the issue is architectural rather than local, say so and propose the structural fix.\n\nWeigh technical merit and UX goals together. Challenge assumptions and propose alternatives whenever they would lead to a better outcome — don't default to politeness.\n\n\n---\n\nSpec written at `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-07-awareness-pipeline-observability-and-resilience.md`.\n\nStructure:\n- **Problem** — three issues mapped to the same underlying gap (silent failure modes indistinguishable from intentional silence).\n- **Product Decisions** — the standalone up-front section you asked for. Each of the four interview decisions plus the Stage 1/3 alignment, with chosen shape, two or three rejected alternatives per decision, and the reasoning. This is the section your engineering team can push back on without having to reconstruct the conversation.\n- **Evidence From The Reports** — concrete log evidence per issue, including the Stage 1/3 disagreement that surfaced during investigation.\n- **Current Architecture / Root Cause / UX Goal / Design Principles** — the gap analysis.\n- **Proposed Solution** — five components: status read model, Imprints footer, agent honesty (tool wording + surface block + new `awareness_status_read` tool + multi-day-failure proactive hint), Stage 1/3 alignment, provider failover with capability cache.\n- **Implementation Plan** — four phases, each independently shippable, with concrete file paths and tests.\n- **Data Model Changes** — new files (`status.json`, `capability-cache.json`), preserved invariants on `index.json`.\n- **Risks** — six risks with mitigations, including the privacy regression and the \"footer becomes a status board\" creep risk.\n- **Test Plan** — server / Electron / renderer / agent prompt eval / regression fixtures (one per investigated issue).\n- **Recommendation** — phase ordering and what's explicitly out of scope.\n\nTwo things I'd particularly flag for your engineering review:\n- **The pre-seeded fingerprint regex list** in §5.1 is the highest-friction point of the failover design. If pi-ai or the gateway changes its error wrapping, the regex stops matching and the system silently falls back to \"transient\" classification. Worth a server-side fingerprint update path eventually, but I marked it out of scope for v1.\n- **The `<system-context>` injection of `consecutiveFailureCount`** in §3.3 needs sticky-context signature integration to settle naturally when the streak resolves. I described the hash approach but didn't pin down the exact field name; engineers should confirm it doesn't collide with existing voice/work signature inputs in `sticky-context.ts`.","I have a personal comment on problem 3 as well, Largely, I think we should aim for a middle ground with the reviewers: something less poetic, but also not dull.\n\nI feel that it is probably wrong to explicitly say we are going to check this out after 9:30. That wording exposes the awareness as a pure background job or scheduled routine, which makes the feature feel less humane and less personal.\n\nTechnically, it is a background job, but that is not the product sense we are trying to convey to the user. You should probably adjust the wording here to avoid explicit timestamps that make it look like a hard-coded process rather than a personal, agentic reflection. You might want to put some more thought into that. and try to distinguish between different scenarios. What would be a personal note in different scenarios?\n\nFor example, when the pipeline runs successfully but there are no entries or errors, you probably want to make it a little bit banter or intimate to read. That's my thought.\n\nActually, I'm having another thought on the scenario where the agent judges that there is no entry today.\r\rIn the current prompt, we tell the agent that if there is nothing to reflect on, it should just output \"no entry today.\" What do you think if we instead asked the agent to output some kind of playful banter? It would need to respect the established voice, of course, but it could be a single sentence like, \"I found nothing interesting here,\" or even a funny comment on the task the user is working on (e.g., \"I don't want to say too much about the day; good luck with your job interview!\").\n\nThis probably poses a challenge in how we distinguish between a \"no entry\" scenario and a real reflection scenario, because right now the agent outputs a fixed string when no reflection is needed. However, I'm thinking we can probably use a similar pattern to the Haiku model:\n1. We ask the model to call a tool.\n2. We parse the tool response with a Boolean argument to see the agent's judgment.\n3. If there is a reflection, the model calls the tool and writes its reflection notes.\n4. Otherwise, it calls the tool with \"false\" and outputs one simple, very short sentence explaining that it has nothing to say today or adding a simple funny comment.\r\rWhat do you think about this? Are there any challenges or trade-offs that have not been considered? What do you think the pros and cons are?","this is the spec author response per your feeddback and my comment on the banter\n\n---\n\nReviewer feedback is largely valid. Going through point by point, then\n  addressing your footer/banter thinking, then updating the spec.\n\n  Per-point assessment\n\n  1. runs: Record<string, PipelineRunRecord> loses retry info. Valid. Real bug in\n  my schema. #1720 is exactly the case it can't represent. Adopting their\n  attempts[] + daily shape, with one refinement: consecutiveFailureCount should be\n   derived on read from daily (look at recent days' latestOutcome), not stored as\n  a primary field. Storing it invites drift between record state and counter\n  state.\n\n  2. Schema doesn't model \"captured but not published.\" Valid. I named this state\n  in the problem statement and dropped it from the schema. Adding\n  pendingDraftCount, lastDraftAt, and draftDates to DailyPipelineState. Also\n  surfacing it through awareness_status_read so the agent can answer\n  \"你刚刚记的那条呢?\" truthfully.\n\n  3. Footer copy implies a note exists. Partially valid. They're right that\n  \"上次反思\" reads as \"last note was on...\" and is wrong when the last successful\n  run returned no entry. But their replacement \"上次检查：2026-05-03\" is also\n  wrong — it makes the feature sound like a job ledger. Combining their truth\n  concern with your pushback below.\n\n  4. \"Pre-seeded cache\" terminology. Valid. Pre-seeding fingerprint regexes only\n  classifies failures faster; it doesn't prevent first failure. To prevent first\n  failure, we need pre-seeded runtime-identity entries. Adopting both: ship a\n  small set of known-bad (provider, baseUrlHost, modelId, capability) cache\n  entries in code so users on those resolved configurations skip straight to\n  fallback without paying a wasted DeepSeek call.\n\n  5. Failover scope under-specified. Valid and important. I conflated \"this\n  stage's model failed\" with \"this fire's provider is broken.\" Adopting their\n  runtime-identity + capability model. Cache entries key on {provider, apiCompat,\n  baseUrlHost, modelId, capability} not (agent, modelId). Within a fire, entering\n  \"safe mode\" only for stages whose resolved model shares the same risky family\n  (provider + apiCompat + baseUrlHost), not blanket-applying fallback to all\n  stages regardless of their tier.\n\n  6. Sticky-context alone doesn't guarantee once-per-streak. Valid. Compaction or\n  cadence re-injection would re-surface the hint. Adopting their dual-id pattern.\n  One refinement: a \"streak ID\" minted at the 0→1 failure transition (UUID) and\n  cleared on streak break. The agent's consumed state updates when the streak ID\n  is injected into a turn, regardless of whether the model actually surfaced it.\n  This costs us occasionally-missed hints in exchange for a bulletproof \"never\n  repeats\" guarantee. Acceptable.\n\n  7. Feedback bundle without note bodies doesn't solve quality complaints. Valid —\n   I overclaimed. The privacy boundary is right; the claim that #1721-style\n  complaints become debuggable was overstated. Adopting their targeted shape:\n  default bundle stays status-only; the reader UI gets a \"Report this 心迹\" action\n   that includes that one note's body after explicit confirmation. Optionally\n  surfaces neighboring metadata (motif, frame, dates) to give context without\n  dragging in adjacent personal content.\n\n  Smaller corrections — all valid:\n\n  - .last-reflection-date advances after gate-skip OR reflection-complete, not\n  \"per stage.\" Wording fix.\n  - The state count is six (or five if I group failures); my prose says \"five\"\n  then enumerates six. Fix.\n  - Phase 2 test wording is wrong — the regression test should check the agent's\n  user-facing reply, not the tool result string (which intentionally contains the\n  literal \"心迹\" so the agent reads it). Fix.\n  - awareness_status_read desktop-scope gating — clarify implementation: the tool\n  checks ctx.scopeKey === DESKTOP_SCOPE_KEY and returns a \"Imprints are\n  desktop-only\" sentinel from non-desktop scopes rather than hiding the tool\n  entirely.\n  - Status changes route through awareness:changed with reason 'pipeline_run' —\n  make this explicit.\n\n  Footer wording + the no-entry banter idea\n\n  You're pushing on something real. The reviewer's \"上次检查：2026-05-03 · 今晚\n  21:30 后再看看\" is technically truthful but reads like a cron status page. The\n  product feel of 心迹 depends on the surface sounding like Cola noticing, not\n  Cola scheduling.\n\n  The right move is what you sketched: scenario-varied warm copy with no explicit\n  timestamps, plus your banter idea integrated cleanly with the footer surface.\n\n  Footer copy by scenario\n\n  Five scenarios, each with intentionally informal phrasing. No clock times, no\n  job-status framing, but truthful about what state the day is in:\n\n  ┌───────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────┐\n  │     Scenario      │             zh-CN              │        en-US         │\n  ├───────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤\n  │ Recent successful │ 5/3 想起你的时候记下来了       │ Caught something on  │\n  │  note             │                                │ 5/3                  │\n  ├───────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤\n  │ Recent run, no    │                                │ Quiet couple of      │\n  │ entry (no banter  │ 这两天平静，没什么留下的       │ days; nothing stuck  │\n  │ available)        │                                │                      │\n  ├───────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤\n  │ Recent run, no    │                                │ 5/4 — \"<banter       │\n  │ entry (banter     │ 5/4「<banter sentence>」       │ sentence>\"           │\n  │ available)        │                                │                      │\n  ├───────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤\n  │                   │                                │ Jotted a draft;      │\n  │ Pending draft     │ 刚记了一条草稿，晚点再回头看看 │ tonight will see if  │\n  │ today             │                                │ it amounts to        │\n  │                   │                                │ anything             │\n  ├───────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤\n  │                   │                                │ Things haven't been  │\n  │ Multi-day failure │ 最近几次没跑顺，等再试一回     │ quite right — I'll   │\n  │                   │                                │ try again            │\n  ├───────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤\n  │ Fresh install     │ 还在认识你，慢慢来             │ Still getting to     │\n  │                   │                                │ know you             │\n  └───────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────┘\n\n  The \"晚点再回头看看\" / \"I'll try again\" wording stays warm without committing to\n   a specific clock time. We never say \"21:30.\"\n\n  The no-entry banter idea — yes, do this\n\n  Your sketch (tool with Boolean discriminant + brief comment when no-entry) is\n  the right shape. Here's how I'd make it concrete and the tradeoffs I'd flag:\n\n  Tool signature change. awareness_finalize_day becomes a discriminated union:\n\n  type AwarenessFinalizeDayInput =\n    | { date: string; hasReflection: true;  content: string }\n    | { date: string; hasReflection: false; briefSentence: string }\n\n  hasReflection: false records the day as ran_no_entry with briefSentence stored\n  on DailyPipelineState. The literal string [no entry today] exit goes away.\n\n  Stage 3 prompt addition. The current GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT ends with \"If\n  nothing today warrants an entry, respond with exactly: [no entry today].\"\n  Replaces with:\n\n  ▎ If nothing today warrants a published note, call awareness_finalize_day with\n  ▎ hasReflection: false and a briefSentence of one short line in the same voice\n  ▎ your [assistant] turns established today. The brief sentence is for your own\n  ▎ record and may be surfaced to the user as a small footer note in Imprints. It\n  ▎ can acknowledge the day's tenor (\"今天聊得淡淡的\"), name what the user is\n  ▎ occupied with (\"你今天在调那个 502，我先不打扰\"), or simply note that nothing\n  ▎ rose to the surface (\"没什么真留下的\"). Stay at one sentence. This is not a\n  ▎ note — do not try to write a polished reflection in shorter form.\n\n  Storage. briefSentence becomes a field on DailyPipelineState. It is not stored\n  in awareness/notes/ (those are published notes only) and not in\n  awareness/drafts/ (those are pre-reflection captures). It sits inside\n  status.json next to latestOutcome.\n\n  Display. The footer uses the brief sentence when the most recent ran_no_entry\n  day has one. The Imprints panel grid is unchanged — no card. The agent surfaces\n  the brief sentence only if asked directly via awareness_status_read.\n\n  Pros / cons / challenges of the banter idea\n\n  Pros\n  - Distinguishes \"Cola decided not to write today, with personality\" from \"system\n   silence.\" Your stated UX goal.\n  - The footer surface gets one piece of personalized text per non-empty no-entry\n  day, much warmer than generic copy.\n  - Lower performance pressure on Stage 3: the agent has a graceful exit that\n  still feels intentional. Today's [no entry today] literal feels like a system\n  token — most agents probably emit it slightly disappointed.\n  - Failover-aware: even on days with provider failures, once we recover, the\n  banter gives the user a real signal that \"Cola was here today.\"\n\n  Cons and challenges\n\n  1. Token cost on no-entry days. Today these are pure exits (8 output tokens).\n  With banter, ~30-50 tokens. Across users this is a meaningful baseline shift.\n  Mitigation: still cheap relative to a published note's 200-300 tokens; cap\n  briefSentence length at ~60 chars / 30 words in the tool schema and validate\n  server-side.\n  2. Voice drift / banter dilution. The risk you flagged: the agent leans into\n  banter on every day to feel productive, even when the day genuinely warranted\n  nothing. The sentence becomes performative. Mitigation: prompt example pairs\n  that include a \"just don't write anything beyond the bare honest\n  acknowledgement\" example, and a counter-example showing what not to do. We may\n  also want a short eval comparing banter quality across 30 historical days before\n   shipping.\n  3. The boundary between brief banter and a published note becomes fuzzier. A\n  really good briefSentence could feel like it should have been a note.\n  Mitigation: enforce one-sentence + character cap; display treatment in the\n  footer is intentionally small (single line, low contrast) so even a clever\n  sentence doesn't get the full Imprints card treatment.\n  4. Privacy: where does the banter live in feedback bundles? Same posture as\n  notes. Brief sentences are still personal — \"你今天在调那个 502\" reveals what\n  the user is doing. Default bundle excludes them; the targeted \"Report this 心迹\"\n   reader action could include them if the user opts in (but practically these\n  don't have a reader UI to opt from). Cleanest: briefSentence is treated as\n  note-equivalent for privacy purposes.\n  5. Migration: what happens to existing [no entry today] records? Currently\n  awareness/notes/YYYY-MM-DD.md files literally contain that string for skipped\n  days. After the change, no such file is written; the state lives in status.json.\n   The reconciliation pass already skips files whose body is [no entry today]. We\n  do need to make sure the new path doesn't write that literal anywhere on disk\n  going forward.\n  6. What you didn't explicitly raise: failure-day banter. A day where the\n  pipeline failed entirely is a different surface — Cola didn't get to look. We\n  should not generate banter for failed days; the footer's failure copy already\n  covers that case. Banter is hasReflection: false only, not failed_*.\n\n  My recommendation. Adopt the banter idea, ship it as part of Phase 2 (alongside\n  the agent honesty changes — they're closely related). The tool schema change is\n  small; the prompt change is bounded; the storage and display changes integrate\n  cleanly with the footer work.\n\n  The most important thing to get right is the prompt — example pairs and a hard\n  length cap. I'd budget time for an eval pass before shipping (compare against\n  20-30 historical low-activity days from internal traces).\n\n---\n\nthe spec is updated accordingly can you re-review, here are some notes from the update\n\nSpec updated end-to-end. Final structure: 21 top-level sections, ~1255 lines. Summary of changes I made in response to the review:\n\n**Schema rebuild (Point 1, 2):** Replaced the date-keyed `runs: Record<string, PipelineRunRecord>` with the reviewer's proposed shape — append-only `attempts[]` plus per-day `daily` aggregate plus `failureStreak` state. Added `pendingDraftCount`, `lastDraftAt`, and `briefSentence` to `DailyPipelineState` so the \"captured but not published\" state has a real home. `consecutiveFailureCount` is now derived on read, not stored.\n\n**Footer copy (Point 3 + your pushback):** Replaced the `21:30` timestamp wording with a six-scenario table (zh-CN + en-US) covering recent-note, recent-no-entry-with-brief, recent-no-entry-no-brief, pending-draft, multi-day-failure, fresh-install. No clock times anywhere. The Decision 1 alternatives section now explicitly records the rejected timestamp version.\n\n**Failover schema (Points 4, 5):** Cache keys on `(runtimeIdentity, capability)` not `(agent, modelId)`. Added `RuntimeIdentity = {provider, apiCompat, baseUrlHost, modelId}` and the `AwarenessCapability` enum. Per-fire propagation gates on same-family resolution. Pre-seeded the cache with one known-bad runtime identity (DeepSeek thinking-mode flash) since fingerprints alone don't prevent first failure — your terminology fix is right.\n\n**Streak consumption (Point 6):** Adopted the dual-id pattern. `failureStreak.streakId` mints fresh on 0→1 transition; `lastProactiveHintedStreakId` advances when the block is injected into any user turn, regardless of whether the model surfaced it. Robust against compaction.\n\n**Feedback bundle (Point 7):** Default bundle is status-only with `briefSentence` fields stripped on copy. New §7.2 specifies the \"Report this 心迹\" reader action for opt-in single-note quality reports. The recommendation section no longer overclaims quality debuggability.\n\n**No-entry banter (your idea, Decision 6):** New §6 added. Tool schema becomes a discriminated union; `awareness_finalize_day(hasReflection: false, briefSentence)` records to `DailyPipelineState`, never to `notes/`. Strong prompt with good/bad examples, ≤60-char/30-word cap enforced server-side, pre-ship eval gates the merge. Same privacy posture as note bodies (stripped from bundles, opt-in via reader action).\n\n**Smaller corrections:** `.last-reflection-date` wording fixed (line 164 + Data Model section). State count corrected to six. Phase 2 test wording fixed to assert against the assistant's user-facing reply, not the tool result string. `awareness_status_read` desktop-scope behavior specified (returns explicit stub from channel scopes). `awareness:changed` reason `'pipeline_run'` made explicit including the `awareness-watch.ts` path filter update.\n\nThree things worth flagging to your engineering team during review:\n\n1. **The pre-ship banter eval (§6.7) is a real gate.** If brief sentences read worse than the literal `[no entry today]` exit on internal traces, we either tighten the prompt or revert the banter portion of Phase 2. Worth doing this before merging Phase 2 even if it slips the timeline.\n\n2. **The pre-seeded cache list (§5.5) is small on purpose.** Only entries we have direct evidence for. As we get more failover telemetry from production, we can grow it — but not speculatively.\n\n3. **Schema version field is `1`.** Any future change to `AwarenessStatus` or `CapabilityCache` shape should bump this and either provide a migration helper or treat unknown versions as \"start fresh.\" I haven't documented the migration approach because v1 is the shipping shape; flagging it as a known omission.","updated it again, here are update notes\n\n---\n\nSpec is now ~1414 lines, structure intact. Final summary of the changes I made in response to this review:\n\n**Decision 3 stale (point 1):** Rewrote the chosen-shape paragraph in Decision 3 to match §5 — capability cache keys on `(RuntimeIdentity, AwarenessCapability)` with a separate per-fire `brokenFamilies` set. The five sub-decisions now describe persistent cache + family scope explicitly, no more `(user, model, agent, fingerprint)` references.\n\n**Field semantics (point 2):** `RuntimeIdentity` now uses `{providerId, api, compat?, baseUrlHost?, modelId}` matching `server/agent/model-resolve.ts:62-68`. Added an explicit semantics table at the top of §5.1 distinguishing \"exact identity equality\" from \"family equality\" (the latter ignoring `modelId`).\n\n**Family propagation has data structure (point 3):** Split persistent `CapabilityCache` (exact-key, ~7d, `~/.cola/awareness/capability-cache.json`) from in-memory `FireBrokenFamilies` (family-key, scoped to one cron fire, discarded after). New §5.4 specifies the family key shape and the `shouldFailover` lookup that consults both. Added the new file `awareness-fire-broken-families.ts` to the implementation plan.\n\n**TTL anchor (point 4):** Seed materialization now uses first-read time, not build time. Added `source: 'observed' | 'seed'` and `seedVersion` fields to `CapabilityCacheEntry` so cache inspection can distinguish the two.\n\n**Pending draft watermark (point 5):** Added `draftConsumedThrough` and `lastFinalizedAt` to `DailyPipelineState`. Rewrote the draft-state-lifecycle subsection — `awareness_update` now writes status directly through the same lock, and the watermark also fixes the latent bug where a late-night draft after Stage 3 could be ambiguously consumed.\n\n**Banter optionality (point 6):** `briefSentence` is now optional in the discriminated union. `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` instructs the agent to provide one \"only when natural.\" The Decision 6 alternatives section records the rejected \"required banter\" alternative with the filler-risk reasoning. Added a quality-eval target band (30-50% omission) so the omission rate is monitored post-launch.\n\n**Glance-safety rule (point 7):** Added an explicit hard rule in §6.3 covering names, sensitive workplace specifics, health/legal/financial/relationship details, and probing questions. Replaced the bad `Quiet day on this end. You okay?` example with a neutral one. Added a glance-safety violation example bank for unambiguity.\n\n**Brief-sentence report path (point 8):** Documented as a known v1 gap in §6.5 with explicit reasoning for why we don't add a footer-clickable surface in v1, plus the two workarounds users have (generic feedback or wait for the brief to roll off).\n\n**Stale wording fixes:**\n- Intro now says \"six decisions\"\n- Decision 1 now says \"six scenarios\"\n- Design Principle 5 now says \"known-bad runtime identities and known fingerprints\"\n- #1721 closure wording updated to distinguish audit-debug (default bundle) from text-quality debug (targeted reader action)\n- `awareness_status_read` registration unified — register globally, scope-aware response in the tool body\n- Test plan grew with regression tests for each of the new mechanisms (build-time-TTL regression, source-field check, FireBrokenFamilies key shape, between-fire isolation, late-capture watermark)\n- Fixture A reworked to reflect the actual learn-by-failure accumulation behavior; new Fixture A2 documents the seeded-entry path\n\nThree things worth flagging to your engineering team during this round of review:\n\n1. **The persistent-cache + fire-broken-families split is the load-bearing change.** The two structures look similar but encode different intents — exact-identity persistent learning vs same-fire family safety. Engineers should not collapse them back into one structure during implementation; the bug they prevent is real.\n\n2. **The draft watermark approach changes the write contract for `awareness_update`.** It now writes to `status.json` through `runSerializedByKey`. Worth confirming the lock contention is in fact rare in practice — if many users have rapid-fire `awareness_update` calls (which the prompt discourages but doesn't prevent), the lock could become a bottleneck. Failure mode is benign (writes serialize) but worth instrumenting.\n\n3. **Fixture A's \"first-fire pays a wasted-call tax for unfamiliar identities\" tradeoff is honest but worth explicit product confirmation.** A user on DeepSeek with the seed entry pre-loaded still pays one wasted call per resolved family member that isn't the seeded one. We can shrink this with broader pre-seeding (less conservative seed list) or wider family matching (drop more fields from the family key), but both moves are opinionated. The current tradeoff is \"precise seeding + accumulation\" — if PMs prefer \"fewer wasted calls at the cost of broader implicit override,\" that's a knob to discuss before implementation.","ok the spec is updated and we can move to the technical design part, here is my implementation plan, any comments or suggested improvements?\n\n---\n\n<plan>\n# Plan — Awareness Pipeline Observability and Model Resilience\n\n## Context\n\nWe are implementing the spec at\n`docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-07-awareness-pipeline-observability-and-resilience.md`\n(authored after three review rounds).\n\nThe motivating problem: three GitHub feedback issues (#1714, #1720, #1721) all\nsurface as \"心迹无更新,\" but they are three different things — a real DeepSeek\nprovider-contract bug, a working-but-invisible no-entry case, and an\nunauditable quality complaint. Today every failure mode and every silent-but-\ncorrect outcome look identical to the user, the agent has no read model so it\nhallucinates explanations, and feedback bundles ship neither pipeline state\nnor a path for users to opt into note bodies.\n\nOutcome: pipeline failures stop being indistinguishable from intentional\nsilence, the agent stops claiming things it cannot claim, deterministic\nprovider failures stop trapping users in multi-day silent outages, no-entry\ndays carry a warm in-voice artifact, and quality complaints become debuggable\nwhen the user opts in.\n\nScope: **all four phases land in the same PR**, broken into ten focused\ncommits along the spec's Phase 1 → Phase 4 ordering. Each commit leaves the\nbuild green and tests passing. We follow TDD with **vertical slices** — one\ntest → one implementation step — never write all tests first.\n\n---\n\n## Critical files (touched in this PR)\n\n### Server (new)\n\n- `server/agent/awareness-status.ts` — `AwarenessStatus`, `PipelineRunAttempt`,\n  `DailyPipelineState`, `FailureStreakState`. Read/write via `runSerializedByKey`\n  on `~/.cola/awareness/status.json`. Mirrors `awareness-index.ts` lock pattern\n  (`writeAwarenessIndex` at `awareness-index.ts:99-111`).\n- `server/agent/awareness-runtime-identity.ts` — `RuntimeIdentity`, the\n  `AwarenessCapability` type, `AWARENESS_CAPABILITY_MATRIX`,\n  `resolveRuntimeIdentity(modelId)`. Field semantics from\n  `model-resolve.ts:62-68` and `buildModelFromListItem` (lines 56-92).\n- `server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.ts` — `classifyFailure`,\n  `KNOWN_FINGERPRINTS` regex registry.\n- `server/agent/awareness-capability-cache.ts` — exact-key persistent cache\n  (`~/.cola/awareness/capability-cache.json`) with first-read-time TTL seed\n  materialization.\n- `server/agent/awareness-fire-broken-families.ts` — in-memory per-fire family\n  set (created at the top of each cron fire, discarded when the fire ends).\n- `server/agent/awareness-failure-streak-context.ts` — system-context\n  contributor mirroring the active-work pattern\n  (`active-work-injection.ts:89-134`). Dual-id consumption\n  (`streakId` vs `lastProactiveHintedStreakId`).\n\n### Server (modified)\n\n- `server/cron/memory-cron.ts` — write status records at every termination\n  point (lines 350, 404, 419, 464, 467); add `<today-episode>` to Stage 3\n  task (around the existing Stage 3 task construction); call\n  `shouldFailover()` before each spawn; populate `runtimeUsed` /\n  `failoverFrom` on attempts.\n- `server/agent/tools/awareness.ts` — `awareness_update` description, result\n  text, and `promptGuidelines` per spec §3.1.\n- `server/agent/tools/reflection.ts` — `awareness_finalize_day` discriminated\n  union per §6.1; server-side length validation; route `briefSentence` into\n  `DailyPipelineState`.\n- `server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts` (new) — `awareness_status_read`\n  tool. Globally registered; `ctx.sessionKey !== DESKTOP_SCOPE_KEY` returns\n  the desktop-only stub. Wire into `tools/index.ts:47-66` next to\n  `createAwarenessUpdateTool`.\n- `server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts` — extend `awarenessSurfaceBlock` (lines\n  1027-1059) per §3.2 / §3.3; update `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` (lines 775-875)\n  to add `<today-episode>` description and the no-entry banter rules\n  including the glance-safety bank.\n- `server/agent/index.ts` — wire `buildAwarenessFailureStreakContext` into\n  the `<system-context>` parallel build at lines 928-943.\n\n### Electron / shared / renderer\n\n- `electron/awareness-watch.ts` — extend the path filter at line 48 to\n  include `status.json`.\n- `electron/handlers/feedback-package.ts` — add `awareness/index.json`,\n  `awareness/status.json` (with `briefSentence` redacted on copy),\n  `awareness/capability-cache.json`; add bundle README. Mirror the\n  `collectSupportStateEntries` pattern (lines 126-141).\n- `electron/handlers/awareness-status.ts` (new) — IPC handler for\n  `awareness:listStatus`. Wire registration alongside other awareness\n  handlers.\n- `shared/protocol.ts` — add `'pipeline_run'` to the `AwarenessChangedEvent`\n  reason union (lines 189-191); add the `awareness:listStatus` IPC contract.\n- `src/components/ImprintsPanel.tsx` — add the dim footer below the grid\n  (after line 64); compute scenario per §2; consume `awareness:listStatus`.\n- `src/components/imprints-footer/` (new) — small isolated component plus\n  zh-CN / en-US copy bundle.\n- Imprints reader action — add \"Report this 心迹\" entry on the\n  reader's action menu (locate during implementation; the existing reader\n  component is `src/components/imprints/...`).\n\n### Tests (new)\n\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-status.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-capability-cache.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-fire-broken-families.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-runtime-identity.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-failure-streak-context.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/tools/awareness-finalize-day.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/cron/memory-cron-status.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/cron/memory-cron-failover.test.ts`\n- `tests/electron/awareness-status-bundle.test.ts`\n- `tests/electron/awareness-watch.test.ts` (extend existing)\n- `tests/renderer/imprints-footer.test.ts`\n\n---\n\n## TDD approach (applies to every commit)\n\nPer `~/.claude/skills/tdd/skill.md` and `docs/testing.md`:\n\n- **Vertical slices.** For each behavior in a commit's \"behaviors\" list:\n  RED (write the test) → GREEN (minimum code) → next behavior. Never write\n  all tests first.\n- **Stub backlogs with `test.todo`** so the remaining slices are visible in\n  `vitest` output as we work.\n- **Mock at boundaries** — Pi SDK `spawnSubAgent` factory, file-system\n  config-getter overrides via `(globalThis as any).__TEST_*` injection,\n  `vi.useFakeTimers()` for cron timing. Keep registries, queues, archive\n  reconciliation, status-file readers, and prompt-block assemblers real.\n- **`vi.waitFor` always with assertions inside** (per `docs/testing.md:46-54`).\n  `vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync` whenever testing debounce or cron timers —\n  the sync variant skips microtasks.\n- **Semantic assertions, not exact strings.** Tool result text and prompt\n  blocks evolve; assert on content presence (`toContain`,\n  `toMatch(/draft|草稿/)`) and structural ordering. Tool description /\n  `promptGuidelines` exact wording is not a test target (see\n  `docs/testing.md:128-131`).\n- **Existing test cleanup is part of the work** — if a memory-cron test\n  asserts on the pre-status-file shape, update it in the same commit.\n\nPer `docs/agent/prompting-guide.md`:\n\n- New prompt rules use **positive framing** wherever possible (e.g.,\n  \"When responding after `awareness_update`, frame the result as a draft\" —\n  not \"never claim you wrote a 心迹\").\n- Examples wrapped in `<example type=\"good\">` / `<example type=\"avoid\">`.\n- The glance-safety bad-example bank in `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` keeps the\n  good→bad ordering and matches existing prompt-block style.\n- One source of truth per behavior: `awareness_update` wording lives in\n  the tool result text (the moment-of-action surface). The\n  `awarenessSurfaceBlock` rule cross-references that posture but does not\n  duplicate the canonical phrasing.\n- Dial back aggressive language for Opus 4.6 — no \"MUST,\" \"ALWAYS,\"\n  \"NEVER\" except for the glance-safety hard rules and the\n  do-not-mention-after-injection consumption rule.\n\n---\n\n## Commit-by-commit plan\n\nEach commit is its own RED-GREEN-REFACTOR loop. Commit at the end of each\nsection once tests pass and `pnpm exec tsc -p server/tsconfig.json --noEmit`\nis clean.\n\n### Commit 1 — Status read model (data layer, no cron wiring)\n\nGoal: `awareness-status.ts` lands as a pure, locked read/write data layer\nthat the rest of the PR will build on. No behavior changes for users yet.\n\nBehaviors to test (vertical slices):\n1. Write-then-read roundtrip preserves shape across restart.\n2. Two writes in flight serialize through `runSerializedByKey` on the\n   `status.json` path (atomic temp-file-rename like\n   `awareness-index.ts:104-106`).\n3. `daily[date]` overwrites the latest aggregate while `attempts[]` keeps\n   both attempts (Fixture D regression).\n4. `attempts[]` retention prunes >90d on write.\n5. `daily` retention prunes >60d on write.\n6. `consecutiveFailureCount`, `lastSuccessfulDate`, `lastFailureDate`\n   compute correctly from `daily` across mixed outcome types.\n7. `failureStreak.streakId` mints on 0→1 transition; persists across\n   consecutive failures; clears on streak break; mints fresh on next streak.\n\nFiles: `server/agent/awareness-status.ts`,\n`tests/server/agent/awareness-status.test.ts`.\n\n### Commit 2 — Wire memory-cron + draft watermark consistency boundary\n\nGoal: every cron termination point and every `awareness_update` tool call\nwrites through `awareness-status.ts`. Draft append and status update sit\ninside one `runSerializedByKey` critical section per §1's \"Consistency\nboundary\" rule. The cron does not yet route around failures (Phase 3) nor\nemit brief sentences (Phase 2's banter); status records are populated for\nthe existing outcome types only.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. Successful Stage 1 → Stage 2 → Stage 3 fire writes one `attempts[]` entry\n   and updates `daily[targetDate]` to `published` (or whatever the existing\n   pipeline produces).\n2. Stage 1 failure writes a `failed_transient` (or `failed_provider_contract`\n   if classified — initially everything is transient until commit 8) attempt\n   and stops the fire.\n3. Stage 3 returning the legacy `[no entry today]` writes `ran_no_entry` and\n   leaves `briefSentence` undefined (the discriminated union arrives in\n   commit 5).\n4. Same-date failure-then-success preserves both attempts in `attempts[]`\n   and updates `daily.latestOutcome` to the success (Fixture D).\n5. `failureStreak` advances correctly across two consecutive failed fires\n   and clears on the next success.\n6. `awareness_update` appends the draft section and updates\n   `daily.lastDraftAt` / `pendingDraftCount` under one shared lock; if the\n   status write fails after the draft append, the next read recomputes\n   `pendingDraftCount` from disk (recovery rule).\n\nFiles: `server/cron/memory-cron.ts`,\n`server/agent/tools/awareness.ts` (draft append integration),\n`tests/server/cron/memory-cron-status.test.ts`,\nextend `tests/server/agent/tools/awareness.test.ts` (or its equivalent).\n\nTests use the temp-dir + `globalThis.__TEST_COLA_DIR` pattern from\n`memory-cron.test.ts:33-65` and stub `spawnSubAgent` to drive scripted\nterminal callbacks.\n\n### Commit 3 — IPC + watcher + Imprints footer\n\nGoal: the renderer can read pipeline status and surface a single dim line\nunder the grid. Five of the six §2 scenarios are reachable; Scenario 3\n(brief sentence) lights up later in commit 5.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. `awareness:listStatus({ days })` IPC returns `daily` desc by date and\n   `failureStreak`.\n2. `awareness-watch.ts` path filter includes `status.json`; mutations\n   broadcast `awareness:changed` with `reason: 'pipeline_run'`.\n3. Renderer footer scenario selection picks the correct scenario for each\n   of the five Phase-1-reachable cases (multi-day failure, pending draft,\n   no-entry without brief, recent successful note, fresh install).\n4. zh-CN and en-US copy bundles ship and locale switch updates the line.\n5. Footer truncates to a single line at 1× / 2× panel widths (visual\n   smoke test, simple length check).\n\nFiles: `electron/awareness-watch.ts`,\n`electron/handlers/awareness-status.ts` (new IPC handler),\n`shared/protocol.ts`,\n`src/components/ImprintsPanel.tsx`,\n`src/components/imprints-footer/*` (new),\n`tests/electron/awareness-watch.test.ts` (extend),\n`tests/renderer/imprints-footer.test.ts` (new).\n\n**Commit checkpoint after this** — the user already gets a working\nobservability win even before Phase 2 ships.\n\n### Commit 4 — Stage 1 / Stage 3 alignment (`<today-episode>`)\n\nGoal: pass the day's full episode digest into Stage 3 alongside the\nexisting style sample. `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` documents the new block.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. When `awareness/episodes/{today}.md` exists, the Stage 3 task input\n   contains a `<today-episode>` block with the file's contents.\n2. Missing episode file falls back to `<today-episode>\\n(empty)\\n</today-episode>`\n   — Stage 3 still runs.\n3. `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` describes both `<today-episode>` (content\n   source) and `<today-style-sample>` (voice source) — structural\n   assertion (block present, ordering preserved), not exact wording.\n\nFiles: `server/cron/memory-cron.ts`,\n`server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts`,\nextend `tests/server/cron/memory-cron-status.test.ts` (or a sibling) to\nassert on the assembled task string captured from the `spawnSubAgent` mock.\n\n### Commit 5 — No-entry banter (discriminated `awareness_finalize_day`)\n\nGoal: replace the literal `[no entry today]` exit with the discriminated\nunion per §6.1. `briefSentence` is optional; the prompt gates it on\nnaturalness and the glance-safety rule. The renderer's Scenario 3 can now\nfire.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. `awareness_finalize_day({ hasReflection: true, content })` publishes a\n   note and clears any prior `briefSentence` (existing behavior, regressed).\n2. `awareness_finalize_day({ hasReflection: false })` (no payload) writes\n   no file under `notes/`, sets `daily.latestOutcome = 'ran_no_entry'`,\n   leaves `briefSentence` undefined.\n3. `awareness_finalize_day({ hasReflection: false, briefSentence })` of\n   acceptable length writes `briefSentence` to `DailyPipelineState`.\n4. `briefSentence` over the length cap returns an error to the agent;\n   no status mutation occurs (the agent retries shorter or omits).\n5. `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` updates carry the §6.3 banter rules\n   including the glance-safety good/bad bank — structural assertion only.\n6. Renderer Scenario 3 lights up when `briefSentence` is set on the most\n   recent no-entry day; falls through to Scenario 4 when absent.\n\nFiles: `server/agent/tools/reflection.ts`,\n`server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts`,\n`server/cron/memory-cron.ts` (legacy `[no entry today]` path is removed\nfrom cron-side parsing once the tool emits `ran_no_entry` directly),\n`tests/server/agent/tools/awareness-finalize-day.test.ts` (new),\nextend `tests/renderer/imprints-footer.test.ts` for Scenario 3.\n\nMigration note: existing `awareness/notes/{date}.md` files containing the\nliteral `[no entry today]` string remain on disk and continue to be\nskipped by `awareness-archive.ts:87-97` reconciliation — this commit\ndoes not retroactively populate `briefSentence` for past days. Existing\ntests that asserted on the legacy `[no entry today]` exit shape are\nupdated in this commit (test maintenance per `docs/testing.md:15`).\n\n### Commit 6 — Agent honesty (tool wording + `awareness_status_read` + surface block)\n\nGoal: the agent has truthful state to report when asked, and the\n`awareness_update` user-facing acknowledgement frames its result as a\ndraft.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. `awareness_update` tool result text contains \"draft\" / \"草稿\" wording\n   that teaches the agent how to acknowledge to the user.\n   `promptGuidelines` carry the framing rule. Assert structural presence,\n   not exact wording.\n2. `awareness_status_read({ date })` returns the day's\n   `DailyPipelineState` plus the aggregate triple\n   (`lastSuccessfulDate`, `consecutiveFailureCount`,\n   `pendingDraftCountToday`).\n3. `awareness_status_read` invoked from a non-desktop scope returns the\n   string `'Imprints are only available in the desktop app.'` —\n   single global registration with scope-aware response, not conditional\n   registration.\n4. `awarenessSurfaceBlock` extension is present in the assembled main\n   prompt — block-presence test, not full text match.\n5. Tool registration is wired through\n   `server/agent/tools/index.ts:47-66` next to `createAwarenessUpdateTool`.\n\nFiles: `server/agent/tools/awareness.ts`,\n`server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts` (new),\n`server/agent/tools/index.ts`,\n`server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts`,\n`tests/server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.test.ts` (new),\nextend `tests/server/agent/tools/awareness.test.ts` (or equivalent).\n\nThe agent prompt-eval items in spec test plan §\"Agent prompt eval\" 1-7\nare ack'd in this commit but full eval execution is a manual checkpoint\ndescribed under \"Verification\" below — they do not gate the unit tests.\n\n### Commit 7 — Multi-day failure-streak proactive hint injection\n\nGoal: when `consecutiveFailureCount >= 2` and the streak's hint hasn't\nbeen injected yet, the next user turn includes a\n`<awareness-failure-streak>` block in `<system-context>`. Once per\nstreak. Robust to compaction.\n\nBehaviors (mirror `active-work-injection.ts:89-134` pattern):\n1. Fresh streak with `consecutiveFailureCount === 1` → no injection.\n2. `consecutiveFailureCount >= 2` and\n   `failureStreak.streakId !== failureStreak.lastProactiveHintedStreakId`\n   → block included; `lastProactiveHintedStreakId` advances to\n   `streakId` regardless of whether the model used it.\n3. Same streak, second turn → block omitted.\n4. Streak resolved (any non-failure outcome) → `streakId` cleared; no\n   block.\n5. New streak after a clean day → fresh `streakId`, fresh injection.\n6. Compaction during a streak does NOT cause re-injection (the dual-id\n   check blocks it even though `state.forceNext = true` is set by\n   `markActiveWorkCompactionHappened`-style flag).\n\nFiles: `server/agent/awareness-failure-streak-context.ts` (new),\n`server/agent/index.ts` (wire into the parallel build at lines 928-943),\n`server/agent/awareness-status.ts` (the\n`lastProactiveHintedStreakId` write helper, if not already present from\nCommit 1),\n`tests/server/agent/awareness-failure-streak-context.test.ts` (new).\n\n**Commit checkpoint after this** — Phase 2 is complete. Pre-ship banter\nquality eval (spec §6.7) runs as a manual gate before merging the PR;\nfindings either tighten the prompt or trigger a follow-up commit. We\ndon't block this commit on the eval since the schema and behavior are\ntestable here.\n\n### Commit 8 — Failure classifier + runtime identity helpers\n\nGoal: pure-function building blocks for Phase 3, so commit 9's cache and\ncommit 10's wiring can stand on tested primitives.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. `classifyFailure` returns `provider_contract` with the right capability\n   for the DeepSeek `reasoning_content` 400; same for the\n   `eager_input_streaming` 400.\n2. Realistic transient errors (`Connection error.`, 5xx, `terminated`,\n   `Host resumed after sleep`) classify as `transient`.\n3. Unknown 4xx classifies as `unknown` (treated as transient downstream).\n4. `resolveRuntimeIdentity(modelId)` produces the five-field\n   `RuntimeIdentity` for cached-model-list entries; SDK built-ins return\n   `baseUrlHost: undefined`.\n5. Family equality predicate ignores `modelId`; exact equality compares\n   all five fields.\n\nFiles: `server/agent/awareness-runtime-identity.ts` (new),\n`server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.ts` (new),\n`tests/server/agent/awareness-runtime-identity.test.ts` (new),\n`tests/server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.test.ts` (new).\n\n### Commit 9 — Persistent capability cache (with seed)\n\nGoal: `~/.cola/awareness/capability-cache.json` with exact-key lookup,\nfirst-read-time TTL, and pre-seeded known-bad runtime identities.\n\nBehaviors:\n1. Write/read roundtrip; serialized through `runSerializedByKey`.\n2. Exact-key lookup on `(RuntimeIdentity, capability)` hits non-expired\n   entries, misses expired entries.\n3. Seed materialization on first read sets `expiresAt = now + 7d` (NOT\n   build-time). Regression test: install older build → seed entry valid\n   for 7d.\n4. `source` field correctly distinguishes `'seed'` from `'observed'`;\n   `seedVersion` is set on seed entries only.\n5. Repeated read does not re-materialize seeds whose key already exists.\n\nFiles: `server/agent/awareness-capability-cache.ts` (new),\n`tests/server/agent/awareness-capability-cache.test.ts` (new).\n\n### Commit 10 — Per-fire FireBrokenFamilies + cron failover wiring + bundle + reader action\n\nGoal: this single commit closes Phase 3 (failover wiring) and Phase 4\n(feedback bundle + targeted reader action). The two are bundled here\nbecause failover changes the cron's per-attempt write shape\n(`runtimeUsed`, `failoverFrom`), and the bundle additions need both that\nshape and `capability-cache.json` available — landing them together\nmeans we never ship a half-state.\n\nBehaviors (failover):\n1. `FireBrokenFamilies` `add` / `has` work on the family key shape\n   (without `modelId`).\n2. Memory-cron Stage 1 fails on a known fingerprint → persistent cache\n   entry written (exact key) AND fire `brokenFamilies` populated (family\n   key) → Stage 1 respawns with `SAFE_FALLBACK[stage]` → succeeds →\n   `attempts[]` has two entries with `runtimeUsed` set on each;\n   `failoverFrom` set on the success attempt only;\n   `daily.latestOutcome === 'published'` (per the §1 outcome-precedence\n   rules — failover that succeeds does not show as\n   `failed_provider_contract`).\n3. Per-fire family propagation: Stage 1 fails on `deepseek-v4-flash`,\n   Stage 2 resolves to `deepseek-v4-pro` (same family) → persistent cache\n   misses (different `modelId`) but `brokenFamilies.has` returns true →\n   Stage 2 uses fallback. Stage 3 same.\n4. Per-fire NON-propagation: Stage 1 fails on DeepSeek, Stage 2 resolves\n   to an Anthropic model on a different family → both lookups miss →\n   Stage 2 runs on the user's tier.\n5. Per-fire state isolation: between fires, `FireBrokenFamilies` is\n   fresh; only the persistent cache carries over.\n6. Persistent cache hit on Stage 1's first lookup → user's tier model is\n   never spawned for that stage (Fixture A2's seed-prevented case).\n7. Second-failure handling: fallback failure records `failed_*` outcome,\n   no further fallback attempted; `daily.latestOutcome` follows the §1\n   precedence rules.\n8. Transient failure: no cache write, no fallback (regression).\n\nBehaviors (feedback bundle + reader action):\n9. Default bundle includes `awareness/index.json`, `awareness/status.json`,\n   `awareness/capability-cache.json` when present.\n10. `briefSentence` fields are stripped from each `DailyPipelineState`\n    in the bundled `status.json`.\n11. Default bundle never includes files matching `awareness/notes/*.md`\n    or `awareness/drafts/*.md` (regression — comment block in\n    `feedback-package.ts` documents the privacy posture).\n12. Bundle README at the bundle root lists what's included and what's\n    not.\n13. \"Report this 心迹\" reader action menu item appears only when a\n    published note is open in the reader.\n14. Confirmation dialog explains scope (\"This will include this note's\n    body. Other notes are not included.\"). On confirm, the standard\n    feedback dialog opens with `awareness/reported-note.md` and the\n    day's full (un-redacted) `DailyPipelineState`.\n15. Cancel does not attach the note.\n\nFiles: `server/agent/awareness-fire-broken-families.ts` (new),\n`server/cron/memory-cron.ts` (failover wiring + per-attempt\n`runtimeUsed`/`failoverFrom`),\n`electron/handlers/feedback-package.ts`,\n`src/components/imprints/...` (reader action — exact path to be located\nat implementation time),\n`tests/server/cron/memory-cron-failover.test.ts` (new),\n`tests/server/agent/awareness-fire-broken-families.test.ts` (new),\n`tests/electron/awareness-status-bundle.test.ts` (new),\nplus a thin renderer test for the reader-action menu wiring.\n\nThis commit is the largest by surface area; if during implementation it\nproves to be too coarse (e.g., the bundle work and the reader action\ndiverge in shape), it splits cleanly along the failover/bundle/reader-\naction axis.\n\n---\n\n## Verification (end-to-end, before opening the PR)\n\n1. **Server typecheck** — `pnpm exec tsc -p server/tsconfig.json --noEmit`\n   passes. (The root tsconfig does not cover the standalone server, so this\n   is the canonical typecheck per `docs/testing.md`.)\n2. **Vitest** — full suite passes (`pnpm test`); changed-files variant\n   (`vitest