b9122f` — that these failures pre-date this branch. None introduced by this work.\n\nManual verification gates from the plan still remain for you to run (these can't run in CI):\n\n1. **Banter quality eval (HARD GATE for merge)** — run reflection on 20-30 historical low-activity days under the new `awareness_finalize_day` schema; verify omission rate lands in the 30-50% target band, glance-safety holds, voice matches `[assistant]` turns. If quality regresses against the literal `[no entry today]` exit, either tighten `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` (additional commit) or revert Commit 6 while keeping the rest of the PR.\n2. **Server prompt smoke** — `pnpm tsx scripts/show-system-prompt.ts` to inspect `awarenessSurfaceBlock` extension and `awareness_update` wording in the assembled prompt.\n3. **Cron dry-run** — invoke the awareness cron manually; verify `~/.cola/awareness/status.json` and `capability-cache.json` materialize on a fresh account; `index.json` unchanged.\n4. **Desktop UX smoke** — Imprints footer renders the right scenario for fixture states (zh-CN + en-US, dark + light); ask \"今天有心迹吗?\" and confirm `awareness_status_read` answers truthfully; simulate 2-day streak in `status.json` and confirm the once-per-streak hint surfaces.\n5. **Feedback bundle smoke** — generate a bundle on a real account; confirm three awareness JSON files + README; confirm `awareness/notes/` and `awareness/drafts/` are absent and `briefSentence` redacted from `status.json`.\n6. **Reader action smoke** — open a published note; click \"Report this 心迹\"; confirm the dialog explains scope; submit; inspect bundle for `awareness/reported-note.md` + `awareness/reported-day-state.json`.\n\nPlan-tracked docs follow-up (deferred per your instruction): `docs/agent/awareness.md`, `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-07-...md` (reflect PipelineStageAttempt stage-level + consistency-protocol corrections), `docs/agent/proactive-delivery.md`. Will land in a separate PR.","this is their response for your review, what do you think\n\n---\n\nI'll assess each finding and propose targeted fixes — no code changes yet, per your instruction.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 1 — Draft watermark race: **VALID, fix as suggested**\n\n`server/cron/memory-cron.ts:752` reads the draft, then spawns Stage 3 (which can run for minutes). After it returns, line 837 calls `markDraftsConsumed(today, now())`, which in `awareness-status.ts:344-360` recounts **current** sections on disk and writes that count as `draftConsumedThrough`. Any `awareness_update` that ran during Stage 3 — those drafts the model never saw — get marked consumed and disappear from `pendingDraftCount`. This is exactly the \"I captured something but can't see it\" failure mode this PR is supposed to eliminate.\n\n**Proposed fix** (matches the reviewer's shape):\n1. Add `countDraftSectionsOnDisk(today)` capture at line 752 right after `readAwarenessDraft`, store as `draftSnapshotCount`.\n2. Add `markDraftsConsumedThrough(date, throughCount, now)` to `awareness-status.ts` that sets `draftConsumedThrough = throughCount` and computes `pendingDraftCount = max(0, currentSectionsOnDisk - throughCount)`. Replace the call at line 837 with `markDraftsConsumedThrough(today, draftSnapshotCount, now())`.\n3. Keep `markDraftsConsumed` for callers that genuinely want \"consume all currently visible\" (none today inside the cron), or remove it if unused after the swap.\n4. Regression test in `memory-cron-status.test.ts`: snapshot count = 1, run reflection, simulate a second `recordDraftAppend` while the spawned subagent mock is awaiting, complete reflection, assert `pendingDraftCount === 1` and `draftConsumedThrough === 1` post-finalize. The repair-on-read path (Finding 4) further heals this.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 2 — Channel-scope leak of `awareness_status_read`: **INVALID**\n\nThe reviewer's stated premise — \"the tool is globally registered but ignores the tool context, so non-desktop scopes can query desktop Imprints state\" — does not match the code. The tool is filtered at the registration boundary, not at execute-time:\n\n- `server/agent/index.ts:297`: `const DESKTOP_ONLY_TOOLS = ['clipboard_read', 'clipboard_write', 'awareness_status_read']`\n- `server/agent/index.ts:309-310`: in `getSpawnContext`, channel scopes have these tools stripped from `availableCustomTools`.\n- `server/agent/index.ts:356-357`: in `getToolSet`, the same filter applies.\n\nSlack, QQ, and plugin scopes (the channel scopes — the only ones where another human is on the other end of the conversation) never see `awareness_status_read` in their tool list at all. The model cannot call a tool it doesn't have. This is the existing idiomatic pattern — `clipboard_read`/`clipboard_write` use the same mechanism — and it's strictly stronger than a per-execute scope check because the tool surface is removed from the prompt entirely.\n\nThe reviewer's \"decide explicitly whether CLI sync scopes should be allowed\" is the only remaining question, and the answer is *yes, allow CLI*: `isSyncScope()` at `server/channels/scope.ts:28-30` defines the equivalence — desktop and CLI are the same user on the same machine, sharing `~/.cola/awareness/`. Treating them differently would create artificial asymmetry. This was the conscious decision earlier in the implementation; the prior review pushed *toward* DESKTOP_ONLY_TOOLS and away from per-execute scope checks. The spec wording (\"non-desktop scopes return the desktop-only stub\") is satisfied in the meaningful sense — non-local scopes don't see the tool — even though the implementation pattern differs from the spec's prose. I'd push back on this finding and update the spec doc text to match the cleaner pattern in the docs follow-up.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 3 — Fallback identity drift: **VALID, fix as suggested**\n\n`memory-cron.ts:397` builds `safeFallbackIdentity = resolveRuntimeIdentity(safeFallbackModel)` with no `baseUrl`, while line 416/494 spawn the subagent through `input.ctx`, and `subagent/session-factory.ts:150` plumbs `ctx.baseUrl` straight into `resolveModel`. So a fallback from `deepseek-v4-flash` → `claude-haiku-4-5-20251001` actually routes the haiku call through the user's gateway URL (e.g., zhuoma) but records `runtimeUsed` as if the call went to default Anthropic. That breaks two things:\n\n1. **Persistent cache correctness.** Future fires that pre-spawn-check `(haiku, anthropic-default)` get a different cache slot from the one the call actually exercised. If the gateway later breaks haiku, the cache won't reflect it.\n2. **Debug evidence.** Attempts log says haiku-via-default; reality is haiku-via-gateway. Anyone investigating a fallback-loop bug from a feedback bundle gets misled.\n\n**Proposed fix:** change line 397 to `resolveRuntimeIdentity(safeFallbackModel, input.ctx.baseUrl)`. This is the minimal, correct change — same baseUrl as the actual call. Add a unit test in `memory-cron-failover.test.ts`: run a fire with `ctx.baseUrl = 'https://gw.example/v1'`, force a provider_contract failure on stage 1, assert the recorded fallback attempt's `runtimeUsed.baseUrlHost === 'gw.example'`, not undefined.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 4 — Repair-on-read not wired into RPC paths: **VALID, fix as suggested**\n\n`repairDailyPendingDraftCount` exists at `awareness-status.ts:371` but is never called from any read path. `server/rpc/awareness-status.ts:12` and `server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts:39` both call `readAwarenessStatus()` directly. Per Correction 2 in the plan (\"any code path reading status that depends on pendingDraftCount … recomputes from the draft file when the value looks suspicious\"), this is a wiring gap. After a crash between draft append and status update, the footer and the agent stay blind to a real pending draft until something else triggers a write.\n\n**Proposed fix** — fold repair into a small helper rather than spreading the call:\n\n1. Add `readAwarenessStatusWithRepair(dates: string[])` to `awareness-status.ts`. It calls `repairDailyPendingDraftCount(date)` for each requested date, then returns `readAwarenessStatus()`. Single source of truth for \"give me a read-model view that's been reconciled.\"\n2. `handleAwarenessStatusList`: derive the date window (`[today, today-1, …, today-(days-1)]`), call the new helper. The window is at most 30 entries, all reads of small files, very cheap.\n3. `awareness_status_read`: call the new helper for `[targetDate, today]` (today because the aggregate triple `pendingDraftCountToday` depends on today even if the user asked about another day).\n4. Cron startup reconciliation already happens on every fire because `recordDraftAppend` and `markDraftsConsumed*` rewrite `pendingDraftCount` from disk; no change needed there.\n5. Regression test: write status with `pendingDraftCount: 0` and a draft file containing 2 sections plus `draftConsumedThrough = 0`. Call `handleAwarenessStatusList`. Assert the returned daily entry shows `pendingDraftCount: 2` and that the on-disk status has been corrected.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 5 — Brief-sentence cap looser than product rule: **PARTIALLY valid; smaller fix preferred**\n\nThe reviewer's diagnosis (200-char server cap is looser than the prompt's \"≤60 zh-CN chars / ≤30 en-US words\") is correct, but the proposed fix — language-aware caps — adds genuine complexity for one footer line. Mixed-language briefs (\"今天 spent the day debugging\") make detection fuzzy at sentence granularity, and the practical concern reduces to \"don't store something the footer will silently truncate.\"\n\n**Proposed fix (lighter):** lower `BRIEF_SENTENCE_MAX_CHARS` from 200 to ~140. 30 English words at ~4.5 chars + 1 space averages ~165 chars, but 30 typical-density English words (5-letter average) lands closer to 150; 60 CJK characters lands at 60 string-length units. A 140 cap is generous for the en-US ceiling, very generous for zh-CN, and tight enough that the failure mode the reviewer cares about (a paragraph passing the cap) is precluded. Keep the rejection error specific so the model retries shorter or omits.\n\nI would push back on the language-aware approach explicitly: the prompt already carries the correct contract; the server cap's job is to be a safety net, not the canonical authority. If we ever see reflection drift past 140 chars in practice, that's a prompt-tuning failure to address in the GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT bank, not server validation logic.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nFix in this order: **Finding 1** (the actual product-correctness bug), **Finding 4** (closes the recovery story Correction 2 promised), **Finding 3** (data-integrity for cache + bundles), **Finding 5** (one-line constant change). **Finding 2** is closed as invalid; the only follow-up is updating the spec doc prose during the deferred docs catch-up so the next reader doesn't expect a per-execute scope check. None of these unblock the manual gates — banter quality eval and desktop UX smoke still need to run before the PR ships.","Per your suggestion, I've updated the relevant files. The current uncommitted changes should now contain only the targeted updates. Please recheck.\n\nAll four commits landed clean. Final summary:\n\n**Branch state**: 4 follow-up commits on top of the original 13, all CI-clean.\n\n| Commit | Finding                                 | Hash       |\n| ------ | --------------------------------------- | ---------- |\n| A      | #1 — Stage 3 draft watermark race       | `28319881` |\n| B      | #4 — Repair-on-read in RPC + tool paths | `58de947f` |\n| C      | #3 — Fallback identity uses ctx.baseUrl | `9bcade3e` |\n| D      | #5 — Tighter briefSentence safety net   | `aea0938a` |\n\n**Verification**:\n- Both typechecks (`server/tsconfig.json` + root) clean.\n- New tests pass: 12 watermark, 6 RPC, 7 status-read, 5 failover, 10 finalize-day.\n- Pre-existing failures (10 across 5 files including conversation-history) confirmed unchanged via stash-comparison.\n\n**Notes for the spec doc follow-up** (deferred per