ave a good understanding of the production vision","read the spec and mentioned relevant documents to have a good understanding of the production vision","read the spec and mentioned relevant documents to have a good understanding of the production vision","read the spec and mentioned relevant documents to have a good understanding of the production vision","read the spec and mentioned relevant documents to have a good understanding of the production vision","can you open my chrome","read the spec and mentioned relevant documents to have a good understanding of the product vision","Deep dive into Cola's agent module — the execution core that owns sessions, prompt construction, subagent orchestration, work tracking, memory, and the tool surface.\n\n## Phase 1: Read the Docs\n\nThree docs build the mental model every agent-layer task needs. Read them in order.\n\n1. `docs/agent/README.md` — Session model, MODs, skills, memory, tools, cron, prompt queue, announce buffering. This is the map of the entire agent layer.\n2. `docs/agent/subagents.md` — Multi-turn child sessions with interactive control (idle state, session_send/wait/close), agent definitions, lifecycle, context inheritance, announce delivery and batching. Subagent delegation is the primary orchestration primitive.\n3. `docs/agent/memory.md` — Memory system map: global memory storage and write paths, voice overlay, awareness, nightly three-stage authoring pipeline, tools, read-on-demand vs inherited-inline design.\n\n### Invariants To Keep In Mind\n\nThese are the load-bearing behaviors that shape any code change in the agent layer. You don't need the deep-dive docs to respect them — the detail docs live in Phase 3 and are read when the task requires them.\n\n- **Main agent's system prompt is static.** Runtime-varying context (memory, work state, voice, reminders, caring notes) rides in message-side `<system-context>`, never the system prompt. Adding dynamic content to the static prompt invalidates cache on every turn. Subagents are short-lived and inherit memory inline instead.\n- **Compaction is automatic and cache-preserving.** Don't pre-optimize the session by truncating history or skipping messages — the summarizer handles it and manual truncation will break cache. L1 stacks new \"eras\" without rewriting old ones; L2 merges when the user is idle.\n- **Delegate large reads to subagents.** Image inspection, bulk file scans, and verbose commands belong in child sessions via `session_spawn`, returning textual summaries. Keeping the main session's context lean is the agent's responsibility, enforced through prompt rules.\n- **Single-flight per scope.** One prompt runs at a time per scope. Additional user input goes through the prompt queue with `steer` / `followUp` / `collect` modes.\n- **Post-turn sequence drains in a fixed order:** deferred session updates → prompt queue → announce flush → awareness delivery → compaction check → cron drain → idle timer restart. New post-turn hooks land in this sequence.\n\nWhen to go deeper: `docs/agent/prompt-system.md` for block architecture, `docs/agent/prompt-flow.md` for message lifecycle, `docs/agent/context-management.md` for compaction and cache behavior. All three are Phase 3 — read when your work requires them.\n\nFor an intuitive sense of the assembled prompt, browse `data.local/system-prompt-*.md` — generated snapshots of the main agent and all ten subagent prompts, refreshed by `scripts/show-system-prompt.ts`.\n\n\n\nNow that you have a good understanding of our core primitives, let's deep dive into our proactive systems, specifically our awareness system.\n\nIn this session, we are mostly going to be analyzing two user reports relevant to the awareness system, so it is essential that we understand its current state in good detail.\n\n## Proactive Systems\n\nEverything Cola does without being asked, plus the plumbing that gets background results to the user.\n\n- **Proactive behavior map**: Read `docs/agent/proactive-scheduling.md` — caring, user-created crons, awareness delivery, internal maintenance crons; TTS suppression for non-user prompts.\n- **Delivery mechanics**: Read `docs/agent/proactive-delivery.md` — shared gate primitives (structured skip reasons, delivery mutex, soft-timer arm/fire-gate split, conversational quiet threshold), awareness delivery state machine (`pending | in_flight | delivered | unannounced | expired`), single-note newest-first selection, teaser via `PromptDecoration`, deterministic jitter for maintenance crons. Key files: `server/agent/awareness-delivery.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-index.ts`, `server/cron/internal-maintenance-jitter.ts`.\n- **Awareness**: Read `docs/agent/awareness.md` — reflective note authoring (instant `awareness_update` drafts + nightly publication), archive reconciliation, pipeline observability and model resilience (status read model, failover, failure-streak hint), and the relationship to memory. For the reader UI and motif rotation, see `docs/agent/imprints-reader.md`. Key files: `server/agent/tools/awareness.ts`, `server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-archive.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-index.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-status.ts`, `server/cron/memory-cron.ts`, `electron/awareness-notes.ts`.\n- **Caring**: Read `docs/agent/caring.md` — idle-triggered subagent; notes (injected into next user message as `<system-context>`, not proactively delivered) vs reminders (one-shot crons via standard cron scheduler). Key dir: `server/agent/caring/`.\n- **Cron scheduling**: Read `docs/agent/cron.md` — global vs MOD sources, scheduling model, pause/resume/expiry, `catchUp` policy + checkpoint, isolated root-session execution with one-per-cronKey guard, direct announce delivery. Key files: `server/cron/cron-scheduler.ts`, `server/cron/cron-store.ts`.\n- **Autonomous guardrails**: Read `docs/agent/autonomous-guardrails.md` when touching Caring/internal maintenance budget caps, runtime timeouts, sleep-drift aborts, side-effect tool loop detection, or purpose-aware cache policy.\n\n## After Onboarding\n\nReport back when you have a thorough understanding of the agent module. Then you're ready for implementation tasks.","Deep dive into Cola's agent module — the execution core that owns sessions,\n  prompt construction, subagent orchestration, work tracking, memory, and the\n  tool surface.\n\n  ## Phase 1: Read the Docs\n\n  Three docs build the mental model every agent-layer task needs. Read them in\n   order.\n\n  1. `docs/agent/README.md` — Session model, MODs, skills, memory, tools,\n  cron, prompt queue, announce buffering. This is the map of the entire agent\n  layer.\n  2. `docs/agent/subagents.md` — Multi-turn child sessions with interactive\n  control (idle state, session_send/wait/close), agent definitions, lifecycle,\n   context inheritance, announce delivery and batching. Subagent delegation is\n   the primary orchestration primitive.\n  3. `docs/agent/memory.md` — Memory system map: global memory storage and\n  write paths, voice overlay, awareness, nightly three-stage authoring\n  pipeline, tools, read-on-demand vs inherited-inline design.\n\n  ### Invariants To Keep In Mind\n\n  These are the load-bearing behaviors that shape any code change in the agent\n   layer. You don't need the deep-dive docs to respect them — the detail docs\n  live in Phase 3 and are read when the task requires them.\n\n  - **Main agent's system prompt is static.** Runtime-varying context (memory,\n   work state, voice, reminders, caring notes) rides in message-side\n  `<system-context>`, never the system prompt. Adding dynamic content to the\n  static prompt invalidates cache on every turn. Subagents are short-lived and\n   inherit memory inline instead.\n  - **Compaction is automatic and cache-preserving.** Don't pre-optimize the\n  session by truncating history or skipping messages — the summarizer handles\n  it and manual truncation will break cache. L1 stacks new \"eras\" wit