bservability and model resilience (status read\n  model, failover, failure-streak hint), and the relationship to memory. For\n  the reader UI and motif rotation, see `docs/agent/imprints-reader.md`. Key\n  files: `server/agent/tools/awareness.ts`,\n  `server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts`,\n  `server/agent/awareness-archive.ts`, `server/agent/awareness-index.ts`,\n  `server/agent/awareness-status.ts`, `server/cron/memory-cron.ts`,\n  `electron/awareness-notes.ts`.\n  - **Caring**: Read `docs/agent/caring.md` — idle-triggered subagent; notes\n  (injected into next user message as `<system-context>`, not proactively\n  delivered) vs reminders (one-shot crons via standard cron scheduler). Key\n  dir: `server/agent/caring/`.\n  - **Cron scheduling**: Read `docs/agent/cron.md` — global vs MOD sources,\n  scheduling model, pause/resume/expiry, `catchUp` policy + checkpoint,\n  isolated root-session execution with one-per-cronKey guard, direct announce\n  delivery. Key files: `server/cron/cron-scheduler.ts`,\n  `server/cron/cron-store.ts`.\n  - **Autonomous guardrails**: Read `docs/agent/autonomous-guardrails.md` when\n   touching Caring/internal maintenance budget caps, runtime timeouts,\n  sleep-drift aborts, side-effect tool loop detection, or purpose-aware cache\n  policy.","# iTELL Platform Onboarding\n\nWe are building a multi-tenant LMS platform in Next.js 16 and TypeScript. This onboarding has two real tiers: must-read material that builds the mental model, and on-demand material grouped by theme.\n\n\n## Phase 1: Read the Docs\n\nRead these in order. Each builds on the prior; together they cover the multi-tenant access model, the action layer, and the content boundary.\n\n1. `docs/README.md` — Platform layers, route groups (route group as authorization tier), route surface map. The mental model of where things live.\n2. `docs/organization.md` — Tenancy boundary, roles, teams, the invitation flow with identity-aware acceptance and per-learner volume scope. The most behavior-rich doc; central to both portal and access work.\n3. `docs/volumes.md` — Organization-volume binding as the platform's primary key. Why binding ID (not CMS slug) is the addressing scheme; how generation/import lifecycles end at the same shape.\n4. `docs/auth.md` — Better Auth as the org/team/invitation engine; how the platform composes hooks, additionalFields, and gates without owning auth itself.\n5. `docs/action.md` — The five-level action middleware chain (auth → org → orgAdmin / orgOwner / volume + parallel platformAdmin); what context each layer adds; the volume-access policy shared with route handlers.\n\n\n### Key Invariants\n\nLoad-bearing rules that shape any non-trivial change. These are the project-wide mental model, not subsystem details — sub-feature rules live with the relevant Phase 3 entry.\n\n- **Organization is both the tenant boundary and the billing unit.** Access, invitations, settings, deletion, and Stripe state all key off the org. One Stripe customer = one org; an org has at most one active subscription. Don't introduce primitives that try to scope below or above this boundary.\n- **`organizationVolumeId` is the platform key for org-scoped saved reading state** — not slug, not `cmsDocumentId`. Progress, activity, completion, lesson time, and dashboards all key off this binding ID. The binding row is the join point between tenancy, access, generation, and reading analytics; that's why it must stay first-class and stable.\n- **Route groups are authorization tiers**, not just layout containers. `(admin)` enforces admin/owner before nested pages render; `(owner)` is owner-only; the lesson group enforces team membership for non-admins; `/scorm/*` sits outside the tree because of iframe constraints. Adding a new page means picking the right group, not just the right URL.\n- **Content flows as a pipeline: Payload → remark plugins → custom directives → React.** Payload owns lesson content (source of truth); the platform fetches via 