ocs/billing/README.md` for the seat model and Stripe lifecycle. Read `docs/billing/stripe-integration.md` only when touching Stripe SDK calls, webhooks, or checkout. Read `docs/billing/internal-plan.md` when working on `/admin/organizations` or platform-admin bypass behavior. Code: `src/features/billing/`, `src/app/(portal)/org/[orgSlug]/(owner)/billing/`, `src/app/admin/`. **Sub-rule**: seat count and volume access are independent axes. A learner consumes one seat regardless of how many volumes they can open; the `members.role = \"member\"` projection drives billing, while `team_members` drives access. Code that assumes \"seat → all-volumes auto-sync\" is pre-decoupling — check the doc, not the older callsite.\n\n## After Onboarding\n\nReport back with a super concise understanding of the critical modules when you finish phase 1 and ready for specific tasks.","I'm trying to onboard myself in an AI-powered project scheduling app. I'm mainly focused on the agent part and the evaluation system. \n\nI've come up with several docs that would serve as pointers and get you started in understanding. You can read them and maybe explore some of the critical source files to make sure you have a good understanding of the current state.\n\nstart from application/docs/agents/README.md and the sibling docs, then explore the critical pieces in paralle, I am not asking you to see every bit of code","# iTELL Platform Onboarding\n\nWe are building a multi-tenant LMS platform in Next.js 16 and TypeScript. This onboarding has two real tiers: must-read material that builds the mental model, and on-demand material grouped by theme.\n\n## How To Follow this\n\n- **Read Phase 1 fully** before touching code. The invariants are non-negotiable — older code may contradict them, and pattern-matching from older code without seeing the invariants will produce wrong work.\n- **Execute Phase 2 in parallel.** Three agents, each with a specific extraction question. Each must report back the requested