---\n\nI have enough surface area to give a thorough review. Pulling the threads together.\n\n---\n\n## Review: `codex/goal-2`\n\nThe two themes both hit their stopping conditions: 40-test suite is green, the live AI seam reaches `AppRootView`, and a logged session demonstrably shifts the weekly review's training numbers. The work is **substantively correct** and a real step from \"structurally complete\" to \"useful.\" The issues below are mostly real but bounded — none invalidate the architecture.\n\n---\n\n### Critical\n\n**C1. BGTask handler is registered after launch finishes — iOS likely won't invoke it.**\n- Where: `AppRootView.swift:35-48` calls `BackgroundRefreshCoordinator.shared.registerIfNeeded { ... }` from a SwiftUI `.task` modifier on `ContentView`.\n- Why this matters: Apple's docs require `BGTaskScheduler.shared.register(forTaskWithIdentifier:using:launchHandler:)` to be called *before* `application(_:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:)` returns. SwiftUI's `.task` runs after the first render — well after launch. Behavior is iOS-version-dependent (older iOS terminates the app with \"All launch handlers must be registered before application finishes launching\"; newer iOS just silently fails to invoke the handler).\n- ADR-0008 claims the BGTask now actually runs the daily coach service. With this registration timing it almost certainly doesn't, in practice.\n- Concrete fix: register in the `App` struct's `init()` (or via `UIApplicationDelegateAdaptor`). Move just `BGTaskScheduler.shared.register(...)` to launch-time; keep the daily handler injection lazy via a stored closure that the `App.init` registers a thunk around. Sketch:\n  ```swift\n  @main struct HealthCoachApp: App {\n      init() { BackgroundRefreshCoordinator.shared.registerLaunchHandler() }\n      ...\n  }\n  ```\n  And split `registerIfNeeded` into `registerLaunchHandler()` (idempotent BG register, called at launch) + `setDailyHandler(_:)` (called from `.task` once the model context exists).\n\n---\n\n### Moderate\n\n**M1. PhotosPicker returns HEIC; the analyzer hardcodes `image/jpeg`.**\n- Where: `LiveCoachAIClient.swift:48-58` (`analyze`), used by `FoodLoggingView.swift:43-53` and `RegisteredMealCalibrationView.swift:115-123`.\n- Why: iPhone camera default since iOS 11 is HEIC. `PhotosPicker(... loadTransferable(type: Data.self))` returns the original asset bytes. The Anthropic Messages API accepts only `image/jpeg | png | gif | webp` — HEIC is rejected with an opaque 400. Theme A's \"real-world flow\" path will fail on the most common photo source.\n- Theme A handoff acknowledges this (\"If PhotosPicker produces non-JPEG data in practice, add lightweight media-type detection\") — leaving it open in a user-facing path is a moderate gap, not minor.\n- Concrete fix: prefer `loadTransferable(type: Image.self)` and re-encode to JPEG, OR keep `Data` + sniff: check the first bytes (`ftypheic`/`ftypheix` prefix → re-encode through `UIImage(data:).jpegData(compressionQuality: 0.85)`; PNG signature → pass `image/png`; default JPEG). Centralize as a helper since both views need it.\n\n**M2. Main-compound performance-drop signal pools different lifts into one mean.**\n- Where: `TrainingReadinessAggregator.swift:85-112` (`hasMainCompoundPerformanceDrop`).\n- Why: `previous = baseline avg of weight*reps across squat+bench+row+ohp+deadlift entries pooled`, then compared against `recentWeeks[i].max()`. Different lifts have wildly different absolute weight×reps (a deadlift entry dominates a squat entry in the pool). Result:\n  - False positive: if user only logs squat in the recent week (lower weight×reps than deadlift baseline), the signal fires with no actual regression.\n  - False negative: if bench drops 10% but deadlift sets a PR, pooling masks it.\n- Severity moderate because this is one of two confirming signals for a critical deload Anomaly — a noisy signal here can either trigger a false deload recommendation or hide a real one. Spec §4.5 reads as per-compound regression.\n- Concrete fix: group `logs` by `exerciseName.lowercased()`, compute baseline-mean and weekly-max *per exercise*, then check `anyExercise.allWeeks(best ≤ baseline*0.95)`. Same data, different aggregation. ADR-0014 should be amended to reflect \"per-exercise comparison; signal fires if any single main compound drops ≥5% across both weeks.\"\n\n**M3. Sets-per-session counted as a single `hardSets` integer per `ExerciseLogModel`.**\n- Where: `TrainingLogService.swift:23-40` writes one log row per \"Log Exercise\" tap with `hardSets` as an Int. `weeklySummary` sums `hardSets` over all logs for the week. `mainCompoundPerformanceDrop` treats `weight × reps` per row as a performance score.\n- Why this matters: if the user logs the same exercise three times in one session (3 separate \"Log Exercise\" presses), volume sums correctly (good) but performance comparison double-counts. If they log it once with `hardSets=3`, the performance score is `weight*reps` of one set — without information about which set. Spec §4.4 expects sets and reps as the granular unit.\n- Severity moderate: works for v1 but the \"log three sets at once\" UX choice silently distorts the per-set comparison the deload signal needs. Either (a) commit to \"one ExerciseLog row per hard set\" with `hardSets=1` always (UX: log each set separately; matches every other lifter app), or (b) keep the current shape but use `weight × reps × hardSets` as the performance score for drop detection. (b) is the cheaper fix.\n\n**M4. 21:00 daily notification fires regardless of whether a fresh push exists.**\n- Where: `CoachNotificationScheduler.swift:21-32` schedules a `UNCalendarNotificationTrigger` with hardcoded body \"Daily plan is ready.\"\n- Why: With M1's BG registration likely silently failing, with no API key set, or any HTTP error, no `DailyPushLogModel` is written. The 21:00 system notification still fires claiming a plan is ready. User opens to yesterday's data with no indication anything is wrong. Existed before goal 2 but goal 2 made it more visible by introducing the missing-key state as a normal first-run condition.\n- Concrete fix (cheap): drop the calendar trigger; have the BG handler (or a Run Coach success path) post a one-shot `UNTimeIntervalNotificationTrigger` with body referencing the actual response (e.g., \"Tomorrow: Push — technique focus\"). Falls back silently when no log was generated, matches HealthGPT-style \"post after data\" pattern.\n\n**M5. `WeeklyReviewService` overrides only two of the six `weekSummary` fields with deterministic data.**\n- Where: `WeeklyReviewEngine.swift:101-103` — `trainingCompletionRate` and `totalVolumeByMuscle` are overwritten with `TrainingReadinessAggregator.weeklySummary`. The other four (`avgProteinG`, `proteinComplianceRate`, `weightChangeKG`, `avgRestingHR`, `avgHRV`, `sleepTimingRegularitySDMin`) stay as whatever the LLM produced.\n- Why: with the mock client they're hardcoded fictions (e.g., `avgRestingHR: latest()...`); with the live client they're whatever Claude infers. The spec lists these as numeric facts the system computes from data, not as model judgment. The current state means the JSON shipped to the user is half-deterministic / half-LLM.\n- Concrete fix: extend `weeklySummary` aggregator to compute all six summary numbers from the `MealEntryModel` / `DailySummaryModel` / `WorkoutSessionModel` data already available, and override the LLM payload across the board. Keeps the LLM in charge of `wins/concerns/longHorizonCheck/nextWeekAdjustments` (judgment) but pins the numbers (facts).\n\n---\n\n### Minor\n\n**m1. `APIKeySettingsView` has no read-back, no clear/replace, no \"key is set\" state.**\n- Where: `Settings/APIKeySettingsView.swift`.\n- After save, `apiKey = \"\"`. There's no indicator that a key already exists in Keychain. Users can't tell whether they need to paste again. Fix: read on appear via `provider.apiKey()`, show \"Key currently stored (last 4: …xyz)\" or just a checkmark; add a \"Clear key\" button that calls a new `provider.deleteApiKey()`. Adding `func deleteApiKey() throws` to the protocol is ~5 lines.\n\n**m2. `LiveAnthropicClient` calls Keychain synchronously from inside `complete()`.**\n- Where: `AnthropicClient.swift:60-61`. `apiKey()` blocks on `SecItemCopyMatching` from the calling actor (typically `@MainActor` since `CoachRunCoordinator` is). Keychain calls are usually fast but can block briefly. Not a real bug — flag for awareness; could move to first-line caching: read once per `LiveAnthropicClient` lifetime.\n\n**m3. `runDailyCoachNow` re-runs `model.load()` and `DailySummarySync.sync()` on every tap.**\n- Where: `ContentView.swift:129-143`. Dashboard `.task` already did this. Refresh-before-coach is reasonable but the user sees a 30-day HK fetch latency between tap and any error appearing. Not breaking. Could short-circuit if last load was <1 minute ago.\n\n**m4. `MockKeyProvider.saveApiKey` validates but doesn't store.**\n- Where: `ApiKeyProvider.swift:42-45`. Future tests that exercise the save→read flow will silently fail. Either make `MockKeyProvider` a class with `var storedKey` mutated by `saveApiKey`, or document. Cosmetic now; trap later.\n\n**m5. `DailySummarySync.sync` clobbers existing values with nil when a metric is absent on a day.**\n- Where: `DailySummarySync.swift:26-32`. If yesterday's row had `hrvSDNN = 47` and today's HK fetch returns no HRV sample for yesterday (unlikely but possible after the observer hardening lands), the row's HRV gets set to nil. Currently safe because each fetch is the source of truth for the 30-day window. Worth a one-line \"// last-fetch-wins\" comment when observer-based delivery lands.\n\n**m6. `mainCompounds` Set is private to the aggregator and uses lowercased exercise names that must match the seed library exactly.**\n- Where: `TrainingReadinessAggregator.swift:125`. Adding \"Sumo Deadlift\" or \"Front Squat\" to the library wouldn't qualify them as main compounds. This is a \"known small risk of drift\" — link the canonical set to a tag on `ExerciseSeed` (`isMainCompound: Bool`) so the source of truth is the library, not a parallel Set. Not load-bearing yet.\n\n**m7. Population SD vs sample SD in SWC computation.**\n- Where: `DailySummarySync.swift:69` and `TrainingReadinessAggregator.swift:74`. Both divide by `n` not `n-1`. For n≥7 the bias is <8%; for the 28-day case it's <2%. Not worth changing now, but worth a one-line note in ADR-0013 acknowledging the choice.\n\n---\n\n### Did it solve the intended problem?\n\n**Theme A: largely yes.** The seam is correct, tests prove the missing-key path doesn't persist a log, and the Settings → Run Coach loop is the right shape for a real key. The two real obstacles to \"tap a real key in the simulator and the daily push works end-to-end\" are M1 (HEIC photos) for the food path and C1 (BG handler timing) for unattended runs. Both are mechanical fixes.\n\n**Theme B: yes for the data plumbing, partly for the signal logic.** The pipeline lights up — a logged session changes the next weekly review's numbers, all five deload signals exist and are tested, SWC is computed with a documented window. The signal-extraction quality has two real flaws (M2, M3) that will distort live judgments once the user actually logs sessions. Catch them now while the signal logic is a single small file rather than after data accumulates.\n\n**Recommended order:** C1, M1 immediately (block the live merge); M2, M3, M5 before goal 3 starts (signal correctness now is cheaper than after 4 weeks of skewed data); M4 whenever; minor items as drive-bys.\n\n---\n\nOne comment from me is that you should probably first break down your uncommitted changes into a couple of focused commits. Then, on top of that, implement your fixes as a few more follow-up commits."],"019e0b07-18eb-71e3-a438-602b5414df3c":["i noticed that one of the commands takes more time than usual, we only have some boileraplaes, is anything wrong?"],"019e0b10-cde3-7e61-89d9-13b8fe592e28":["/goal \n\n## Objective\n\nImplement Phases 0 through 3 of HealthCoach per `docs/spec-v1.md §8`. End state:\n\n- Builds with `xbuild` and runs on the iPhone 17 simulator.\n- HealthKit permission flow works; the wrapper reads the seven core sample types (HRV-SDNN, RHR, sleep, active energy, steps, body mass, workouts) and the dashboard shows the last 30 days of each.\n- Daily 21:00 push fires with structured JSON per `§6.4`, using mocked Claude API calls (real key is post-run — see \"API key\" below).\n- Tier 2 photo food logging works end-to-end. Tier 1 calibration wizard UI is built but not exercised (kitchen scale arrives later).\n- Sunday 20:00 weekly review fires per `§6.5` with all four `long_horizon_check` fields populated.\n- Anomalies flow through the `§6.3` mechanism, including autoregulated deload as `severity=critical, recommended_action=\"deload\"`.\n- First-launch baseline (`§2.2`) seeds `UserProfile` and an initial `Goal` from `PROFILE.md` defaults; the wizard does not return after completion.\n\n## Stopping condition\n\nAll four:\n\n1. Each phase's acceptance in `§8` passes (Phase 0 acceptance is now spec-pinned; Phases 1–3 you exercise via tests + a manual smoke run noted in the handoff).\n2. `xbuild` clean. `xtest` green.\n3. ADRs and per-phase handoff docs are committed.\n4. The `codex/phase-0-3` branch is pushed; **do not merge to main**.\n\nWhen you are confident all four hold, stop. Don't keep polishing.\n\n---\n\n## Architectural premise (non-negotiable)\n\n- Single user, single device. No backend. No third-party analytics, ads, telemetry.\n- Claude API called directly from device (Anthropic SDK or direct HTTP — your call).\n- Health data stays on device. Only summaries (not raw streams) leave the device, and only in calls to Claude.\n- iOS 26.4 deployment target, Swift 6.0 mode, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency. Treat `Sendable` / actor-isolation diagnostics as real bugs to fix, not noise to silence.\n- Default to the latest Claude models per `§7.1` (Sonnet 4.6 default, Opus 4.7 for weekly review / complex decisions).\n\n## Personal-health invariants (non-negotiable)\n\nThese shape any code, prompt, test fixture, seed data, or comment you write:\n\n- `§6.7` rules 5/8/9: no medical-advice generation; no chronotype-shift suggestions (\"go to bed earlier\"); no \"don't eat X\" framings; **no chicken-breast recommendations** (user explicitly dislikes chicken breast).\n- `§4.7` red lines (RED-S signals, OTS thresholds) and `§4.2` deficit volume caps are **silent** — they shape proposals but never surface as user-facing alerts. User-visible signals go through `§6.3` Anomalies only.\n- `§2.1` locked profile and `PROFILE.md` current state are facts about the user. Don't invent. Seed defaults from these.\n- Three-state missing-data convention from `§6.4`: omit / `\"no data\"` / `0`. Never collapse missing into zero.\n\n---\n\n## Decision freedom\n\nWide. The spec is the source of *intent*; your implementation is the source of *expression*.\n\n- SwiftData schema (field types, relationships, `@Model` shapes), file layout under `HealthCoach/HealthCoach/`, internal naming, Swift API surfaces — your call from first principles.\n- Prompt structure, feature engineering for LLM input, prompt-version pinning protocol — your call.\n- Trigger mechanism for the 21:00 push (HK observer + `enableBackgroundDelivery`, `BGAppRefreshTask`, hybrid) — your call. `00-index.md` recommends a hybrid (HK observer primary, server fallback) but we have no server, so adapt: HK observer primary, `BGAppRefreshTask` backstop, log gracefully when both miss.\n- Glossary changes are allowed. If you rename a term in `CONTEXT.md`, sweep references in the same commit and add a \"Resolved YYYY-MM-DD\" line under \"Flagged ambiguities\" matching the existing format.\n- If you find a better product design while implementing, implement it and write a one-paragraph note in the relevant handoff (or open a draft spec patch). Don't stop.\n\n**Stop only when:**\n- A non-negotiable invariant above is genuinely in conflict with what you'd need to do.\n- A spec ambiguity touches a personal-health invariant.\n\nIn either case, surface the conflict in the current handoff doc with enough context that a human can decide, then halt.\n\n---\n\n## Required reading\n\nRead once at run start (in addition to `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md` which is auto-loaded):\n\n- `CONTEXT.md` (root) — glossary; ubiquitous-language anchor.\n- `PROFILE.md` (root) — user's current state.\n- `docs/spec-v1.md` — full spec.\n- `docs/adr/0001`, `0002`, `0003` — three short rationale-first decisions; clone the format for your own.\n- `docs/oss-reference/00-index.md` — synthesis of OSS deep-dives, especially \"What to actually borrow\".\n- `docs/evidence-citations.md` — research sources for numeric thresholds.\n\nRead at the start of the relevant phase:\n\n- **Phase 0**: `docs/oss-reference/01-spezi.md` — Spezi's HK patterns. Lift, don't import. Key patterns: `HealthKitConstraint` seam, per-sample-type anchor persistence, ref-counted `enableBackgroundDelivery`, observer→anchored→sink→completion ordering (anchor *before* completion), result-builder DSL idea, `SourceFilter` enum, `@HealthKitQuery`-equivalent on `@Observable` + `.task { for await ... }`.\n- **Phase 1**: `docs/oss-reference/02-healthgpt.md` (mechanical patterns: `HKStatisticsCollectionQuery` daily-bucket primitive, if-let omission renderer fed **real nils**, 3pm→3pm sleep window) + `docs/oss-reference/04-coach-watts.md` (prompt skeleton: persona → profile → 30d context → today recovery → rule-derived English alert → decision logic → JSON-only; structured output via JSON-Schema; \"LLM proposes, server verifies target\" pattern).\n- **Phase 2**: `docs/oss-reference/04-coach-watts.md` again (only the structured-output wrapper; their prompt content is endurance-specific and not transferable) + `docs/oss-reference/07-wger.md` (data extraction: hand-pick 30–50 PPL exercises from `.oss-research/07-wger/` fixtures; factual fields only — name, category, muscles, equipment; write your own descriptions to dodge CC-BY-SA ShareAlike; skip images for v0).\n- **Phase 3**: `docs/oss-reference/05-open-wearables.md` (Sleep score 4-pillar structure with our own paper-cited weights — Hirshkowitz 2015 NSF + Ohayon 2017; **reject** their `60000/hr` bpm→RR recompute, it's a category error; use Apple's `HKHRVSDNN` directly).\n\nTreat OSS references as inspiration, not contract. Verify any pattern against your own judgment of fit. In each handoff, note which sections you actually consulted (one line each: kept this / skipped this / why).\n\n---\n\n## Skills to apply\n\nAt the start of each phase, write a short \"what applies here\" note in working scratch (don't commit) for each:\n\n- `tdd` — red-green-refactor per vertical slice. Tests first.\n- `swift-testing-pro` — modern Swift Testing API patterns and review heuristics.\n- `swiftui-pro` — SwiftUI best practices for the views you write.\n- `improve-codebase-architecture` — deep modules, seams, integrations. The skill is framed for existing codebases, but its core ideas apply to greenfield design too — use them when shaping module boundaries.\n\nAdd at the start of Phase 1:\n\n- `claude-api` — Anthropic SDK and prompt-cache patterns. Default to the latest Claude models. Add prompt caching where the prompt has stable headers.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow\n\n### 1. Branch\n\nCheck out `codex/phase-0-3` off `main` at the very start. Commit regularly with meaningful messages. **Do not merge to main.** Push the branch when stopping.\n\n### 2. Slice\n\nWithin each phase, work in vertical slices with a clear acceptance condition each. TDD per slice (red-green-refactor). `xbuild` clean and `xtest` green before each commit.\n\n### 3. ADRs for keystone decisions\n\nWhen you make a real architectural decision — one that pins shape for downstream work — write `docs/adr/00NN-short-slug.md` and commit it in the same commit (or the immediately-prior commit) that lands the code. Format: short, rationale-first, like the existing three ADRs.\n\nDecisions worth an ADR (non-exhaustive):\n\n- HK wrapper protocol seam shape\n- SwiftData schema first cut and entity boundaries (the `§7.1.1` model overview is names-only — you're designing fields and relations)\n- Anthropic API call wrapper interface and error model\n- Prompt-version pinning protocol (none of the surveyed projects had this — design it)\n- Trigger mechanism (HK observer / `BGAppRefreshTask` / hybrid)\n- Three-state missing-data encoding implementation (the spec pins the convention; you pick the type-level expression)\n- Weekly-review aggregation strategy\n- Vision API integration shape (clarifying-questions roundtrip is implied by `§5.4` but unspecified)\n\n### 4. Per-phase handoff\n\nAt the **end of each phase** (not just at run end), write `docs/handoff/phase-N-<slug>.md`. Read prior handoff docs at the start of each phase — they're the cross-phase memory.\n\nDo **not** duplicate code, ADR text, or commit messages — reference them by path/SHA. Include only:\n\n- What's verified (tests, manual smoke) vs pending.\n- Spec gaps you hit and how you resolved each (proposed spec patch / conservative interpretation / escalation).\n- Glossary or `§6.7` near-misses worth flagging.\n- The keystone decision the next phase will face and links to relevant context.\n- Which skills you applied and which OSS deep-dive sections you actually consulted (one line each: kept / skipped / why).\n\n### 5. Spec edits during the run\n\nFor narrow gaps you resolve while implementing (e.g., \"spec didn't pin whether HK anchor persistence keys on identifier or display name\"), add a one-line spec addendum in the same commit, marked `(YYYY-MM-DD: pinned during Phase N implementation)`. Bump the spec version (`v0.6` → `v0.7`) only if you accumulate enough that the diff is materially different.\n\nFor genuine contradictions with non-negotiables — STOP and surface in the handoff for human review.\n\n---\n\n## API key handling\n\nAll Claude API calls in tests are mocked. The real key will be provisioned by the user post-run, stored in iOS Keychain per spec `§7.1`. Build the API wrapper with a clean injection seam so the mock and the real path are interchangeable (a protocol that both a `LiveAnthropicClient` and a `MockAnthropicClient` conform to is the shape).\n\n**Don't block on having a real key. Don't commit one. Don't make network calls in tests.**\n\n---\n\n## Build commands\n\nFrom inside `HealthCoach/` (where the `.xcodeproj` lives):\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild` | Build for the iPhone 17 simulator. Prints `✅ Build succeeded` or only the compiler errors. |\n| `xtest` | Run all tests. Prints `✅ All N tests passed` or each failing test's identifier + assertion message. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>` | Narrow to one suite/class. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>/<test>` | Narrow to one test method. |\n| `xtests-list` | List test classes (file basenames containing `func test*`, `@Test`, or `@Suite`). |\n\nAdding/removing source files inside `HealthCoach/HealthCoach/` does **not** require `pbxproj` edits (the project uses `PBXFileSystemSynchronizedRootGroup`).\n\n---\n\n## Suggested first commit\n\nBefore writing any code, commit a short `docs/handoff/phase-0-plan.md` with your slice plan for Phase 0, the OSS sections you'll consult, and the ADRs you anticipate writing. This gives the user a quick artifact to skim if they check on the run early. (Optional but useful.)\n\n---\n\nThat's the contract. Read the required docs, plan Phase 0, then start implementing.\n","A senior engineer reviewed your changes and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct.\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\n\n# Review of `codex/phase-0-3`\n\n20 tests green, build clean, simulator launch verified. Codex did a lot in 25 minutes — and the handoffs are honest about the seams that are mocked vs real. But a careful read of the code says **the breadth landed; the depth didn't**. The honest one-line: this is \"everything sketched, nothing yet truly working end-to-end.\" That's not a critique of Codex — it's the predictable shape of an autonomous run that values \"phase acceptance\" defined narrowly. The actual job for the next goal is filling depth, not adding width.\n\n## What's solid (keep, don't churn)\n\n- **The `HealthDataProviding` seam** (ADR-0004) is well-shaped. Live + Mock adapters, `HealthMetricSeries` carrying explicit `permission` state, `HealthDailyValue.noData` vs `.value`. The three-state encoding (ADR-0005) reaches all the way into `promptPayload()` returning `nil` for denied — exactly the convention we pinned in spec §6.4.\n- **`LiveHealthKitProvider`'s metric routing** (HRV-SDNN/RHR/active energy/steps/body mass via `HKStatisticsCollectionQuery`, sleep via 3pm-3pm window, workouts via `HKSampleQuery`) is correct in shape and respects cumulative-vs-discrete. The 3pm window math is right (verified the off-by-9-hours).\n- **SwiftData entity-per-domain decision** (ADR-0006) over a generic JSON blob — exactly what we wanted from the open-health rejection.\n- **Anthropic seam separation** (ADR-0007): raw `AnthropicClient` distinct from product-shaped `CoachAIClient`. The shape is right even though only one side is implemented.\n- **`DeloadDetector` is deterministic and returns `Anomaly(severity: .critical, recommendedAction: \"deload\")`** — exactly the ADR-0002 pattern.\n- **`PromptVersion` with operation + version + SHA-256 of static header** is a cleaner versioning surface than any of the OSS references had. Good outcome.\n- **20 tests with real assertions** — including one that explicitly checks `specificAdvice.contains(\"chicken breast\") == false`. Codex internalized the personal-health invariants.\n- **Per-phase handoffs are honest.** They explicitly call out \"real Claude calls not exercised\", \"USDA not downloaded\", \"HK observer + anchors deferred\" — no false claims of completeness.\n\n## Major gaps (these define the next goal's real scope)\n\nThese aren't polish — they're missing load-bearing pieces that the spec assumes exist.\n\n### 1. The live coach path doesn't exist\n\n`AnthropicClient` exists, `CoachAIClient` protocol exists, but **only `MockCoachAIClient` is implemented**. There is no `LiveCoachAIClient` that:\n\n- Composes the actual prompt (persona → profile → 30d health context → today recovery → rule-derived English alerts → decision logic → JSON-only output — the Coach Watts skeleton we agreed to borrow).\n- Calls `LiveAnthropicClient`.\n- Parses the JSON response into `DailyCoachResponse`.\n- Handles errors / retries.\n\nThe `DailyCoachPrompt.header` is just the policy preamble; it has no persona, no profile injection, no rule-derived alerts, no decision logic. Same for `WeeklyReviewPrompt.header`. Zero of the Coach Watts pattern made it past structure.\n\nSame for vision: `MockFoodPhotoAnalyzer` exists; no `LiveFoodPhotoAnalyzer` that calls Claude vision.\n\n### 2. The 21:00 push isn't actually wired up\n\n`LocalCoachNotificationScheduler` schedules a notification with **fixed text** (\"Daily plan is ready.\"). Nothing invokes `DailyPushService.runDailyPush` — not the BGTask handler (which just calls `setTaskCompleted(success: true)` with no work), not a notification delegate, not the app foreground.\n\n`BackgroundRefreshCoordinator.register` uses the no-op handler:\n\n```swift\nBGTaskScheduler.shared.register(forTaskWithIdentifier: …) { task in\n    task.setTaskCompleted(success: true)\n}\n```\n\nSo the daily push generation pipeline is a connected graph from `runDailyPush → engine → mock client`, but **nothing triggers `runDailyPush`**. The Phase 1 acceptance (\"Daily 21:00 push with summary and tomorrow's plan\") is technically not met. Same gap for the weekly review.\n\n### 3. The training data layer is missing entirely\n\nSpec §7.1.1 lists 13 SwiftData models. Codex implemented 6. Missing: `WorkoutSession`, `ExerciseLog`, `DeloadRecord`, `DailySummary`, `USDAFoodItem`, `HooperEntry`, `RPEEntry`, `SubjectiveNote`.\n\nConsequences cascade:\n\n- **Daily push training summary** has no source. The mock just writes `\"Baseline established. Keep the onboarding plan conservative and consistent.\"` — there's no logged training to summarize.\n- **Weekly review fields `training_completion_rate` and `total_volume_by_muscle`** are hardcoded fiction in the mock (`0.8`, `[\"chest\": 8, \"back\": 10, \"quads\": 6]`).\n- **`DeloadDetector` has nothing to feed it.** All 5 spec §4.5 trigger conditions need data we don't store — HRV-vs-SWC needs SWC computation (not implemented), Hooper Z-score needs `HooperEntry` (not implemented), main compound performance drop needs `WorkoutSession`+`ExerciseLog` (not implemented), completion rate same, low motivation needs `SubjectiveNote` (not implemented).\n- **The `§6.1` decision hierarchy** (\"training performance > subjective readiness > objective physiology\") cannot operate without training performance and subjective data.\n\nThe deload detector exists as theoretically correct rule code with no integration to the rest of the system. ADR-0010 frames this as deliberate separation; the reality is it's an island.\n\n### 4. The First-launch baseline doesn't capture anything\n\n`FirstLaunchBaselineView` displays `LabeledContent(\"Age\", value: \"28\")` etc. — pure read-only confirmation of `PROFILE.md` defaults — and a Start button. It captures **none** of the spec §2.2 fields (age, height, weight, training history, injury history, food preferences, initial Goal-or-none).\n\nWorse: it auto-seeds the recomp Goal as `.active`, **violating both PROFILE.md** (\"None yet — the recomp Goal described in spec §3.3 is the seed Goal that the First-launch baseline (§2.2) will offer\") **and spec §3.2** (\"Zero is also a valid state\"). The user is supposed to be offered the Goal, not have it auto-activated.\n\n### 5. The dashboard doesn't render today's coach output\n\nThe user sees the 30-day metrics list. There's nowhere in the app to view today's daily push response, the high-protein-meal-count tally (`§5.3` Primary KPI), today's anomalies, or the weekly review. So even if the live coach path existed, the user couldn't read its output without inspecting SwiftData.\n\n### 6. USDA + Tier 1 calibration are sketches\n\n- USDA download path: not implemented. No `USDAFoodItem` model. No first-launch download into Application Support. Calibration UI uses placeholder values (`Stepper(value: $proteinEstimate, in: 0...200)` — the user enters numbers, no lookup).\n- Calibration step 3 (\"AI proposal\") is hardcoded text: `\"Beef, radish, broth, and rice.\"` — no vision call, no USDA back-calc.\n- The calibration view doesn't have a PhotosPicker, just a placeholder icon. Step 1 of the wizard is non-functional.\n\nThis is fine if scoped as \"structure for the post-scale future.\" But ADR-0009 frames it as built; in practice it's a form skeleton.\n\n## Smaller issues (polish, can fold into next goal)\n\n- **`@unchecked Sendable` on `LiveHealthKitProvider`** — has no mutable state, can be plain `Sendable`. On `MockHealthDataProvider` — has `requestAuthorizationCallCount` mutable; better as an actor or with an `OSAllocatedUnfairLock`.\n- **`LiveHealthKitProvider` returns `permission: .denied` for \"device unavailable\"** — conflates two distinct cases. Either add a third state (`.unavailable`) or rename `.denied` to `.omit` to match the spec's prompt-input semantics rather than HK's authorization vocabulary.\n- **`AnthropicClient` uses `anthropic-version: 2023-06-01`** — current is `2024-10-22`. Also: no prompt caching despite the static header being huge once the real prompt is composed, no streaming, no error decoding from Anthropic's JSON error envelope, only handles `content[0].text` (breaks if there's a `tool_use` block first). The `claude-api` skill recommends caching by default — the Phase 0 plan flagged that the skill wasn't installed in Codex's session, so this is a known shortfall, not a Codex error.\n- **`HealthMetricSeries.promptPayload()` keys days with `Calendar.current` + `.current` timezone** — for a user moving Nashville → London, this can shift day labels mid-trip. Pin the calendar/timezone at the prompt-build site.\n- **`HealthDailyValue.format()` collapses `8.0` to `\"8\"`** — the dashboard renders sleep as \"8 h\" and steps as \"8420 count\". The integer collapse for sleep is jarring. Use a per-metric formatter.\n- **`DailyCoachResponse.summary.energy.totalKcal` is hardcoded to 0** in the mock — needs real input source.\n- **No prompt files in `Prompts/`** — spec §7.4 says they live there, bundled at build time. Codex inlined the static header in Swift. Defensible (simpler) but contradicts the spec; either update spec or extract files.\n- **Calorie classification `very_heavy` in `FoodPhotoAnalysis`** does not match the spec §5.4 categories (`light | medium | heavy | very_heavy` per spec — actually this matches; my misread). OK, ignore this one.\n- **No usage logging** (token counts, model id, duration). Cheap to add when the live client lands; Coach Watts pattern.\n- **`DailyPushLogModel` and `WeeklyReviewLogModel` lack indexes** on `date` / `weekStart`. SwiftData usually handles fetch but for \"today's log\" lookup it'll matter once data accumulates.\n- **`baselineCompletedOverride` in `AppRootView`** is a transient `@State` flag layered on top of the `@Query` profile check. Either source of truth would do; both is a smell.\n- **The dashboard `MetricSeriesRow` height function** uses `.truncatingRemainder(dividingBy: 34) + 8` — this means a sleep value of 8.0 and 42.0 produce the same bar height. The visualization is decorative, not informative. Either properly normalize per-metric or drop the bars.\n- **`xtest` runs 20 tests all unit-level**. There are zero integration tests asserting that \"scheduling notifications + receiving them + invoking DailyPushService\" actually wires together. The trigger plumbing has no test coverage because there's no plumbing.\n\n## Documentation polish before the next goal\n\nThe handoffs are useful but a few cleanups will help the next loop:\n\n- **All five handoff docs say `Commit: pending at handoff write time`**. Once the run is over, these should reference the actual SHA. Cheap to fix in one pass.\n- **`handoff/final-verification-phase-0-3.md` \"Known follow-up\" section is too short** for what's actually pending. The real follow-up list includes everything in my \"Major gaps\" section above. Either expand it or replace with a pointer to a new `gaps-after-phase-0-3.md` doc.\n- **ADR-0007 says \"the spec's `claude-sonnet-4-6` / `claude-opus-4-7` names appear ahead of currently published IDs and should be revisited in a spec patch when Anthropic publishes those snapshots\"** — this is an open spec edit Codex didn't make. Either (a) update the spec now to use the published IDs Codex used, or (b) leave the spec as aspirational and add a one-liner near §7.1 saying the implementation pins to currently-published snapshots. I'd do (a) since the spec is supposed to be the source of intent and the implementation is reproducing it.\n- **ADR-0008 (\"Schedule local notifications with a BGTask backstop\")** says \"BGTask is best-effort and must log gracefully when missed\" — but the actual code logs nothing and does nothing. Update the ADR to match reality, or fix the code.\n- **ADR-0009** describes the calibration UI as built; reality is structural placeholder. The ADR overstates.\n- **Phase 0 plan's claim that `claude-api` skill wasn't installed** is worth surfacing in `CLAUDE.md` or somewhere durable so the next loop doesn't re-discover it. If it's actually unavailable in Codex's environment, drop it from the goal contract; if available, install it.\n- **`docs/handoff/final-verification-phase-0-3.md` does not list any of the missing SwiftData entities** — the handoff says \"model fields and calibration flow are ready\" for USDA, but `USDAFoodItem` doesn't exist. Polish so the next loop has accurate cross-phase memory.\n\n## Recommendation for the next goal\n\nDon't move to Phase 4 yet. Phase 4 is watchOS and adds breadth on top of a foundation that's structurally complete but functionally hollow. The right next goal is **\"Fill in Phases 0–3\"** — make the seams actually connect end-to-end. Concretely, the goal should target:\n\n1. **Live AI path**: implement `LiveCoachAIClient` and `LiveFoodPhotoAnalyzer`, compose the real prompts (Coach Watts skeleton), parse responses, with prompt caching, retry/error handling, and usage logging.\n2. **Trigger plumbing**: BGTask handler that runs `DailyPushService`; notification delegate that surfaces the latest `DailyPushLogModel` instead of fixed text. Test with a \"fire now\" debug button so simulator smoke is real.\n3. **Training data layer**: `WorkoutSession`, `ExerciseLog`, `HooperEntry`, `RPEEntry`, `SubjectiveNote`, `DeloadRecord` SwiftData models + minimal logging UI. Wire the deload detector to read from these.\n4. **Dashboard surfaces today's coach output**: high-protein-meal-count tally, today's anomalies, \"tomorrow's plan\" card, weekly review card. Per spec the dashboard is \"minimal\" but it has to render the daily/weekly outputs somewhere.\n5. **First-launch baseline that captures inputs**: a real form, not a confirmation screen, with a \"no Goal\" option respected.\n6. **USDA download + lookup**: real `USDAFoodItem` table populated on first launch, used by calibration step 3 to back-calculate protein/calories from confirmed components.\n\nThat scope is roughly the same magnitude as Phases 0–3 in raw lines, but **only if you treat each as a vertical**. I'd structure the goal contract identically: branch `codex/phase-0-3-deepening`, ADRs per keystone (real prompt composition, training-data schema, USDA shape, trigger handler architecture), per-deepening-pass handoff. Reuse the existing `docs/goal/phase-0-3.md` template.\n\nTwo small edits to the goal template before launching the next one, learned from this run:\n\n- **Tighten the acceptance**: \"Phase N acceptance\" should require a manual smoke that exercises the end-to-end pipeline, not just `xtest` green. For Phase 1 deepening: \"trigger the daily push manually via a debug button, see real Anthropic JSON parsed and rendered on the dashboard.\"\n- **Make the `claude-api` skill availability explicit**: either install it or remove from the contract so Codex doesn't write a \"skill not available\" handoff line again.\n\n","Let's now go ahead and implement the recommended fixes. If you have better fixes, feel free to implement those instead, but don't forget to include the documentation suggestions.\n\nI would suggest you follow these steps:\n1. Break down your current uncommitted changes into a few separate commits.\n2. After you have implemented the follow-up fixes, create commits for those as well.\n\nI don't like having a large, giant set of uncommitted changes."],"019e0b65-8e06-7810-ba2f-2137eae8725e":["/goal \n\n# Goal 2: Connect the live AI path and populate the training/readiness pipeline\n\nThis is goal 2 of the HealthCoach implementation. Goal 1 (`codex/phase-0-3`, now merged) established the structure of Phases 0–3 and deepened it. This goal makes that structure functional end-to-end.\n\nYou have already built and deepened this codebase. You don't need to re-read the spec from scratch. The required reading list below is short for that reason. Refresh the parts that matter for this goal, then start.\n\n**Do not edit this file during the run.** If the contract needs to change, the user pauses, edits, and resumes.\n\n---\n\n## Why this scope\n\nGoal 1 left the seams correct but the pipeline disconnected at two points:\n\n- The live AI adapters exist and parse Anthropic JSON in tests, but the running app still calls `MockCoachAIClient`. Connecting them needs a Keychain key path, a `CoachRunCoordinator.live(_:)` factory, prompt caching, and a usage-token envelope.\n- The training/readiness models exist and the deload aggregator reads them, but no path writes them. Without logging UI, HK→`DailySummary` sync, and SWC computation, the deload detector sees zero signals and the weekly review's training summary is empty.\n\nFilling these is the difference between \"structurally complete\" and \"useful.\" After this goal, a real user can log a workout, log a meal, run the coach with a real API key, and see real Anthropic-generated output reflecting their data.\n\n## Objective and stopping condition\n\nTwo themes. Both required for stopping.\n\n**Theme A — live AI path:**\n- `CoachRunCoordinator.live(_:)` factory exists and is what `AppRootView`/`ContentView` use when a key is available.\n- `ApiKeyProviding` protocol with `LiveKeychainKeyProvider` and `MockKeyProvider` adapters; `LiveAnthropicClient` gets its key through injection.\n- Settings or onboarding surface where the user pastes their Anthropic key; persisted to Keychain; never logged, never committed.\n- \"Run Coach\" button without a key surfaces a graceful \"set your API key first\" prompt — does not crash, does not silently mock.\n- `AnthropicCompletion` envelope returns `{ text, usage, model }`; `DailyPushLogModel` and `WeeklyReviewLogModel` persist usage tokens + model id.\n- Prompt caching enabled on the static system block.\n- `LiveCoachAIClient.weeklyReview` threads its `promptVersion` parameter through to the request.\n- `LiveFoodPhotoAnalyzer` is wired into the calibration wizard: step 1 captures a photo via `PhotosPicker`, step 3 calls the analyzer and proposes components the user can adjust before USDA back-calculation.\n- All tests still mock the transport (`StubAnthropicClient`) and the key provider; **no network calls in tests**.\n\n**Theme B — training/readiness pipeline:**\n- Minimal in-app logging surfaces for: starting/ending a `WorkoutSession`, logging `ExerciseLog` entries (hard sets, reps, weight, primary muscle from `ExerciseLibrary`), session-end Hooper Likert (`HooperEntryModel`, four 1–7 fields), session RPE (`RPEEntryModel`), free-text `SubjectiveNoteModel` with a `motivationLow` toggle.\n- `DailySummaryModel` rows are populated from HK on the same fetch that drives the 30-day dashboard. `hrvSWCLowerBound` is computed from a rolling baseline per spec §4.8 (`SWC = 0.75 × SD_baseline`); the rolling window choice is documented in an ADR.\n- All five deload signals from spec §4.5 are extracted in `TrainingReadinessAggregator`: `hrvBelowSWC`, Hooper Z-score, main compound performance drop, training completion < 70% over 2 weeks, sustained low motivation. Confirming-signal count still gates `severity ≥ warning`.\n- A logged session within week N visibly shifts the next weekly review's `trainingCompletionRate` and `totalVolumeByMuscle` for that week (verifiable via a SwiftData test that inserts a session, runs the weekly review service, and asserts the response numbers reflect the data — not the mock fiction).\n\n**Stopping condition (all four):**\n\n1. Theme A acceptance above is satisfied — verified through tests with stubbed transport + the manual \"set a real key in the simulator and tap Run Coach\" smoke if practical (otherwise document in handoff that user verifies post-merge).\n2. Theme B acceptance above is satisfied — verified through unit + SwiftData integration tests.\n3. `xbuild` clean, `xtest` green, simulator launch verified.\n4. ADRs and per-theme handoff docs committed; branch pushed; **do not merge to main**.\n\n## Branch\n\n`codex/goal-2` off the (now-merged) `main`.\n\n---\n\n## Architectural premise (non-negotiable, same as goal 1)\n\n- Single user, single device. No backend.\n- Claude API direct from device.\n- Health data stays on device. Only summaries leave the device.\n- iOS 26.4 deployment, Swift 6.0, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency.\n\n## Personal-health invariants (non-negotiable, same as goal 1)\n\nThese shape every line you write — code, prompts, UI copy, test fixtures, seed data:\n\n- `§6.7` rules 5/8/9: no medical advice, no chronotype-shift suggestions, no \"don't eat X\" framings, no chicken-breast recommendations.\n- `§4.7` red lines (RED-S, OTS) and `§4.2` deficit caps stay silent — they shape proposals, not user-facing alerts. User-visible signals go through `§6.3` Anomalies only.\n- `§2.1` + `PROFILE.md` are facts. Don't invent.\n- Three-state missing-data convention from `§6.4`: omit / `\"no data\"` / `0`. Never collapse missing into zero.\n\n## Decision freedom (same as goal 1)\n\nWide. SwiftData additions, UI shapes, API surfaces, ADR placement — your call from first principles within the architectural premise. Spec patches allowed for narrow gaps with `(YYYY-MM-DD: pinned during Goal 2 implementation)` marker. Glossary changes allowed if you sweep `CONTEXT.md` references and add a \"Resolved YYYY-MM-DD\" line. Stop only when a non-negotiable conflicts genuinely with what you'd need to do.\n\n---\n\n## Required reading\n\nSkim, don't re-read full:\n\n- `docs/handoff/goal-1-followups.md` — the residuals list this goal targets. Numbered items map directly to themes A/B and polish.\n- `docs/handoff/phase-0-3-deepening.md` — most recent state-of-the-world for the codebase you're working in.\n- `docs/spec-v1.md`: `§4.5` (deload triggers), `§4.8` (HRV/SWC), `§5.7` (calibration wizard), `§6.1` (decision hierarchy), `§7.1` (Keychain), `§7.4` (prompt versioning).\n- `docs/adr/0004` through `0011` — keep your new ADRs consistent with the seams already established.\n- `docs/oss-reference/04-coach-watts.md` — prompt caching and per-call usage logging patterns.\n- `docs/oss-reference/05-open-wearables.md` — HRV stability/CV idea (still skip the `60000/hr` recompute).\n\nIf something feels uncertain mid-implementation, re-read the relevant spec section before guessing.\n\n## Skills\n\nSame as goal 1. At the start of each theme, write a short \"what applies here\" note in working scratch (don't commit):\n\n- `tdd` — red-green-refactor per slice.\n- `swift-testing-pro` — Swift Testing patterns.\n- `swiftui-pro` — for the new logging UIs (workout, Hooper, RPE, settings, photo capture).\n- `improve-codebase-architecture` — deep modules. Especially relevant for the logging-UI design — narrow seams between session UI, exercise logging, and persistence.\n- `claude-api` — load-bearing this goal. Apply prompt caching, completion envelope with usage, structured output (tool use is reasonable for our JSON schemas; weigh against the current \"JSON-only via prompt\" approach). If the skill is unavailable in your session, use Anthropic's official docs and note it in the handoff.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow (same as goal 1)\n\n1. **Branch.** `codex/goal-2`. Commit per slice. **Do not merge to main.**\n2. **Slice.** Work in vertical slices with a clear acceptance condition each. TDD per slice. `xbuild` clean and `xtest` green before each commit.\n3. **ADRs for keystone decisions.** Same format as `0001`–`0011`. Examples worth an ADR this goal:\n   - `ApiKeyProviding` seam + Keychain schema.\n   - `AnthropicCompletion` envelope shape (usage token model, where it persists).\n   - Workout-logging UX flow + entity boundaries (one ExerciseLog per Hard set vs per exercise).\n   - HK→`DailySummaryModel` sync strategy (when, how, idempotency).\n   - SWC computation method (rolling window length, artifact handling).\n   - Deload signal extraction algorithms (one ADR or one per signal — your call).\n4. **Per-theme handoff.** At end of theme A and end of theme B, write `docs/handoff/goal-2-theme-a-live-ai.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-2-theme-b-training-pipeline.md`. Do not duplicate code, ADR text, or commit messages — reference by path/SHA. Include only: what's verified vs pending, spec gaps you hit and how resolved, glossary near-misses, what the next loop should know, which skills + OSS sections you actually used (one line each: kept / skipped / why).\n5. **Spec edits** during the run: allowed for narrow gaps with date-stamped marker. STOP and surface in the handoff for genuine non-negotiable conflicts.\n\n## API key handling\n\nThe user provisions a real Anthropic key post-run via the Keychain UI you build. During this run:\n\n- **Build the Keychain read/write path** with a small `ApiKeyProviding` protocol. `LiveKeychainKeyProvider` reads/writes from Keychain; `MockKeyProvider` is for tests.\n- **Build a settings or onboarding surface** where the user pastes their key. Validate format (starts with `sk-ant-`); never log; never commit.\n- **`LiveAnthropicClient` reads its key through injection** — never directly from Keychain at call site.\n- **When no key is set**, the \"Run Coach\" button surfaces a friendly \"set your API key first\" with a navigation link to the settings UI. Don't crash, don't silently fall back to mock.\n- **All tests use `MockKeyProvider`.** No network calls in tests.\n\nYou will not have a real key during this run. Verify the live path through stubbed-transport tests; live verification with a real key is a post-merge user step.\n\n## Build commands\n\nSame as goal 1, run from inside `HealthCoach/`:\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild` | Build for the iPhone 17 simulator. |\n| `xtest` | Run all tests. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>` | Narrow to one suite. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>/<test>` | Narrow to one test method. |\n| `xtests-list` | List test classes. |\n\nAdding/removing source files inside `HealthCoach/HealthCoach/` does **not** require pbxproj edits.\n\n## Polish to fold in\n\nThese are residuals from goal 1 that don't fit either theme cleanly. Pick them up where they're cheap; don't accumulate as a separate phase:\n\n- Update ADR-0008 wording to reflect the now-active BGTask handler (`docs/handoff/goal-1-followups.md` item #11).\n- Consolidate the two `CoachRunCoordinator` instances into a single source (item #12).\n- Decide on `HealthDailyValue.displayText(unit:)` — keep canonical or delete (item #13).\n\n## Suggested first commit\n\nA short `docs/handoff/goal-2-plan.md` with your slice plan for both themes, the ADRs you anticipate, and which OSS sections you'll consult. Optional but useful — same as the goal-1 first commit.\n\n---\n\nThat's the contract. Skim the required reading, plan the themes, then start with Theme A.\n","A senior engineer reviewed your changes and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct.\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\nI have enough surface area to give a thorough review. Pulling the threads together.\n\n---\n\n## Review: `codex/goal-2`\n\nThe two themes both hit their stopping conditions: 40-test suite is green, the live AI seam reaches `AppRootView`, and a logged session demonstrably shifts the weekly review's training numbers. The work is **substantively correct** and a real step from \"structurally complete\" to \"useful.\" The issues below are mostly real but bounded — none invalidate the architecture.\n\n---\n\n### Critical\n\n**C1. BGTask handler is registered after launch finishes — iOS likely won't invoke it.**\n- Where: `AppRootView.swift:35-48` calls `BackgroundRefreshCoordinator.shared.registerIfNeeded { ... }` from a SwiftUI `.task` modifier on `ContentView`.\n- Why this matters: Apple's docs require `BGTaskScheduler.shared.register(forTaskWithIdentifier:using:launchHandler:)` to be called *before* `application(_:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:)` returns. SwiftUI's `.task` runs after the first render — well after launch. Behavior is iOS-version-dependent (older iOS terminates the app with \"All launch handlers must be registered before application finishes launching\"; newer iOS just silently fails to invoke the handler).\n- ADR-0008 claims the BGTask now actually runs the daily coach service. With this registration timing it almost certainly doesn't, in practice.\n- Concrete fix: register in the `App` struct's `init()` (or via `UIApplicationDelegateAdaptor`). Move just `BGTaskScheduler.shared.register(...)` to launch-time; keep the daily handler injection lazy via a stored closure that the `App.init` registers a thunk around. Sketch:\n  ```swift\n  @main struct HealthCoachApp: App {\n      init() { BackgroundRefreshCoordinator.shared.registerLaunchHandler() }\n      ...\n  }\n  ```\n  And split `registerIfNeeded` into `registerLaunchHandler()` (idempotent BG register, called at launch) + `setDailyHandler(_:)` (called from `.task` once the model context exists).\n\n---\n\n### Moderate\n\n**M1. PhotosPicker returns HEIC; the analyzer hardcodes `image/jpeg`.**\n- Where: `LiveCoachAIClient.swift:48-58` (`analyze`), used by `FoodLoggingView.swift:43-53` and `RegisteredMealCalibrationView.swift:115-123`.\n- Why: iPhone camera default since iOS 11 is HEIC. `PhotosPicker(... loadTransferable(type: Data.self))` returns the original asset bytes. The Anthropic Messages API accepts only `image/jpeg | png | gif | webp` — HEIC is rejected with an opaque 400. Theme A's \"real-world flow\" path will fail on the most common photo source.\n- Theme A handoff acknowledges this (\"If PhotosPicker produces non-JPEG data in practice, add lightweight media-type detection\") — leaving it open in a user-facing path is a moderate gap, not minor.\n- Concrete fix: prefer `loadTransferable(type: Image.self)` and re-encode to JPEG, OR keep `Data` + sniff: check the first bytes (`ftypheic`/`ftypheix` prefix → re-encode through `UIImage(data:).jpegData(compressionQuality: 0.85)`; PNG signature → pass `image/png`; default JPEG). Centralize as a helper since both views need it.\n\n**M2. Main-compound performance-drop signal pools different lifts into one mean.**\n- Where: `TrainingReadinessAggregator.swift:85-112` (`hasMainCompoundPerformanceDrop`).\n- Why: `previous = baseline avg of weight*reps across squat+bench+row+ohp+deadlift entries pooled`, then compared against `recentWeeks[i].max()`. Different lifts have wildly different absolute weight×reps (a deadlift entry dominates a squat entry in the pool). Result:\n  - False positive: if user only logs squat in the recent week (lower weight×reps than deadlift baseline), the signal fires with no actual regression.\n  - False negative: if bench drops 10% but deadlift sets a PR, pooling masks it.\n- Severity moderate because this is one of two confirming signals for a critical deload Anomaly — a noisy signal here can either trigger a false deload recommendation or hide a real one. Spec §4.5 reads as per-compound regression.\n- Concrete fix: group `logs` by `exerciseName.lowercased()`, compute baseline-mean and weekly-max *per exercise*, then check `anyExercise.allWeeks(best ≤ baseline*0.95)`. Same data, different aggregation. ADR-0014 should be amended to reflect \"per-exercise comparison; signal fires if any single main compound drops ≥5% across both weeks.\"\n\n**M3. Sets-per-session counted as a single `hardSets` integer per `ExerciseLogModel`.**\n- Where: `TrainingLogService.swift:23-40` writes one log row per \"Log Exercise\" tap with `hardSets` as an Int. `weeklySummary` sums `hardSets` over all logs for the week. `mainCompoundPerformanceDrop` treats `weight × reps` per row as a performance score.\n- Why this matters: if the user logs the same exercise three times in one session (3 separate \"Log Exercise\" presses), volume sums correctly (good) but performance comparison double-counts. If they log it once with `hardSets=3`, the performance score is `weight*reps` of one set — without information about which set. Spec §4.4 expects sets and reps as the granular unit.\n- Severity moderate: works for v1 but the \"log three sets at once\" UX choice silently distorts the per-set comparison the deload signal needs. Either (a) commit to \"one ExerciseLog row per hard set\" with `hardSets=1` always (UX: log each set separately; matches every other lifter app), or (b) keep the current shape but use `weight × reps × hardSets` as the performance score for drop detection. (b) is the cheaper fix.\n\n**M4. 21:00 daily notification fires regardless of whether a fresh push exists.**\n- Where: `CoachNotificationScheduler.swift:21-32` schedules a `UNCalendarNotificationTrigger` with hardcoded body \"Daily plan is ready.\"\n- Why: With M1's BG registration likely silently failing, with no API key set, or any HTTP error, no `DailyPushLogModel` is written. The 21:00 system notification still fires claiming a plan is ready. User opens to yesterday's data with no indication anything is wrong. Existed before goal 2 but goal 2 made it more visible by introducing the missing-key state as a normal first-run condition.\n- Concrete fix (cheap): drop the calendar trigger; have the BG handler (or a Run Coach success path) post a one-shot `UNTimeIntervalNotificationTrigger` with body referencing the actual response (e.g., \"Tomorrow: Push — technique focus\"). Falls back silently when no log was generated, matches HealthGPT-style \"post after data\" pattern.\n\n**M5. `WeeklyReviewService` overrides only two of the six `weekSummary` fields with deterministic data.**\n- Where: `WeeklyReviewEngine.swift:101-103` — `trainingCompletionRate` and `totalVolumeByMuscle` are overwritten with `TrainingReadinessAggregator.weeklySummary`. The other four (`avgProteinG`, `proteinComplianceRate`, `weightChangeKG`, `avgRestingHR`, `avgHRV`, `sleepTimingRegularitySDMin`) stay as whatever the LLM produced.\n- Why: with the mock client they're hardcoded fictions (e.g., `avgRestingHR: latest()...`); with the live client they're whatever Claude infers. The spec lists these as numeric facts the system computes from data, not as model judgment. The current state means the JSON shipped to the user is half-deterministic / half-LLM.\n- Concrete fix: extend `weeklySummary` aggregator to compute all six summary numbers from the `MealEntryModel` / `DailySummaryModel` / `WorkoutSessionModel` data already available, and override the LLM payload across the board. Keeps the LLM in charge of `wins/concerns/longHorizonCheck/nextWeekAdjustments` (judgment) but pins the numbers (facts).\n\n---\n\n### Minor\n\n**m1. `APIKeySettingsView` has no read-back, no clear/replace, no \"key is set\" state.**\n- Where: `Settings/APIKeySettingsView.swift`.\n- After save, `apiKey = \"\"`. There's no indicator that a key already exists in Keychain. Users can't tell whether they need to paste again. Fix: read on appear via `provider.apiKey()`, show \"Key currently stored (last 4: …xyz)\" or just a checkmark; add a \"Clear key\" button that calls a new `provider.deleteApiKey()`. Adding `func deleteApiKey() throws` to the protocol is ~5 lines.\n\n**m2. `LiveAnthropicClient` calls Keychain synchronously from inside `complete()`.**\n- Where: `AnthropicClient.swift:60-61`. `apiKey()` blocks on `SecItemCopyMatching` from the calling actor (typically `@MainActor` since `CoachRunCoordinator` is). Keychain calls are usually fast but can block briefly. Not a real bug — flag for awareness; could move to first-line caching: read once per `LiveAnthropicClient` lifetime.\n\n**m3. `runDailyCoachNow` re-runs `model.load()` and `DailySummarySync.sync()` on every tap.**\n- Where: `ContentView.swift:129-143`. Dashboard `.task` already did this. Refresh-before-coach is reasonable but the user sees a 30-day HK fetch latency between tap and any error appearing. Not breaking. Could short-circuit if last load was <1 minute ago.\n\n**m4. `MockKeyProvider.saveApiKey` validates but doesn't store.**\n- Where: `ApiKeyProvider.swift:42-45`. Future tests that exercise the save→read flow will silently fail. Either make `MockKeyProvider` a class with `var storedKey` mutated by `saveApiKey`, or document. Cosmetic now; trap later.\n\n**m5. `DailySummarySync.sync` clobbers existing values with nil when a metric is absent on a day.**\n- Where: `DailySummarySync.swift:26-32`. If yesterday's row had `hrvSDNN = 47` and today's HK fetch returns no HRV sample for yesterday (unlikely but possible after the observer hardening lands), the row's HRV gets set to nil. Currently safe because each fetch is the source of truth for the 30-day window. Worth a one-line \"// last-fetch-wins\" comment when observer-based delivery lands.\n\n**m6. `mainCompounds` Set is private to the aggregator and uses lowercased exercise names that must match the seed library exactly.**\n- Where: `TrainingReadinessAggregator.swift:125`. Adding \"Sumo Deadlift\" or \"Front Squat\" to the library wouldn't qualify them as main compounds. This is a \"known small risk of drift\" — link the canonical set to a tag on `ExerciseSeed` (`isMainCompound: Bool`) so the source of truth is the library, not a parallel Set. Not load-bearing yet.\n\n**m7. Population SD vs sample SD in SWC computation.**\n- Where: `DailySummarySync.swift:69` and `TrainingReadinessAggregator.swift:74`. Both divide by `n` not `n-1`. For n≥7 the bias is <8%; for the 28-day case it's <2%. Not worth changing now, but worth a one-line note in ADR-0013 acknowledging the choice.\n\n---\n\n### Did it solve the intended problem?\n\n**Theme A: largely yes.** The seam is correct, tests prove the missing-key path doesn't persist a log, and the Settings → Run Coach loop is the right shape for a real key. The two real obstacles to \"tap a real key in the simulator and the daily push works end-to-end\" are M1 (HEIC photos) for the food path and C1 (BG handler timing) for unattended runs. Both are mechanical fixes.\n\n**Theme B: yes for the data plumbing, partly for the signal logic.** The pipeline lights up — a logged session changes the next weekly review's numbers, all five deload signals exist and are tested, SWC is computed with a documented window. The signal-extraction quality has two real flaws (M2, M3) that will distort live judgments once the user actually logs sessions. Catch them now while the signal logic is a single small file rather than after data accumulates.\n\n**Recommended order:** C1, M1 immediately (block the live merge); M2, M3, M5 before goal 3 starts (signal correctness now is cheaper than after 4 weeks of skewed data); M4 whenever; minor items as drive-bys.\n\n---\n\nOne comment from me is that you should probably first break down your uncommitted changes into a couple of focused commits. Then, on top of that, implement your fixes as a few more follow-up commits.","ok, lets implement the followup improvements as next set of commits, update relevant docs to make them up to date along the way, focus on describing the current state, no changelog style pharsing"],"019e0d7d-c804-7bc0-aab7-e36458255c1b":["/goal \n\n# Goal 3: watchOS app + close out Phase 0–3 production hardening\n\nThis is goal 3 of the HealthCoach implementation. Goal 1 (`codex/phase-0-3`) and goal 2 (`codex/goal-2`) made the iOS app structurally complete and functional end-to-end through Phase 3. This goal adds the watch (Phase 4) and closes the remaining Phase 0–3 residuals that turn the iOS app from \"works\" into \"production-grade.\"\n\nYou have already built and deepened this codebase across two prior goals. The required reading list below is short for that reason. Refresh the parts that matter for this goal, then start.\n\ncreate focused commits alongside your implementation, do not wait until the end to commit them\n\n---\n\n## Why this scope\n\nTwo things are true after goal 2:\n\n- The iOS app is the only logger. The watch is silent. Spec §8 Phase 4 calls for real-time HR, RPE input, Hooper input, and an HRV self-computation feasibility check — all on the wrist, where the user actually trains. Without this, every Hooper/RPE entry is a post-hoc iPhone tap, which it won't survive contact with reality.\n- Phase 0–3 has visible-but-deferred infrastructure debt: HK reads still poll 30 days direct (no observer/anchor); the FNDDS lookup is a 6-item fallback seed instead of the spec's ~7k-row offline table; anomalies live only in the most recent JSON response (no history, no UI surface, no acknowledgment); `sleep_timing_regularity_sd_min` is a static `0` because sleep-onset isn't extracted yet. The next user-real flows (chronic underfueling, motivation decay over weeks, deload acceptance loops) all depend on these.\n\nThese two themes converge on the same data layer: when the watch starts writing too, the iOS read seam needs to be observer-based, not poll-based. Doing them together is cheaper than doing them serially.\n\n## Objective and stopping condition\n\nTwo themes. Both required for stopping.\n\n**Theme A — watchOS (Phase 4):**\n- A watchOS app target exists in the Xcode project, deployment target consistent with iOS 26.4 (watchOS 26.x), Swift 6, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency.\n- HK permission flow on the watch reads the same seven sample types as iOS plus heart rate and (if used) `HKHeartbeatSeriesSample` for RMSSD compute.\n- Session lifecycle on the watch: start a session (planned type from the same `ExerciseLibrary`), log `ExerciseLog` entries one row per Hard set, end the session, capture the four-item Hooper Likert and session RPE before exiting. UI is finger-on-watch — no on-screen keyboard for numbers; use the digital crown or steppers.\n- Real-time HR display during the session, with the spec §4.6 Zone 2 (50–65% maxHR) band visible enough to be useful mid-set. Sustained > 95% maxHR raises a logged anomaly per §4.7 (silent, not user-visible).\n- Watch ↔ iPhone data sync. Choose one mechanism (shared SwiftData via App Group, `WatchConnectivity`, or CloudKit) from first principles and document the choice in an ADR. Conflict resolution rule must be explicit (e.g., last-writer-wins by `updatedAt`, or watch-is-source-of-truth for sessions, or merge by `id`).\n- HRV self-computation feasibility: a real spike against `HKHeartbeatSeriesQuery` / `HKBeatToBeatMeasurement` to compute RMSSD on-device, with findings in an ADR. If feasible and validation looks reasonable, ship it as the new HRV path and update `DailySummaryModel.hrvSDNN` semantics (or add `hrvRMSSD`). If not feasible, document why and stay on SDNN — but the ADR must be a real \"we tried, here's what we found,\" not a deferral.\n- All tests still mock the transport, the key provider, and any new sync seam. **No network calls, no HK live calls in tests.**\n\n**Theme B — Phase 0–3 production hardening:**\n- HealthKit observer + anchor persistence. Replace the direct 30-day fetch with observer-based delivery for the seven sample types: `HKObserverQuery` per type, ref-counted background delivery, anchor stored in the SwiftData store (or `UserDefaults`), `HKAnchoredObjectQuery` for incremental reads. Idempotent on first install (no anchor → fall back to 30-day window). The Spezi pattern in `docs/oss-reference/01-spezi.md` is the reference; do not borrow Spezi's HealthKitConstraint protocol verbatim — adapt to our existing `HealthDataProviding` seam (ADR-0004).\n- Full FNDDS download. On first launch, fetch the ~7k-row FNDDS subset from `fdc.nal.usda.gov` into Application Support, cache, fall back to the existing 6-item seed if the network fails. Show progress (it's a multi-MB download). Idempotent — re-running doesn't re-download. The download URL/format detail lives in spec §5.7; pick a stable subset (FNDDS at-home + away-from-home survey foods) and document in an ADR.\n- Anomaly history persistence + UI. New `AnomalyHistoryModel` capturing every emitted anomaly: `type`, `severity`, `detail`, `signalsConfirmed`, `recommendedAction`, `source` (`dailyPush` | `weeklyReview`), `emittedAt`, `acknowledgedAt?`. Daily push and weekly review services persist alongside their existing log models. Dashboard surface: a section listing the last 14 days of anomalies with their resolution state, plus a rolling-pattern view (\"HRV below SWC: 8 of last 14 days\"). Accept/dismiss action mutates `acknowledgedAt`. Cold-start rule (history < N days) lives in a new ADR (see Polish below).\n- Sleep-onset timing SD. Extract sleep-onset timestamp from HK sleep samples within the existing 3pm→3pm sleep window. Maintain a rolling 7-day SD in minutes in `DailySummaryModel` (replace the static `0`). Spec §5.6 is the rule: trigger attention at SD > 90 min over 7 days. Weekly review's `sleep_timing_regularity_sd_min` should now be a real number from `WeeklyReviewService` aggregation, joining the deterministic-facts override pattern from goal 2 (ADR-0015).\n\n**Stopping condition (all four):**\n\n1. Theme A acceptance above is satisfied — verified through stubbed-transport tests + a watchOS simulator launch where you can start a session, log a set, end the session, and see it appear on the iPhone after sync. HRV self-compute decision committed in an ADR.\n2. Theme B acceptance above is satisfied — verified through unit + SwiftData integration tests. Observer behavior tested with a fake HK store that emits incremental samples; FNDDS download tested with a stub URLSession; anomaly history tested with a SwiftData round-trip; sleep-onset SD tested with fixture samples.\n3. `xbuild` clean for both iOS and watchOS schemes; `xtest` green; both simulators launched.\n4. ADRs and per-theme handoff docs committed; branch pushed; **do not merge to main.**\n\n## Branch\n\n`codex/goal-3` off the (now-merged-or-soon-merged) `main`.\n\n---\n\n## Architectural premise (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\n- Single user, two devices (iPhone + Apple Watch). No backend.\n- Claude API direct from device — only iPhone runs the coach loop. Watch is a logger and a real-time HR surface.\n- Health data stays on device. Only summaries leave the device.\n- iOS 26.4 + watchOS 26.x deployment, Swift 6.0, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency.\n\n## Personal-health invariants (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\nThese shape every line you write — code, prompts, UI copy, test fixtures, seed data:\n\n- `§6.7` rules 5/8/9: no medical advice, no chronotype-shift suggestions, no \"don't eat X\" framings, no chicken-breast recommendations.\n- `§4.7` red lines (RED-S, OTS) and `§4.2` deficit caps stay silent — they shape proposals, not user-visible alerts. User-visible signals go through `§6.3` Anomalies only. **The new anomaly history UI is bound by this rule too** — surface anomalies the system already emits; do not invent new red-line UI from raw data.\n- `§2.1` + `PROFILE.md` are facts. Don't invent.\n- Three-state missing-data convention from `§6.4`: omit / `\"no data\"` / `0`. Never collapse missing into zero. Sleep-onset SD with < 7 days of data is `\"no data\"`, not `0`.\n\n## Decision freedom (same as prior goals)\n\nWide. SwiftData additions, UI shapes, sync mechanism, FNDDS download format, ADR placement — your call from first principles within the architectural premise. Spec patches allowed for narrow gaps with `(YYYY-MM-DD: pinned during Goal 3 implementation)` marker. Glossary changes allowed if you sweep `CONTEXT.md` references and add a \"Resolved YYYY-MM-DD\" line. Stop only when a non-negotiable conflicts genuinely with what you'd need to do.\n\nThe watch ↔ iPhone sync mechanism is the highest-leverage decision this goal. Pick one and commit; don't hedge.\n\n---\n\n## Required reading\n\nSkim, don't re-read full:\n\n- `docs/handoff/goal-2-theme-a-live-ai.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-2-theme-b-training-pipeline.md` — most recent state-of-the-world.\n- `docs/spec-v1.md`: `§4.6` (HR zones), `§4.7` (silent red lines), `§4.8` (HRV/SWC, RMSSD note), `§5.6` (sleep timing regularity), `§5.7` (FNDDS), `§6.3` (anomalies), `§8` Phase 4 row, `§10` OSS amendments.\n- `docs/adr/0004` (HealthKit seam — the one you'll extend), `0006` (SwiftData entity boundaries — for `AnomalyHistoryModel`), `0013` (daily summary sync — extend with sleep-onset), `0015` (weekly review factual summary — pattern for sleep-onset SD).\n- `docs/oss-reference/01-spezi.md` — observer + anchor persistence patterns. Adapt, don't import.\n- `docs/oss-reference/02-healthgpt.md` — 3pm→3pm sleep window (already implemented; reuse for sleep-onset extraction).\n- `docs/oss-reference/05-open-wearables.md` — HRV stability/CV idea. Still skip the `60000/hr` recompute.\n\nIf something feels uncertain mid-implementation, re-read the relevant spec section before guessing.\n\n## Skills\n\nSame set as prior goals. At the start of each theme, write a short \"what applies here\" note in working scratch (don't commit):\n\n- `tdd` — red-green-refactor per slice.\n- `swift-testing-pro` — Swift Testing patterns; observer/sync tests want fakes, not mocks.\n- `swiftui-pro` — both iOS additions (anomaly history list/cards) and watchOS UI. Watch UI has its own conventions (digital crown, glanceable layouts, smaller hit targets) — apply them.\n- `improve-codebase-architecture` — load-bearing this goal. The watch ↔ iPhone sync seam, the observer-vs-poll seam, and the anomaly history persistence boundary are all deep-module decisions. Narrow seams; document the contract; one ADR per keystone.\n- `claude-api` — light-touch this goal. The only AI-side change is anomaly history feeding back into prompt context if you choose to (default: don't; weekly review already gets anomaly snapshots through `WeeklyReviewInput`). If you do, weigh against the prompt-cache invalidation cost.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow (same as prior goals)\n\n1. **Branch.** `codex/goal-3`. Commit per slice. **Do not merge to main.**\n2. **Slice.** Vertical slices with a clear acceptance condition each. TDD per slice. `xbuild` clean (both schemes once watchOS lands) and `xtest` green before each commit.\n3. **ADRs for keystone decisions.** Same format as prior ADRs. Examples worth an ADR this goal:\n   - watchOS app shape and target boundaries.\n   - Watch ↔ iPhone sync mechanism + conflict-resolution rule.\n   - HRV self-compute feasibility findings and the SDNN-vs-RMSSD decision.\n   - HK observer + anchor persistence strategy (ref-counting, anchor storage, idempotency on cold install).\n   - FNDDS download shape (subset selected, format, fallback behavior).\n   - `AnomalyHistoryModel` schema + cold-start rule (or amend existing ADR — see Polish).\n   - Sleep-onset SD extraction (which HK samples count as \"onset,\" 3pm→3pm window edge cases).\n4. **Per-theme handoff.** At end of each theme, write `docs/handoff/goal-3-theme-a-watchos.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-3-theme-b-production-hardening.md`. Don't duplicate code, ADR text, or commit messages — reference by path/SHA. Include only: what's verified vs pending, spec gaps you hit and how resolved, glossary near-misses, what the next loop should know, which skills + OSS sections you actually used (one line each: kept / skipped / why).\n5. **Spec edits** during the run: allowed for narrow gaps with date-stamped marker. STOP and surface in the handoff for genuine non-negotiable conflicts.\n\n## API key handling\n\nUnchanged from goal 2. The watch does not call Claude. The watch is a logger and a HR display only. If a watch UI surface would benefit from coach output (e.g., \"tomorrow's plan\" glance), pull it from the iPhone-persisted `DailyPushLogModel` via the chosen sync mechanism — do not call the API from the watch.\n\nAll tests still use `MockKeyProvider`. No network calls in tests.\n\n## Build commands\n\nThe wrappers are scheme-aware. iOS commands stay the same:\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild` | Build for the iPhone 17 simulator (default scheme `HealthCoach`). |\n| `xtest` | Run all iOS tests. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>` | Narrow to one suite. |\n| `xtests-list` | List test classes. |\n\nOnce you add the watchOS target, build it explicitly:\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild -s HealthCoachWatch` | Build the watchOS scheme (use whatever scheme name you create). |\n| `XCODE_DESTINATION='platform=watchOS Simulator,name=Apple Watch Series 10 (46mm)' xtest` | Run watchOS tests on the watch simulator. |\n\nAdding/removing source files inside `HealthCoach/HealthCoach/` (and the new watch target's source group) does **not** require pbxproj edits when using `PBXFileSystemSynchronizedRootGroup`. **Adding a new target itself does** require pbxproj editing — do this in Xcode or via a careful manual edit; commit the pbxproj diff in its own commit so it's reviewable.\n\n## Polish to fold in\n\nThese are doc-quality items the next implementer (you) will benefit from. Do them on a quiet slice; don't accumulate as a separate phase:\n\n- **`CONTEXT.md`** — add canonical entries for `SWC` (smallest worthwhile change, formula `0.75 × SD_baseline`), `Signal` (with cardinality rule: a Signal is aggregated, not a single reading), `Hooper Index` (4-item Likert: sleep/stress/fatigue/DOMS, used as Z-score for deload), `RED-S` (relative energy deficiency in sport), `OTS` (overtraining syndrome), `RMSSD` (root mean square of successive differences, the Phase 4 HRV target metric).\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §8** — add a \"Status (YYYY-MM-DD): Phases 0–3 complete and functional after goals 1+2; live AI active, training/readiness pipeline populated. Phase 4 in progress under goal 3.\" preamble so future readers don't think it's all aspirational.\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §7.1.1** — mark each SwiftData model in the prose list with an \"(implemented)\" marker so a future agent doesn't try to re-scaffold them.\n- **New ADR `0016-anomaly-history-cold-start.md`** — pin the rule for how anomaly trends behave with insufficient history. Examples: \"HRV below SWC for 5+ days\" requires ≥ 7 days of HRV data before it can fire; new-device cold start defaults to no anomaly until the baseline window is filled. Without this ADR pinned, Theme B's anomaly history UI will accidentally fire empty or fictional patterns on day 1.\n\n## Suggested first commit\n\nA short `docs/handoff/goal-3-plan.md` with your slice plan for both themes, the ADRs you anticipate, the watch ↔ iPhone sync mechanism you're leaning toward (with one-paragraph rationale), and which OSS sections you'll consult. Optional but useful — same as prior first commits.\n\n---\n\nThat's the contract. Skim the required reading, plan the themes, then start with whichever theme unblocks the other. (Theme B's observer hardening usually wants to land first so Theme A's watch writes don't fight a polling iOS reader, but it's your call.)\n\n\n","A senior engineer reviewed your changes and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct.\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\n\n## Goal 3 review\n\n40 net production files + 12 new tests landed. Big surface, mostly correct. Genuinely partial in the senses the author flagged — plus a couple they didn't.\n\n---\n\n### Critical\n\n**C1. ~24k lines of global skill docs were committed to the repo.**\n- Where: `.agents/skills/claude-api/` and `.claude/skills/claude-api/` (89 files, commit `58d5cae`). `.gitignore` doesn't exclude them; `skills-lock.json` is also committed.\n- Why: skills are user-/agent-level tooling, not project artifacts. Bloats the repo, leaks the agent toolchain into product history, and makes future diffs noisy.\n- Fix: `git revert 58d5cae` (or `git rebase -i` and drop it), then add `.agents/skills/`, `.claude/skills/` to `.gitignore`. Keep `skills-lock.json` only if it has a real purpose — otherwise drop it too.\n\n**C2. HK observer runs *in parallel* with the existing 30-day poll, not as a replacement.**\n- Where: `LiveHealthKitProvider.swift` adds `HKObserverQuery` + `HKAnchoredObjectQuery` paths, but `DailyPushService.runDailyPush(...)` and `ContentView.task` still call `thirtyDaySummary(endingAt:)`. Both fire on every coach run and every dashboard load.\n- Why: the goal-3 contract (Theme B, line 32) said \"Replace the direct 30-day fetch with observer-based delivery.\" Today the observer's incremental data feeds `DailySummarySync`, but the consumer paths still poll. Net effect: more code, no actual reduction in HK reads — and now two write paths into `DailySummaryModel` that both call `context.save()`.\n- Fix: leave the 30-day poll as a cold-start fallback only (`if anchor == nil`). Steady-state reads come from anchored incrementals + cached `DailySummaryModel` rows. The dashboard view-model should query SwiftData first, hit HK only when absent. ADR-0019 should be updated to specify this transition rule explicitly.\n\n**C3. Anomaly history cold-start rule (ADR-0016) is documented but not enforced.**\n- Where: ADR-0016 specifies \"trend signals (HRV below SWC, sleep-onset SD, sustained low motivation) require ≥7 days of underlying data before they may fire.\" `DailyCoachEngine` and `WeeklyReviewEngine` emit anomalies through the LLM/JSON pipeline without any history-depth gate. `ContentView` renders \"History building\" only if total anomaly count < 7, which is the wrong predicate.\n- Why: a brand-new install, day 3, can persist a `hrv_7_day_below_swc` anomaly into `AnomalyHistoryModel` with three days of HRV data. The rolling-pattern UI then shows \"HRV below SWC: 1 of 3 days\" as a real signal. This contradicts §6.4 three-state and the goal contract's invariant (\"the new anomaly history UI is bound by this rule too\").\n- Fix: gate persistence at the `AnomalyHistoryStore.persist(...)` boundary — refuse to insert any trend-shaped anomaly whose underlying signal lacks ≥7 valid `DailySummaryModel` rows in the lookback window. Add a test that inserts a 3-day-old install and asserts no trend anomalies survive the gate.\n\n---\n\n### Moderate\n\n**M1. Watch HR thresholds are hardcoded, not personalized.**\n- Where: `HealthCoachWatch/WatchHealthKitModel.swift` defines `zone2LowerBound: 96`, `zone2UpperBound: 125`, `highHeartRateStopBound: 182` as static `Int` properties. These match the user's profile (maxHR 192) but are wrong for anyone else and freeze even for this user as max changes.\n- Why: spec §4.6 defines Zone 2 as 50–65% of *maxHR* (per-user), §4.7 sustained alert at 95% of maxHR. The watch app has no access to `UserProfileModel` or `modelContext`. Even though the product is single-user, freezing thresholds in code makes the anomaly logic untestable against age changes and silently breaks the spec's per-user framing.\n- Fix: either (a) push the user's `maxHR` to the watch via `WCSession.updateApplicationContext` at app start (single-shot, retried on activation), or (b) share `UserProfileModel` defaults via App Group `UserDefaults` and read on watch launch. (a) is cheaper and matches the existing WC seam.\n\n**M2. Smoke-test claim conflates fixture path with user UI path.**\n- Where: `WatchSessionView.swift:101-121` has a `sendUITestSessionIfRequested(...)` block gated behind `--hc-auto-watch-session` launch argument. The author's \"watch auto-session imported into iPhone SwiftData as 1 Push workout, Bench Press hard set, RPE 8, Hooper 4/3/3/2\" is the *fixture* round-trip, not a real-tap session.\n- Why: the real `WatchSessionView` UI (steppers, exercise picker, \"Log Set\" button) compiles and renders, but the smoke evidence presented doesn't prove a human tapping the watch produces a session. That's a meaningful confidence gap.\n- Fix: either (a) drive the real UI in a Swift Testing `@MainActor` test that calls the `logSet`/`endSession` functions through view-model state and asserts the envelope, or (b) explicitly downgrade the handoff line to \"fixture-driven smoke; real-tap path verified post-merge on device.\" The current framing is misleading.\n\n**M3. RMSSD math is shipped but never invoked.**\n- Where: `HealthCoachShared/HRVMetrics.swift` correctly computes RMSSD from beat-time arrays (tested in `HRVComputationTests`). `WatchHealthKitModel.rmssdFromMostRecentHeartbeatSeries()` exists. Neither is called by the session lifecycle — no end-of-session capture, no result stored in `WatchSessionDraft`, no field on the synced envelope.\n- Why: ADR-0021 documents the deferral, which is fine — but the seam is one `await` away from \"captured at session end and surfaced through the envelope.\" Leaving it dormant means the next time someone touches this code they'll either re-derive the contract or wonder why the dead code exists.\n- Fix: either wire it (`endSession` calls `rmssdFromMostRecentHeartbeatSeries()`, stores in the envelope, iPhone importer writes to a new optional field on `WorkoutSessionModel`), or delete the watch-side method and keep only the math + tests in shared until a follow-on goal commits to RMSSD. Currently it's a half-built feature.\n\n**M4. `WatchWorkoutImporter` re-insert path can clobber prior session fields.**\n- Where: `WatchWorkoutImporter.swift:19-25`. Existing exercise sets are deduped by `id`, but the parent `WorkoutSessionModel` is re-inserted (or fetched + overwritten?) on each envelope arrival. WatchConnectivity transfers can retransmit on activation; if the watch later updates duration or plannedType, the iPhone overwrite is silent.\n- Why: spec doesn't define watch-vs-iPhone authority for an in-flight session. Without a documented merge rule the importer's behavior depends on whatever path runs last, which is untested.\n- Fix: in the importer, fetch existing session by `id` first; if found, apply `WatchWorkoutMerge` (last-writer-wins by `updatedAt` per ADR-0020) field-by-field rather than re-inserting. Add a test that imports the same envelope twice with mutated fields and asserts the merge rule.\n\n**M5. Anomaly pattern UI is generic; doesn't render the per-Signal pattern the contract called for.**\n- Where: `ContentView.swift` lines around the anomaly history section. Aggregates by `anomaly.type` and shows top-N counts. Does not render named-Signal patterns (\"HRV below SWC: 8 of last 14 days\").\n- Why: the goal-3 contract explicitly cited \"HRV below SWC: 8 of last 14 days\" as the example surface. Today the user sees `nutrition_logging: 2 of 14`, which is informational but not the rolling-Signal trend the spec wants.\n- Fix: in the UI, distinguish trend Signals (HRV-SWC, sleep-onset SD, sustained low motivation) from one-off anomalies (nutrition logging gaps), and render the trend Signals with the named-Signal-of-N-of-window framing. The data model already supports it.\n\n---\n\n### Minor\n\n**m1. `WCSession.activate()` may fire twice.** `WatchWorkoutConnectivityReceiver.start()` is invoked from a `.task` modifier in `AppRootView`; SwiftUI can re-run `.task` if the view's identity changes. Add a one-shot guard or move activation into the receiver's `init`. Harmless today.\n\n**m2. No standalone test suite for `AnomalyHistoryModel`.** Persistence is verified transitively via `DailyPushServiceTests` and `WeeklyReviewTests`. Add a `AnomalyHistoryStoreTests` exercising acknowledge/clear/round-trip directly — small file, big debugging payoff.\n\n**m3. ZIP extractor in `USDAFoodItemModel.swift` is hand-rolled.** The custom DEFLATE-aware central-directory walker (lines ~164-263) is impressive and tested, but it's now a foundation chunk that has nothing to do with food. Either move to a `Compression/` helper file (so future contributors don't think USDA owns ZIP parsing) or replace with `Compression`/`AppleArchive` framework if it covers your subset. Cosmetic.\n\n**m4. Spec markers landed correctly** (§8 preamble, §7.1.1 implementation markers) — good. Minor: the §7.1.1 markers say \"(implemented)\" without a date or goal reference, so a future agent can't tell which goal landed which model. Worth a one-time sweep adding \"(implemented in goal N)\" tags.\n\n---\n\n### Did it solve the intended problem?\n\n**Theme A (watchOS): structurally yes, ergonomically not yet.** The watch app builds, the WC sync round-trip works as a fixture, the shared module is clean, and the importer is mostly idempotent. But (a) the smoke evidence doesn't include a real-tap session, (b) HR thresholds are frozen for one user, and (c) RMSSD is dormant. None of these block the device-validation pass the author intends to do post-merge — they just need to be tracked as the gating list for \"Phase 4 ready.\" ADR-0021's \"we tried, here's what we found, stay on SDNN until device validation\" is exactly the right shape.\n\n**Theme B: half-done in two specific ways.**\n- Observer/anchor: the implementation is solid (Spezi pattern adapted correctly, ref-counting clean, tests good), but it doesn't actually replace the poll. Until consumers stop calling `thirtyDaySummary`, the observer is decorative. This is the single biggest \"the goal contract said replace, the code added\" discrepancy.\n- Anomaly history: schema, persistence from both services, dashboard surface — all real. Cold-start rule is the missing safety net. UI is generic where the contract asked for named-Signal patterns.\n\n**Sleep-onset SD and FNDDS download are genuinely well done** — three-state-correct, deterministic-override threaded through the weekly review, FNDDS importer handles the real ~7k-row archive with a ZIP reader and idempotent skip, fallback path intact, tests comprehensive.\n\n**Recommended cleanup before merge** (in this order):\n1. C1 — revert the skill commit, gitignore the directories. Pure hygiene.\n2. C3 — gate anomaly persistence by history depth. ~30 lines + one test. Without this the UI lies on day 1.\n3. C2 — fold the observer in as the steady-state path; keep poll as cold-start fallback. ~50 lines spanning provider + service.\n4. M1 — push maxHR to the watch via WC application context. ~40 lines.\n5. M2 — either add a real-UI Swift Testing pass or rephrase the handoff smoke claim.\n6. The rest are M-tier and can land in goal 4 polish.\n\nAfter (1)–(5) this branch is mergeable as a real Phase 4 + 0–3 hardening cut. Without them the live AI experience on a fresh device will fabricate trends, the watch will use the wrong HR bands, and the repo will carry a 24k-line skill snapshot.","Go ahead and implement a couple of follow-up commits that apply the suggested fixes.\n\nRegarding the skill docs:\n1. For C1, do not revert it. I want to keep this commit because I am okay with including the skills files directly on this branch. Do not do anything for C1.\n2. For the others, implement the appropriate fixes as you discovered.\n\nDon't forget to update the relevant change handoff or other relevant documents as you go through. Focus on describing the latest states; there is no need to include any changelog-style wording."],"019e0e8e-0022-7a82-9c88-cf277141e72c":["/goal \n\n# Goal 4: ship Phases 5 + 6, close Goal 3 residuals\n\nThis is goal 4 of the HealthCoach implementation. Goals 1–3 took the iOS+watchOS app from skeleton through a functional Phase 0–4 build with live AI, training/readiness pipeline, watchOS logging, HK observer hardening, FNDDS download, anomaly history, and sleep-onset SD. This goal finishes the spec roadmap (Phases 5 + 6) and closes the residuals from goal 3 plus two long-deferred §9 open questions.\n\nYou have already built and deepened this codebase across three prior goals. The required reading list below is short for that reason. Refresh the parts that matter for this goal, then start.\n\n\n---\n\n## Why this scope\n\nTwo things are true after goal 3:\n\n- The spec has two phases left and only two: **Phase 5** (smart scale integration, after the London move) and **Phase 6** (Transition Mode UI + active-Goal switching UI). Both are user-visible features. Without Phase 6, the user can declare a Goal but cannot pause it, switch to another, or mark it achieved — the four-state machine in `GoalModel` is dead in the UI. Without Transition Mode, a six-week deload while moving cities is indistinguishable from a sustained motivation drop, and the AI will misinterpret it.\n- Goal 3 left a small but specific residual list: a one-line dashboard cache bug, an RMSSD path that compiles but is never invoked, a watch-importer merge rule that exists in an ADR but not in code, and a smoke claim that conflated a fixture path with real-UI taps. Plus two §9 open questions (Registered Meal 6-month decay, Week-6 onboarding self-attest) that have been deferred since Phase 0–3 design and are now cheap to land.\n\nAfter this goal the spec is feature-complete and the watchOS app reaches its first honest \"yes the user can use it on a real watch\" cut.\n\n## Objective and stopping condition\n\nTwo themes. Both required for stopping.\n\n**Theme A — Phases 5 + 6 (finish the spec):**\n\n*Phase 5 — smart scale integration:*\n- Verify the existing HK BodyMass observer correctly ingests scale-pushed `HKQuantitySample` writes (Withings Body+, Eufy, Apple Health manual entry — all are HK BodyMass writers). No new sensor seam needed; the `HealthDataProviding` + observer path from ADR-0019 already covers this. Add a test fixture that writes a BodyMass sample through the HK store seam and asserts it lands in `DailySummaryModel.bodyMassKG`.\n- Body-mass smoothing UI on the dashboard. Spec §3.3 calls out trend display; the current UI shows a daily bar. Add a 7-day rolling mean overlay, with the three-state convention preserved (omit when < 7 days of data; never collapse missing into zero). One ADR documenting the smoothing choice.\n\n*Phase 6 — Transition Mode + Goal switching:*\n- **Transition Mode toggle UI.** A single tap-to-enter modal with a reason picker (`move | travel | illness | renovation | deadline_crunch` — match the §6.6 framings). Persistent dashboard banner while active, showing reason + entry date. Manual exit only — the AI never auto-exits per §6.6.\n- **Transition Mode state persistence.** New `TransitionModeStateModel` with `isActive`, `reason`, `enteredAt`, `exitedAt?`, `notes?`. Flows into the daily push and weekly review prompt payloads as a top-level boolean + reason; the prompt body must respect §6.6's table (frequency 2×/week, minimum-effective-dose volume, soft protein push, maintenance calories, \"expected during transition\" framing rather than \"concern\"). Pin the prompt-version bump in an ADR.\n- **Weekly review respects Transition Mode.** During Transition Mode, the `WeeklyReviewService` emits a 2-line summary shape (one line: what got done; one line: reminder for next week). Either a separate prompt version or a flag on the existing one — your call from first principles, document the decision in an ADR.\n- **Goal pause/switch/achieve UI.** A Goals tab (or section) listing the active Goal plus paused/achieved/abandoned history. Actions: `Pause active Goal`, `Switch to another Goal` (paused or new), `Mark achieved`, `Mark abandoned`. The single-active-Goal cap from ADR-0001 is preserved — switching atomically pauses the current active Goal and activates the chosen one.\n- **Weekly review's `active_goal_status` block surfaces.** Spec §6.5 emits `should_pause_or_abandon` as a boolean on the weekly review JSON. Surface it as an actionable card in the weekly review UI: \"AI suggests pausing this Goal\" → tap to open the pause flow.\n\n**Theme B — Goal 3 residuals + deferred §9 items:**\n\n*Goal 3 residuals (sized in the goal-3 review):*\n- **C2 dashboard cache bug.** `ContentView.swift` passes `recentDailySummaries` (last 14 days) into `model.loadCached(summaries:)`, which builds a 30-day window. Days 15–30 fall through as `.noData` once the user has any history. Pass the unfiltered `dailySummaries` query (or have `loadCached` slice the last 30 itself). One-line code fix; one test asserting the dashboard renders all 30 days when 30 rows exist.\n- **M3 RMSSD wiring or removal.** `HealthCoachShared/HRVMetrics.swift` computes RMSSD correctly from beat-time arrays. `WatchHealthKitModel.rmssdFromMostRecentHeartbeatSeries()` exists. Neither is invoked by the session lifecycle. Either (a) wire it into `WatchSessionView.endSession` so RMSSD is captured at session end and threaded through `WatchSessionDraft` → `WatchWorkoutEnvelope` → `WorkoutSessionModel.rmssdMS?`, or (b) delete the watch-side method and keep only the math + tests in shared until a follow-on goal commits. Pick one and commit; do not leave it half-built.\n- **M4 watch importer last-writer-wins.** ADR-0020 specifies last-writer-wins by `updatedAt` for session fields and merge-by-`id` for hard sets. The importer at `WatchWorkoutImporter.swift` re-inserts the parent `WorkoutSessionModel` without applying the rule. Implement the merge on the session row; add a test that imports the same envelope twice with mutated `durationMinutes` and asserts the merge.\n- **M2 real-tap watch UI evidence.** The goal-3 smoke claim was driven by a `--hc-auto-watch-session` launch-arg fixture, not real UI taps. Either add a `@MainActor` Swift Testing test that exercises `WatchSessionView`'s view-model state transitions through the real `logSet`/`endSession` paths and asserts the resulting envelope, or honestly downgrade the handoff smoke claim to \"fixture-driven; real-tap path verified post-merge on device.\" Don't conflate the two.\n\n*Long-deferred §9 open questions:*\n- **Registered Meal 6-month decay.** Spec §5.7 mentions a one-time prompt when a Registered Meal is unused for 6 months. Implement: track `lastUsedAt` on `RegisteredMealModel` (already present?), add a \"stale meals\" surface to the food UI that lists meals unused > 6 months with `Keep | Archive` actions. One ADR pinning the threshold (6 months as spec states, or different). Don't auto-archive.\n- **Week-6 onboarding self-attest checkpoint.** Spec §4.0 closes Onboarding at week 6 conditional on the user self-attesting form is OK on free weights. Add a checkpoint card that appears at week 6 of the active Onboarding Training context with three actions: `Continue to PPLUL | Extend onboarding 2 weeks | Switch approach`. Persist the user's choice and update `UserProfileModel.trainingHistory` or a new `TrainingContextModel` field accordingly. One ADR.\n\n**Stopping condition (all four):**\n\n1. Theme A acceptance above is satisfied — verified through tests + simulator launch where you can: enter Transition Mode, see the banner, run a daily coach pass that emits Transition-Mode-aware output, exit Transition Mode; pause the active Goal, switch to a paused one, mark a Goal achieved.\n2. Theme B acceptance above is satisfied — verified through unit + SwiftData integration tests for each numbered residual.\n3. `xbuild` clean for both iOS and watchOS schemes; `xtest` green; both simulators launched.\n4. ADRs and per-theme handoff docs committed; branch pushed; **do not merge to main.**\n\n## Branch\n\n`codex/goal-4` off `main` (goal 3 was merged; main is at `b863df1`).\n\n---\n\n## Architectural premise (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\n- Single user, two devices (iPhone + Apple Watch). No backend.\n- Claude API direct from device — only iPhone runs the coach loop.\n- Health data stays on device. Only summaries leave the device.\n- iOS 26.4 + watchOS 26.x deployment, Swift 6.0, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency.\n\n## Personal-health invariants (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\nThese shape every line you write — code, prompts, UI copy, test fixtures, seed data:\n\n- `§6.7` rules 5/8/9: no medical advice, no chronotype-shift suggestions, no \"don't eat X\" framings, no chicken-breast recommendations.\n- `§4.7` red lines (RED-S, OTS) and `§4.2` deficit caps stay silent — they shape proposals, not user-visible alerts. User-visible signals go through `§6.3` Anomalies only. **Transition Mode does not relax red lines** — the deficit cap and pre-planned-deload prohibition still apply during transition. Only the *recommendations* and *failure-framing* shift, never the safety floor.\n- `§2.1` + `PROFILE.md` are facts. Don't invent.\n- Three-state missing-data convention from `§6.4`: omit / `\"no data\"` / `0`. Never collapse missing into zero. The new 7-day weight smoothing uses this convention.\n- §6.6 says **the AI never auto-exits Transition Mode**. UI must enforce manual-exit-only.\n\n## Decision freedom (same as prior goals)\n\nWide. SwiftData additions, UI shapes, prompt-version strategy for Transition Mode, ADR placement — your call from first principles within the architectural premise. Spec patches allowed for narrow gaps with `(YYYY-MM-DD: pinned during Goal 4 implementation)` marker. Glossary changes allowed if you sweep `CONTEXT.md` references and add a \"Resolved YYYY-MM-DD\" line. Stop only when a non-negotiable conflicts genuinely with what you'd need to do.\n\nThe Transition Mode prompt strategy (separate prompt version vs flag on existing one) is the highest-leverage decision this goal. Pick one and commit; don't hedge.\n\n---\n\n## Required reading\n\nSkim, don't re-read full:\n\n- `docs/handoff/goal-3-theme-a-watchos.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-3-theme-b-production-hardening.md` — most recent state-of-the-world.\n- `docs/spec-v1.md`: `§3.2` (Goal struct + status), `§3.3` (active-goal progress display + weight trend), `§4.0` (Onboarding Training context — for the week-6 checkpoint), `§5.7` (Registered Meal decay note), `§6.5` (`active_goal_status.should_pause_or_abandon`), `§6.6` (Transition Mode — the load-bearing section), `§6.7` (hard constraints — red lines do not relax in transition), `§8` Phase 5+6 rows.\n- `docs/adr/0001` (single active Goal — the cap you're preserving), `0007` (Anthropic client and prompt versioning — for the Transition prompt decision), `0015` (deterministic weekly facts — Transition's 2-line review still factual-deterministic where applicable), `0019` (HK observer — smart scale rides this seam), `0020` (WC sync — for M4), `0021` (RMSSD feasibility — for M3).\n- No new OSS reference is load-bearing this goal. If anything, `docs/oss-reference/04-coach-watts.md` for \"active goal lifecycle as state machine\" framing — the basic structure of pause-active-resume isn't novel.\n\nIf something feels uncertain mid-implementation, re-read the relevant spec section before guessing.\n\n## Skills\n\nSame set as prior goals. At the start of each theme, write a short \"what applies here\" note in working scratch (don't commit):\n\n- `tdd` — red-green-refactor per slice.\n- `swift-testing-pro` — Swift Testing patterns; Goal-switch state-machine transitions want @MainActor SwiftData round-trip tests.\n- `swiftui-pro` — load-bearing this goal. Transition Mode banner, modal, reason picker; Goals list with status sections; weekly-review action card; week-6 checkpoint card; stale-meals surface. Match the existing dashboard idiom (`Form` + `Section` + `LabeledContent`) — don't re-skin.\n- `improve-codebase-architecture` — Goal switching is a state machine; Transition Mode is a state machine; prompt-version selection is a strategy. Three small, narrow seams beat one bloated `GoalCoordinator` that knows everything.\n- `claude-api` — light-touch this goal. The only real change is the Transition-Mode prompt path; if you take the \"separate prompt version\" route, prompt caching needs to remain effective on whichever variant the user is in. Don't break the cache hit rate by making the system block variable.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow (same as prior goals)\n\n1. **Branch.** `codex/goal-4`. Commit per slice. **Do not merge to main.**\n2. **Slice.** Vertical slices with a clear acceptance condition each. TDD per slice. `xbuild` clean (both schemes) and `xtest` green before each commit.\n3. **ADRs for keystone decisions.** Same format as prior ADRs. Examples worth an ADR this goal:\n   - Transition Mode state model + UI shape + manual-exit-only rule.\n   - Transition Mode prompt strategy (separate version vs flag) + 2-line weekly-review shape.\n   - Goal pause/switch/achieve flow + atomic-switch invariant + UI shape.\n   - Weight smoothing window + trend display rules.\n   - Registered Meal decay threshold + archive UX.\n   - Week-6 onboarding self-attest model + persistence.\n   - Watch session merge rule (resolves M4 with code, not just doc).\n4. **Per-theme handoff.** At end of each theme, write `docs/handoff/goal-4-theme-a-phases-5-6.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-4-theme-b-residuals.md`. Don't duplicate code, ADR text, or commit messages — reference by path/SHA. Include only: what's verified vs pending, spec gaps you hit and how resolved, glossary near-misses, what the next loop should know, which skills + OSS sections you actually used (one line each: kept / skipped / why).\n5. **Spec edits** during the run: allowed for narrow gaps with date-stamped marker. STOP and surface in the handoff for genuine non-negotiable conflicts.\n\n## API key handling\n\nUnchanged from goal 2. All tests use `MockKeyProvider`; no network calls in tests. Transition Mode's prompt path goes through the same Keychain-backed live client; if you bump the prompt version, the existing usage-token logging in `DailyPushLogModel`/`WeeklyReviewLogModel` should keep working without changes.\n\n## Build commands\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild` | Build for the iPhone 17 simulator (default scheme `HealthCoach`). |\n| `xbuild -s HealthCoachWatch` | Build the watchOS scheme. |\n| `xtest` | Run all iOS tests. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>` | Narrow to one suite. |\n| `XCODE_DESTINATION='platform=watchOS Simulator,name=Apple Watch Series 11 (46mm)' xtest` | Run tests on the watchOS simulator. |\n| `xtests-list` | List test classes. |\n\nAdding/removing source files inside the synchronized roots does **not** require pbxproj edits. The watchOS target itself already exists from goal 3.\n\n## Polish to fold in\n\nThese are doc-quality and small-cleanup items the next implementer (you) will benefit from. Do them on a quiet slice; don't accumulate as a separate phase:\n\n- **`CONTEXT.md`** — add a canonical entry for **Transition Mode** (the §6.6 user-declared, manual-exit-only state with auto-adjusted dimensions per the §6.6 table). Resolved 2026-MM-DD line at the bottom.\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §8** — update the \"Status\" preamble after this goal lands to reflect Phase 5 + Phase 6 complete.\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §7.1.1** — mark new Phase 5/6 SwiftData models (`TransitionModeStateModel`, anything for the week-6 checkpoint, `RegisteredMealModel.lastUsedAt` if added) as `(implemented in goal 4)`. Sweep the existing markers to add their goal numbers if missing — minor, do at end.\n- **m3 (cosmetic, from goal-3 review):** the hand-rolled DEFLATE-aware ZIP extractor in `USDAFoodItemModel.swift` should live in a `Compression/` helper file, not in the food domain. Move it. No behavior change.\n- **m4 (cosmetic, from goal-3 review):** §7.1.1 implementation markers currently say `(implemented)` without a goal reference. Sweep to add `(implemented in goal N)` so future agents can trace which goal landed which model.\n\n## Suggested first commit\n\nA short `docs/handoff/goal-4-plan.md` with your slice plan for both themes, the ADRs you anticipate, the Transition Mode prompt strategy you're leaning toward (with one-paragraph rationale), and which §9 open questions you're closing vs deferring. Optional but useful — same as prior first commits.\n\n---\n\nThat's the contract. Skim the required reading, plan the themes, then start with whichever theme unblocks the other. Theme A is the new product surface; Theme B is the cleanup. Either order works — pick by what's heavier on your decision freedom.\n"],"019e0e90-2a94-77d1-8f91-4ea4c5573485":["/goal \n\n# Goal 4: ship Phases 5 + 6, close Goal 3 residuals\n\nThis is goal 4 of the HealthCoach implementation. Goals 1–3 took the iOS+watchOS app from skeleton through a functional Phase 0–4 build with live AI, training/readiness pipeline, watchOS logging, HK observer hardening, FNDDS download, anomaly history, and sleep-onset SD. This goal finishes the spec roadmap (Phases 5 + 6) and closes the residuals from goal 3 plus two long-deferred §9 open questions.\n\nYou have already built and deepened this codebase across three prior goals. The required reading list below is short for that reason. Refresh the parts that matter for this goal, then start.\n\n\n---\n\n## Why this scope\n\nTwo things are true after goal 3:\n\n- The spec has two phases left and only two: **Phase 5** (smart scale integration, after the London move) and **Phase 6** (Transition Mode UI + active-Goal switching UI). Both are user-visible features. Without Phase 6, the user can declare a Goal but cannot pause it, switch to another, or mark it achieved — the four-state machine in `GoalModel` is dead in the UI. Without Transition Mode, a six-week deload while moving cities is indistinguishable from a sustained motivation drop, and the AI will misinterpret it.\n- Goal 3 left a small but specific residual list: a one-line dashboard cache bug, an RMSSD path that compiles but is never invoked, a watch-importer merge rule that exists in an ADR but not in code, and a smoke claim that conflated a fixture path with real-UI taps. Plus two §9 open questions (Registered Meal 6-month decay, Week-6 onboarding self-attest) that have been deferred since Phase 0–3 design and are now cheap to land.\n\nAfter this goal the spec is feature-complete and the watchOS app reaches its first honest \"yes the user can use it on a real watch\" cut.\n\n## Objective and stopping condition\n\nTwo themes. Both required for stopping.\n\n**Theme A — Phases 5 + 6 (finish the spec):**\n\n*Phase 5 — smart scale integration:*\n- Verify the existing HK BodyMass observer correctly ingests scale-pushed `HKQuantitySample` writes (Withings Body+, Eufy, Apple Health manual entry — all are HK BodyMass writers). No new sensor seam needed; the `HealthDataProviding` + observer path from ADR-0019 already covers this. Add a test fixture that writes a BodyMass sample through the HK store seam and asserts it lands in `DailySummaryModel.bodyMassKG`.\n- Body-mass smoothing UI on the dashboard. Spec §3.3 calls out trend display; the current UI shows a daily bar. Add a 7-day rolling mean overlay, with the three-state convention preserved (omit when < 7 days of data; never collapse missing into zero). One ADR documenting the smoothing choice.\n\n*Phase 6 — Transition Mode + Goal switching:*\n- **Transition Mode toggle UI.** A single tap-to-enter modal with a reason picker (`move | travel | illness | renovation | deadline_crunch` — match the §6.6 framings). Persistent dashboard banner while active, showing reason + entry date. Manual exit only — the AI never auto-exits per §6.6.\n- **Transition Mode state persistence.** New `TransitionModeStateModel` with `isActive`, `reason`, `enteredAt`, `exitedAt?`, `notes?`. Flows into the daily push and weekly review prompt payloads as a top-level boolean + reason; the prompt body must respect §6.6's table (frequency 2×/week, minimum-effective-dose volume, soft protein push, maintenance calories, \"expected during transition\" framing rather than \"concern\"). Pin the prompt-version bump in an ADR.\n- **Weekly review respects Transition Mode.** During Transition Mode, the `WeeklyReviewService` emits a 2-line summary shape (one line: what got done; one line: reminder for next week). Either a separate prompt version or a flag on the existing one — your call from first principles, document the decision in an ADR.\n- **Goal pause/switch/achieve UI.** A Goals tab (or section) listing the active Goal plus paused/achieved/abandoned history. Actions: `Pause active Goal`, `Switch to another Goal` (paused or new), `Mark achieved`, `Mark abandoned`. The single-active-Goal cap from ADR-0001 is preserved — switching atomically pauses the current active Goal and activates the chosen one.\n- **Weekly review's `active_goal_status` block surfaces.** Spec §6.5 emits `should_pause_or_abandon` as a boolean on the weekly review JSON. Surface it as an actionable card in the weekly review UI: \"AI suggests pausing this Goal\" → tap to open the pause flow.\n\n**Theme B — Goal 3 residuals + deferred §9 items:**\n\n*Goal 3 residuals (sized in the goal-3 review):*\n- **C2 dashboard cache bug.** `ContentView.swift` passes `recentDailySummaries` (last 14 days) into `model.loadCached(summaries:)`, which builds a 30-day window. Days 15–30 fall through as `.noData` once the user has any history. Pass the unfiltered `dailySummaries` query (or have `loadCached` slice the last 30 itself). One-line code fix; one test asserting the dashboard renders all 30 days when 30 rows exist.\n- **M3 RMSSD wiring or removal.** `HealthCoachShared/HRVMetrics.swift` computes RMSSD correctly from beat-time arrays. `WatchHealthKitModel.rmssdFromMostRecentHeartbeatSeries()` exists. Neither is invoked by the session lifecycle. Either (a) wire it into `WatchSessionView.endSession` so RMSSD is captured at session end and threaded through `WatchSessionDraft` → `WatchWorkoutEnvelope` → `WorkoutSessionModel.rmssdMS?`, or (b) delete the watch-side method and keep only the math + tests in shared until a follow-on goal commits. Pick one and commit; do not leave it half-built.\n- **M4 watch importer last-writer-wins.** ADR-0020 specifies last-writer-wins by `updatedAt` for session fields and merge-by-`id` for hard sets. The importer at `WatchWorkoutImporter.swift` re-inserts the parent `WorkoutSessionModel` without applying the rule. Implement the merge on the session row; add a test that imports the same envelope twice with mutated `durationMinutes` and asserts the merge.\n- **M2 real-tap watch UI evidence.** The goal-3 smoke claim was driven by a `--hc-auto-watch-session` launch-arg fixture, not real UI taps. Either add a `@MainActor` Swift Testing test that exercises `WatchSessionView`'s view-model state transitions through the real `logSet`/`endSession` paths and asserts the resulting envelope, or honestly downgrade the handoff smoke claim to \"fixture-driven; real-tap path verified post-merge on device.\" Don't conflate the two.\n\n*Long-deferred §9 open questions:*\n- **Registered Meal 6-month decay.** Spec §5.7 mentions a one-time prompt when a Registered Meal is unused for 6 months. Implement: track `lastUsedAt` on `RegisteredMealModel` (already present?), add a \"stale meals\" surface to the food UI that lists meals unused > 6 months with `Keep | Archive` actions. One ADR pinning the threshold (6 months as spec states, or different). Don't auto-archive.\n- **Week-6 onboarding self-attest checkpoint.** Spec §4.0 closes Onboarding at week 6 conditional on the user self-attesting form is OK on free weights. Add a checkpoint card that appears at week 6 of the active Onboarding Training context with three actions: `Continue to PPLUL | Extend onboarding 2 weeks | Switch approach`. Persist the user's choice and update `UserProfileModel.trainingHistory` or a new `TrainingContextModel` field accordingly. One ADR.\n\n**Stopping condition (all four):**\n\n1. Theme A acceptance above is satisfied — verified through tests + simulator launch where you can: enter Transition Mode, see the banner, run a daily coach pass that emits Transition-Mode-aware output, exit Transition Mode; pause the active Goal, switch to a paused one, mark a Goal achieved.\n2. Theme B acceptance above is satisfied — verified through unit + SwiftData integration tests for each numbered residual.\n3. `xbuild` clean for both iOS and watchOS schemes; `xtest` green; both simulators launched.\n4. ADRs and per-theme handoff docs committed; branch pushed; **do not merge to main.**\n\n## Branch\n\n`codex/goal-4` off `main` (goal 3 was merged; main is at `b863df1`).\n\n---\n\n## Architectural premise (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\n- Single user, two devices (iPhone + Apple Watch). No backend.\n- Claude API direct from device — only iPhone runs the coach loop.\n- Health data stays on device. Only summaries leave the device.\n- iOS 26.4 + watchOS 26.x deployment, Swift 6.0, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency.\n\n## Personal-health invariants (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\nThese shape every line you write — code, prompts, UI copy, test fixtures, seed data:\n\n- `§6.7` rules 5/8/9: no medical advice, no chronotype-shift suggestions, no \"don't eat X\" framings, no chicken-breast recommendations.\n- `§4.7` red lines (RED-S, OTS) and `§4.2` deficit caps stay silent — they shape proposals, not user-visible alerts. User-visible signals go through `§6.3` Anomalies only. **Transition Mode does not relax red lines** — the deficit cap and pre-planned-deload prohibition still apply during transition. Only the *recommendations* and *failure-framing* shift, never the safety floor.\n- `§2.1` + `PROFILE.md` are facts. Don't invent.\n- Three-state missing-data convention from `§6.4`: omit / `\"no data\"` / `0`. Never collapse missing into zero. The new 7-day weight smoothing uses this convention.\n- §6.6 says **the AI never auto-exits Transition Mode**. UI must enforce manual-exit-only.\n\n## Decision freedom (same as prior goals)\n\nWide. SwiftData additions, UI shapes, prompt-version strategy for Transition Mode, ADR placement — your call from first principles within the architectural premise. Spec patches allowed for narrow gaps with `(YYYY-MM-DD: pinned during Goal 4 implementation)` marker. Glossary changes allowed if you sweep `CONTEXT.md` references and add a \"Resolved YYYY-MM-DD\" line. Stop only when a non-negotiable conflicts genuinely with what you'd need to do.\n\nThe Transition Mode prompt strategy (separate prompt version vs flag on existing one) is the highest-leverage decision this goal. Pick one and commit; don't hedge.\n\n---\n\n## Required reading\n\nSkim, don't re-read full:\n\n- `docs/handoff/goal-3-theme-a-watchos.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-3-theme-b-production-hardening.md` — most recent state-of-the-world.\n- `docs/spec-v1.md`: `§3.2` (Goal struct + status), `§3.3` (active-goal progress display + weight trend), `§4.0` (Onboarding Training context — for the week-6 checkpoint), `§5.7` (Registered Meal decay note), `§6.5` (`active_goal_status.should_pause_or_abandon`), `§6.6` (Transition Mode — the load-bearing section), `§6.7` (hard constraints — red lines do not relax in transition), `§8` Phase 5+6 rows.\n- `docs/adr/0001` (single active Goal — the cap you're preserving), `0007` (Anthropic client and prompt versioning — for the Transition prompt decision), `0015` (deterministic weekly facts — Transition's 2-line review still factual-deterministic where applicable), `0019` (HK observer — smart scale rides this seam), `0020` (WC sync — for M4), `0021` (RMSSD feasibility — for M3).\n- No new OSS reference is load-bearing this goal. If anything, `docs/oss-reference/04-coach-watts.md` for \"active goal lifecycle as state machine\" framing — the basic structure of pause-active-resume isn't novel.\n\nIf something feels uncertain mid-implementation, re-read the relevant spec section before guessing.\n\n## Skills\n\nSame set as prior goals. At the start of each theme, write a short \"what applies here\" note in working scratch (don't commit):\n\n- `tdd` — red-green-refactor per slice.\n- `swift-testing-pro` — Swift Testing patterns; Goal-switch state-machine transitions want @MainActor SwiftData round-trip tests.\n- `swiftui-pro` — load-bearing this goal. Transition Mode banner, modal, reason picker; Goals list with status sections; weekly-review action card; week-6 checkpoint card; stale-meals surface. Match the existing dashboard idiom (`Form` + `Section` + `LabeledContent`) — don't re-skin.\n- `improve-codebase-architecture` — Goal switching is a state machine; Transition Mode is a state machine; prompt-version selection is a strategy. Three small, narrow seams beat one bloated `GoalCoordinator` that knows everything.\n- `claude-api` — light-touch this goal. The only real change is the Transition-Mode prompt path; if you take the \"separate prompt version\" route, prompt caching needs to remain effective on whichever variant the user is in. Don't break the cache hit rate by making the system block variable.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow (same as prior goals)\n\n1. **Branch.** `codex/goal-4`. Commit per slice. **Do not merge to main.**\n2. **Slice.** Vertical slices with a clear acceptance condition each. TDD per slice. `xbuild` clean (both schemes) and `xtest` green before each commit.\n3. **ADRs for keystone decisions.** Same format as prior ADRs. Examples worth an ADR this goal:\n   - Transition Mode state model + UI shape + manual-exit-only rule.\n   - Transition Mode prompt strategy (separate version vs flag) + 2-line weekly-review shape.\n   - Goal pause/switch/achieve flow + atomic-switch invariant + UI shape.\n   - Weight smoothing window + trend display rules.\n   - Registered Meal decay threshold + archive UX.\n   - Week-6 onboarding self-attest model + persistence.\n   - Watch session merge rule (resolves M4 with code, not just doc).\n4. **Per-theme handoff.** At end of each theme, write `docs/handoff/goal-4-theme-a-phases-5-6.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-4-theme-b-residuals.md`. Don't duplicate code, ADR text, or commit messages — reference by path/SHA. Include only: what's verified vs pending, spec gaps you hit and how resolved, glossary near-misses, what the next loop should know, which skills + OSS sections you actually used (one line each: kept / skipped / why).\n5. **Spec edits** during the run: allowed for narrow gaps with date-stamped marker. STOP and surface in the handoff for genuine non-negotiable conflicts.\n\n## API key handling\n\nUnchanged from goal 2. All tests use `MockKeyProvider`; no network calls in tests. Transition Mode's prompt path goes through the same Keychain-backed live client; if you bump the prompt version, the existing usage-token logging in `DailyPushLogModel`/`WeeklyReviewLogModel` should keep working without changes.\n\n## Build commands\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild` | Build for the iPhone 17 simulator (default scheme `HealthCoach`). |\n| `xbuild -s HealthCoachWatch` | Build the watchOS scheme. |\n| `xtest` | Run all iOS tests. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>` | Narrow to one suite. |\n| `XCODE_DESTINATION='platform=watchOS Simulator,name=Apple Watch Series 11 (46mm)' xtest` | Run tests on the watchOS simulator. |\n| `xtests-list` | List test classes. |\n\nAdding/removing source files inside the synchronized roots does **not** require pbxproj edits. The watchOS target itself already exists from goal 3.\n\n## Polish to fold in\n\nThese are doc-quality and small-cleanup items the next implementer (you) will benefit from. Do them on a quiet slice; don't accumulate as a separate phase:\n\n- **`CONTEXT.md`** — add a canonical entry for **Transition Mode** (the §6.6 user-declared, manual-exit-only state with auto-adjusted dimensions per the §6.6 table). Resolved 2026-MM-DD line at the bottom.\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §8** — update the \"Status\" preamble after this goal lands to reflect Phase 5 + Phase 6 complete.\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §7.1.1** — mark new Phase 5/6 SwiftData models (`TransitionModeStateModel`, anything for the week-6 checkpoint, `RegisteredMealModel.lastUsedAt` if added) as `(implemented in goal 4)`. Sweep the existing markers to add their goal numbers if missing — minor, do at end.\n- **m3 (cosmetic, from goal-3 review):** the hand-rolled DEFLATE-aware ZIP extractor in `USDAFoodItemModel.swift` should live in a `Compression/` helper file, not in the food domain. Move it. No behavior change.\n- **m4 (cosmetic, from goal-3 review):** §7.1.1 implementation markers currently say `(implemented)` without a goal reference. Sweep to add `(implemented in goal N)` so future agents can trace which goal landed which model.\n\n## Suggested first commit\n\nA short `docs/handoff/goal-4-plan.md` with your slice plan for both themes, the ADRs you anticipate, the Transition Mode prompt strategy you're leaning toward (with one-paragraph rationale), and which §9 open questions you're closing vs deferring. Optional but useful — same as prior first commits.\n\n---\n\nThat's the contract. Skim the required reading, plan the themes, then start with whichever theme unblocks the other. Theme A is the new product surface; Theme B is the cleanup. Either order works — pick by what's heavier on your decision freedom.\n","A senior engineer reviewed your changes and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct.\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\n\nVerified the three highest-leverage claims. Two §9 features ship as dead or half-built code despite passing tests and handoffs claiming completion.\n\n## Goal 4 review\n\nCompact run — single commit, ~1100 LoC, 1821s. Architecture mostly clean, but the §9 deferred items both have correctness gaps that the test suite doesn't catch because the tests seed state the production app never creates. Two real critical issues; the rest is moderate UX polish.\n\n---\n\n### Critical\n\n**C1. Week-6 onboarding checkpoint is dead code in production.**\n- Where: `TrainingLogView.swift:65-75` reads `TrainingContextModel` rows; `TrainingContextStore` has create/update methods. **But no production code path inserts a `TrainingContextModel`.** Only the test does (`TrainingContextStoreTests.swift:17`). Verified by `grep -rn \"TrainingContextModel(\" HealthCoach/` — zero hits in production code.\n- Why: `BaselineSeeder` (first-launch baseline) doesn't create one; nothing in the workout-logging flow does either. The `onboardingCheckpoint` computed property always returns nil for real users, so the Week-6 card never appears.\n- Fix: in `BaselineSeeder` (or wherever the first-launch baseline persists `UserProfileModel`), also insert `TrainingContextModel(context: .onboarding, startedAt: .now)`. Alternatively, derive `startedAt` from `UserProfileModel.createdAt` at read time and stop modeling it as a separate row — but the row already exists with the right shape, so just create one. Add a test seeding only the user profile (no TrainingContextModel) and asserting the checkpoint card surfaces after week 6.\n\n**C2. `RegisteredMealModel.lastEaten` is never written.**\n- Where: `FoodModels.swift:35` declares `var lastEaten: Date?`. Grepping the codebase: **only readers exist** (`StaleRegisteredMealStore.swift:13-14`, `FoodLoggingView.swift:46`). Nothing in the meal-logging path updates it. `FoodPhotoAnalysis.swift:70-72` creates `MealEntryModel` with `registeredMealID: nil` (Tier 2 path doesn't link to a Registered Meal anyway), and Tier 1 meal-logging UI doesn't exist yet.\n- Why: the spec §5.7 decay rule is \"unused for 6 months\" — usage. The implementation falls back to `createdAt` everywhere, so the stale list shows meals **6 months after calibration regardless of how often they were eaten.** A meal eaten 50 times last week still gets flagged stale on its 6-month calibration anniversary.\n- Fix: at minimum, set `lastEaten = createdAt` at calibration time so the semantics are consistent (currently it's nil → fallback). For the real fix, when Tier 1 meal logging lands, update `lastEaten` on each log. Add a test that creates a meal, ages it past 6 months, \"logs\" it (whatever path the Tier 1 UI uses), and asserts it's no longer in `staleMeals`.\n\n---\n\n### Moderate\n\n**M1. Transition Mode's \"2-line weekly review shape\" relies entirely on the LLM following instructions.**\n- Where: `Prompts/weekly_review_v2.txt` says \"If transition_mode.is_active is true, return a concise two-line review shape in wins/concerns/adjustments.\" The `WeeklyReviewResponse` schema has unbounded `wins: [String]` and `concerns: [String]`. No post-processing in `WeeklyReviewService` truncates output.\n- Why: spec §6.6 specifies the 2-line shape as a behavioral invariant during transition. With prompt-only enforcement, Claude can emit 5 wins and 5 concerns and the schema accepts it; the user sees a full review framed as transition. Tests pass because `MockWeeklyReviewAIClient` happens to emit short arrays.\n- Fix: in `WeeklyReviewService.runWeeklyReview`, after parsing the response, if the input had `transitionMode.isActive == true`, slice `response.wins.prefix(1)` and `response.concerns.prefix(1)` (or similar) before persistence. Add a test with a stub client that returns 5-line wins; assert the persisted JSON has 1-line shape.\n\n**M2. Goal achieved/abandoned items aren't visually distinguished from paused in the Goals list.**\n- Where: `GoalsView.swift` filters paused goals as \"switchable\" but the History section lumps them with achieved/abandoned. Users may expect to tap an `achieved` goal and resume it.\n- Fix: split history into \"Paused\" (tap to switch-to-active) and \"Archived: achieved/abandoned\" (informational only, no actions). One section divider + per-row check on `status`.\n\n**M3. Weekly-review `should_pause_or_abandon` card doesn't deep-link to the right goal.**\n- Where: `ContentView.swift` (around the weekly review section) renders the AI's pause suggestion with a link to `GoalsView`. The link doesn't pass which Goal the suggestion is about. User opens GoalsView and has to find the active Goal manually.\n- Fix: pass the active Goal's `id` through navigation (e.g., `NavigationLink(value: GoalsRoute.suggestPause(activeGoal.id))`) and have `GoalsView` highlight + scroll to that goal. ~30 lines.\n\n**M4. C2 regression test uses exactly 30 rows.**\n- Where: `HealthDashboardViewModelTests.swift` covers the 30-row case but not the >30 case. The original bug was that a 14-day filter was passed; with 30+ rows in SwiftData, the test should verify only the most recent 30 are surfaced (or that the dashboard's window is correctly anchored to today).\n- Fix: add a test inserting 60 rows and asserting the rendered series contains exactly 30 days ending at the current end-date. One test, ~15 lines.\n\n**M5. Workflow regression: single commit, thin ADRs, no slice evidence.**\n- Where: goal contract said \"Commit per slice.\" Branch landed as one `Ship goal 4 roadmap features` commit covering 5 state machines + Phase 5 + 4 residuals + 2 §9 items. ADRs 0022-0026 are 8-13 lines each — substantially shorter than peers (0011: 16, 0019: 23) — and several state *what* was decided without documenting alternatives or the *why* (e.g., 0022 picks 7-day rolling mean without explaining 7 over 14/30; 0025 picks 183-day threshold without rationale; 0023 doesn't address prompt-cache implications even though the contract called this the \"highest-leverage decision\").\n- Why: this is a process concern, not a code bug. But two of the substantive findings above (C1, C2) are exactly the kind of cross-cutting wiring gaps that show up when work isn't sliced — the unit tests pass because they seed the state directly, and the integration gap with the rest of the app stays invisible.\n- Fix: not actionable on this branch, but for future goals, the contract's \"commit per slice\" line should be tighter — maybe require evidence (slice plan in the first commit + slice-named subsequent commits) before claiming completion.\n\n---\n\n### Minor\n\n**m1.** Rapid double-tap on \"Enter Transition Mode\" creates duplicate active sessions. `TransitionModeStore.enter()` doesn't check for an existing active session before insert. Add a guard: `if try current(in: context) != nil { return }`. Or disable the entry button while `enter()` is running.\n\n**m2.** ZIP extractor relocation (m3 from goal-3 review): **confirmed fixed.** `Compression/ZIPJSONExtractor.swift` exists; `USDAFoodItemModel.swift` no longer hand-rolls deflate.\n\n**m3.** M3 RMSSD wiring (path a chosen): captured at session end on watch, threaded through `WatchSessionDraft.finish(rmssdMS:)` → `WatchWorkoutEnvelope.rmssdMS` → `WatchWorkoutImporter` → `WorkoutSessionModel.rmssdMS`. Tests cover the envelope round-trip; live HK query is correctly deferred to device per ADR-0021.\n\n**m4.** M4 importer last-writer-wins: **implemented and tested correctly.** `WatchWorkoutImporter.swift:8-27` fetches existing session by id, applies `envelope.updatedAt >= session.updatedAt` gate before mutating, merges hard sets by id with their own `updatedAt` check. `duplicateEnvelopeMergesSessionAndHardSetsByUpdatedAt` test exercises the path.\n\n**m5.** M2 watch real-tap evidence: handoff honestly defers to physical device. Acceptable per the goal contract's \"downgrade or test\" choice. No new MainActor test added, though — `logSet`/`endSession` button paths are still only smoke-tested via the launch-arg fixture.\n\n**m6.** Prompt cache: v2 prompt files contain both normal and Transition Mode instructions, conditional on the `transition_mode.is_active` flag in the user payload. **System block stays stable across modes** — cache stays warm. ADR-0023 implicitly does this right; could be more explicit about it.\n\n---\n\n### Did it solve the intended problem?\n\n**Theme A — Phase 5:** Yes. BodyMass smoothing is mathematically correct, three-state-respecting, and the existing observer covers smart-scale ingestion (the test in `HealthKitAnchorTests` walks a fake BodyMass sample through the seam).\n\n**Theme A — Phase 6 Transition Mode:** Largely yes. State machine is clean, manual-exit invariant is preserved, prompts route correctly via flag-not-version (cache-friendly). M1 (deterministic 2-line enforcement) is the real gap — without it, the AI is the only thing keeping the contract.\n\n**Theme A — Phase 6 Goal switching:** Yes for the happy path (atomic switch via `GoalStateStore.switchToGoal`, single-active cap preserved). UX polish issues (M2 visual distinction, M3 deep-link) are real but small.\n\n**Theme B — Goal 3 residuals:** Solid. C2, M3, M4 all properly wired with tests. C2's regression test is narrow (M4 above) but the fix itself is correct.\n\n**Theme B — §9 deferred items:** Both half-built. C1 (week-6 checkpoint) ships as dead code because no production path creates the prerequisite SwiftData row. C2 (Registered Meal decay) ships with usage-based semantics decayed to creation-based because `lastEaten` is never written. Both pass tests because tests seed state directly. **These are the genuine \"did the implementation solve the intended problem\" failures.**\n\n---\n\n### Recommended pre-merge fixes (in this order)\n\n1. **C1** — `BaselineSeeder` (or equivalent) creates `TrainingContextModel(context: .onboarding, startedAt: .now)` for new users, plus a \"no row\" → `nil` integration test that rules out the dead-code state. Without this, the entire week-6 checkpoint feature ships disabled.\n2. **C2** — at calibration time, set `lastEaten = createdAt`. If you intend to keep the spec's \"unused\" semantics, file a follow-up issue for the goal that adds Tier 1 meal logging to wire the actual update path.\n3. **M1** — deterministic 2-line slice in `WeeklyReviewService` when `transitionMode.isActive`. ~5 lines + 1 stub-client test.\n4. **M4** — one extra test covering the `>30 rows` dashboard case.\n5. **M2/M3/m1** — UX polish, can land in goal 5 or as drive-bys.\n\nAfter C1 + C2 this branch ships features that actually serve users; without them, two of the three §9-bucket items I called out as candidates in the goal-4 contract are going to confuse the user the first time they hit them.","I think you should implement all with a few follow up commits, but in order alongside wih the priority, dont forget to update the relevant docs or handoffs alongside the way, no changelog style of wording, just describe the currenet state","lets commit the scheme as well"],"019e0ee7-bbc0-7bb0-a3da-1941362de217":["what about now, whats my current page","do you have access to the video url, I assume its a streamed version of something like m3u8","can you try if you can download it via yt-download","no the course does not have official download button\n\ni purchased this course and now I want to download its mp4 videos (all)\n\nso I need a way of pragmatically get a list of videos (in order) and their titles and download them\n\nI can provide some cookies or inspect the networks tab if you want them","ok, but at least you should give me a list of course index with the metadata you described and save it in ~/courses/practical-effect/ folder","in this practical effect dir, can you also write a script (in typescript or python) up to you, that given the course index, creates a folder for each, the folder name should be the kabab style of the lesson title, with the smae nesting of chapters and lessons, e.g. chapter being a parent folder and each lesson being a subfolder inside, the lesson folder should not contains only one file, which is the transcript for that lesson, its html looks like\n\n```\n<div class=\"prose dark:prose-invert prose-hr:my-6 prose-p:my-3 prose-headings:mt-6 prose-headings:mb-3 prose-pre:my-4 prose-ul:my-3 prose-ol:my-3 [&amp;_:not(pre)_code]:before:content-none [&amp;_:not(pre)_code]:after:content-none max-w-none\"><h2>From Data-First to Data-Last</h2>\n<p>So far, we've built a few foundational operators like <code>map</code>, <code>retry</code>, and <code>catchAll</code> that all take a computation and return a new, more powerful computation. This is how we build complex programs: by starting with simple primitives and combining them like LEGOs to build anything we want.</p>\n<p>But we have one problem. As we chain these operations, our code gets messy.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>The \"Inside-Out\" Problem with Data-First APIs</h3>\n<p>Currently, we declare a new variable for each step in our logic:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"hljs language-typescript\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> fetchUserName = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">map</span>(fetchUser, <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-params\">user</span> =&gt;</span> user.<span class=\"hljs-property\">name</span>);\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> withRetry = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">retry</span>(fetchUserName, <span class=\"hljs-number\">3</span>);\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> program = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">catchAll</span>(withRetry, <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> <span class=\"hljs-string\">\"Guest\"</span>);\n</code></pre><p>This is readable, but it creates a lot of intermediate variables. If we try to combine it into a single definition, we get this:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"hljs language-typescript\"><span class=\"hljs-comment\">// Don't do this!</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> program = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">catchAll</span>(\n  <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">retry</span>(\n    <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">map</span>(\n      fetchUser,\n      <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-params\">user</span> =&gt;</span> user.<span class=\"hljs-property\">name</span>\n    ),\n    <span class=\"hljs-number\">3</span>\n  ),\n  <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> <span class=\"hljs-string\">\"Guest\"</span>\n);\n</code></pre><p>This is incredibly hard to read. To understand what's happening, you have to find the innermost function call (<code>map</code>) and read your way out. The flow of data is from the inside out, which is the opposite of how we normally read code, and the nesting only gets worse as you add more steps.</p>\n<p>This happens because all our operators are written in a <strong>data-first</strong> style, where the main piece of data—our <code>computation</code>—is always the first argument.</p>\n<h4>Data-first implementations (no <code>dual</code>)</h4>\n<pre><code class=\"hljs language-typescript\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\">type</span> <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt; = <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> A;\n\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">export</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> map = &lt;A, B&gt;(\n  <span class=\"hljs-attr\">self</span>: <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt;,\n  <span class=\"hljs-attr\">f</span>: <span class=\"hljs-function\">(<span class=\"hljs-params\"><span class=\"hljs-attr\">a</span>: A</span>) =&gt;</span> B,\n): <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;B&gt; =&gt; {\n  <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> a = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">self</span>();\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">f</span>(a);\n  };\n};\n\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">export</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> retry = &lt;A&gt;(\n  <span class=\"hljs-attr\">self</span>: <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt;,\n  <span class=\"hljs-attr\">retries</span>: <span class=\"hljs-built_in\">number</span>,\n): <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt; =&gt; {\n  <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">let</span> <span class=\"hljs-attr\">lastError</span>: <span class=\"hljs-built_in\">unknown</span>;\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">for</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">let</span> i = <span class=\"hljs-number\">0</span>; i &lt; retries; i++) {\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">try</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">self</span>();\n      } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">catch</span> (error) {\n        lastError = error;\n      }\n    }\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">throw</span> lastError;\n  };\n};\n\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">export</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> catchAll = &lt;A, B&gt;(\n  <span class=\"hljs-attr\">self</span>: <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt;,\n  <span class=\"hljs-attr\">handler</span>: <span class=\"hljs-function\">(<span class=\"hljs-params\"><span class=\"hljs-attr\">error</span>: <span class=\"hljs-built_in\">unknown</span></span>) =&gt;</span> B,\n): <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A | B&gt; =&gt; {\n  <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">try</span> {\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">self</span>();\n    } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">catch</span> (error) {\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">handler</span>(error);\n    }\n  };\n};\n</code></pre><hr>\n<h3>The Alternative: Data-Last APIs</h3>\n<p>What if we flipped the order? What if the computation we're operating on always came <em>last</em>? This is known as a <strong>data-last API</strong>.</p>\n<p>A data-last function takes its configuration arguments first and returns a <em>new function</em> that is waiting for the data to be provided.</p>\n<h4>Data-last counterparts (fully implemented, no <code>dual</code>)</h4>\n<pre><code class=\"hljs language-typescript\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\">type</span> <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt; = <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> A;\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\">// map (data-last)</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">export</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> mapDL = &lt;A, B&gt;<span class=\"hljs-function\">(<span class=\"hljs-params\"><span class=\"hljs-attr\">f</span>: (a: A) =&gt; B</span>) =&gt;</span>\n  (<span class=\"hljs-attr\">self</span>: <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt;): <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;B&gt; =&gt; {\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> {\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> a = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">self</span>();\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">f</span>(a);\n    };\n  };\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\">// retry (data-last)</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">export</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> retryDL = &lt;A&gt;<span class=\"hljs-function\">(<span class=\"hljs-params\"><span class=\"hljs-attr\">retries</span>: <span class=\"hljs-built_in\">number</span></span>) =&gt;</span>\n  (<span class=\"hljs-attr\">self</span>: <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt;): <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt; =&gt; {\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> {\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">let</span> <span class=\"hljs-attr\">lastError</span>: <span class=\"hljs-built_in\">unknown</span>;\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">for</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">let</span> i = <span class=\"hljs-number\">0</span>; i &lt; retries; i++) {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">try</span> {\n          <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">self</span>();\n        } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">catch</span> (error) {\n          lastError = error;\n        }\n      }\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">throw</span> lastError;\n    };\n  };\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\">// catchAll (data-last)</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">export</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> catchAllDL = &lt;A, B&gt;<span class=\"hljs-function\">(<span class=\"hljs-params\"><span class=\"hljs-attr\">handler</span>: (error: <span class=\"hljs-built_in\">unknown</span>) =&gt; B</span>) =&gt;</span>\n  (<span class=\"hljs-attr\">self</span>: <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A&gt;): <span class=\"hljs-title class_\">Computation</span>&lt;A | B&gt; =&gt; {\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> {\n      <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">try</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">self</span>();\n      } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">catch</span> (error) {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">handler</span>(error);\n      }\n    };\n  };\n</code></pre><hr>\n<h3>The Missing Piece: <code>pipe</code></h3>\n<p>Now that our functions are data-last, how do we use them? Chaining them manually is even uglier than before.</p>\n<p>The solution is a powerful utility function called <code>pipe</code>. You will use <code>pipe</code> constantly when writing Effect-style code.</p>\n<p><code>pipe</code> takes an initial value as its first argument, and then \"pipes\" that value through a sequence of functions. The result of one function becomes the input for the next.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"hljs language-typescript\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\">import</span> { pipe } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\">from</span> <span class=\"hljs-string\">\"effect/Function\"</span>;\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\">// Example: using the data-last counterparts defined above</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\">const</span> program = <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">pipe</span>(\n  fetchUser,\n  <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">mapDL</span>(<span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-params\">user</span> =&gt;</span> user.<span class=\"hljs-property\">name</span>),\n  <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">retryDL</span>(<span class=\"hljs-number\">3</span>),\n  <span class=\"hljs-title function_\">catchAllDL</span>(<span class=\"hljs-function\">() =&gt;</span> <span class=\"hljs-string\">\"Guest\"</span>)\n);\n</code></pre><p>The difference is night and day. This version reads naturally from top to bottom and perfectly describes the sequence of operations:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>First, <code>fetchUser</code>.</li>\n<li>Then, <code>map</code> the result to get the user's name.</li>\n<li>Then, <code>retry</code> that operation up to 3 times.</li>\n<li>Finally, <code>catchAll</code> errors and provide a fallback value of \"Guest\".</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h3>How Does <code>pipe</code> Work?</h3>\n<p>Under the hood, <code>pipe</code> is a simple but clever function. It has a series of TypeScript overloads that ensure the output type of one step correctly matches the input type of the next.</p>\n<p>At runtime, its implementation is highly optimized. It uses a <code>switch</code> statement to handle the most common number of arguments (e.g., up to 9) because direct function calls are faster than using a loop. For any number of arguments beyond that, it falls back to a standard <code>for</code> loop.</p>\n<p>With data-last functions and the <code>pipe</code> utility, we can now build complex, multi-step computations in a way that is both powerful and incredibly easy to read.</p>\n</div>\n```\n\nyou should output this as markdown transcript in the lesson dir","if you want you can initialize uv in this dir and add packages using uv ","if you want you can initialize uv in this project and add packages using uv ","I suggest you use established deps instead of hand rolling them","I just run the head command and logged in, the browser is unclosed yet, what are the next steps, can you complete for me","this is what I get after log in with the headed mode\n\n❯ uv run python build_transcripts.py --fetch --headed --overwrite\n\nfetching 01: Why Bother With a New Way of Writing Code?\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"/Users/qiushi/courses/practical-effect/build_transcripts.py\", line 243, in fetch_transcripts\n    page.wait_for_selector(\"div.prose.max-w-