still create the folder and transcript.md file, but leave the main content empty (still create yaml header) this does not need to errror\n\nI would also like all of your transcripts to be grouped in one parent folder, maybe called \"course.\" Inside that folder, there will be nested chapters and nested lessons. All of them should be prepended with an index according to the course index.json. you probably want to clean and rerun the script\n\nadd reasonale delay to the script do we dont get banned\n\nalso in the markdown frontmatter for each transcript, can you also include the video url such as m3u8"],"019e0fad-9be6-79d2-b160-6399bcfce8a8":["/goal\n\n# Goal 5: production cut before real use\n\nThis is goal 5 of the HealthCoach implementation. Goals 1–4 took the app from skeleton through Phases 0–6 of the spec roadmap — the spec is now feature-complete. This goal hardens the live AI path and the real-use failure modes so the user can provision a real Anthropic key, start using the app daily, and trust what comes back.\n\nYou have built and deepened this codebase across four prior goals. The required reading list below is short for that reason. Refresh the parts that matter for this goal, then start.\n\n\n---\n\n## Why this scope\n\nTwo truths after goal 4:\n\n- The live AI path has never met a real outage. `LiveAnthropicClient` has been exercised exclusively against `StubAnthropicClient` in tests. The free-text JSON parser strips ` ```json` fences with regex and decodes; if Claude returns a slightly drifted shape the user sees `LiveAIClientError.invalidJSON` with no recovery path. Empty states across the dashboard, food, goals, and anomaly history haven't been treated as a first-class concern. Notification copy is still a static \"Plan is ready.\" When the user provisions a real key, every one of these will surface within the first week.\n- The current JSON-via-prompt approach is the highest-fragility surface in the live path. Anthropic's tool use exists exactly for this: schema-validated structured output that won't drift on model updates. Migrating now — before two weeks of real use accumulate logs against the old shape — is much cheaper than later.\n\nThis goal is the bridge between \"app builds and tests pass\" and \"user has been running this daily for a month and trusts it.\" It deliberately resists speculative polish — the right cadence is: ship goal 5, use it for real, let goal 6 respond to what real use reveals.\n\n## Objective and stopping condition\n\nTwo themes. Both required for stopping.\n\n**Theme A — AI robustness:**\n- **Structured tool-use migration.** Replace the free-text JSON + fence-strip parser with Anthropic Messages API `tool_use`. Define one tool per response shape: `submit_daily_coach`, `submit_weekly_review`, `submit_food_photo_analysis`. Each tool's `input_schema` matches the existing `DailyCoachResponse` / `WeeklyReviewResponse` / `FoodPhotoAnalysis` Codable types verbatim. `LiveCoachAIClient` and `LiveFoodPhotoAnalyzer` send the tool definition, force the model with `tool_choice: { type: \"tool\", name: ... }`, parse the resulting `tool_use` block, and decode its `input`. The `MessagesResponse` decoder needs to handle `tool_use` blocks (the deferred goal-1 followup #5). Prompt caching still applies on the static system block; tool definitions go alongside.\n- **Token + cache telemetry surface.** A debug section (hidden behind a long-press or settings toggle) listing the last N daily/weekly runs with `model`, input tokens, output tokens, cache-creation tokens, cache-read tokens, and cache-hit ratio. Read-only — purely for catching cost regressions and verifying caching works in real flight.\n- **Prompt-version replay tool.** A debug surface that takes a stored `DailyPushLogModel` or `WeeklyReviewLogModel` and re-runs its original `promptVersion` against the *current* prompt header, side-by-siding the two responses. Lets you tune prompts against historical inputs without burning a real day's data. Tests use `StubAnthropicClient`; no network calls in tests.\n\n**Theme B — real-use readiness:**\n- **Live AI error UX.** Three failure modes need explicit handling: (a) network outage / `URLError` → \"couldn't reach Claude — check connection\" with a retry button on the dashboard error card; (b) `AnthropicHTTPError` (rate-limit, 5xx, auth) → message surfaces the Anthropic error string verbatim, with a retry path for transient errors and a \"go to Settings\" link for auth errors; (c) `LiveAIClientError.invalidJSON` (less likely after Theme A's tool-use migration but still possible) → store the raw response on the log model for debugging and show \"Claude returned an unexpected shape\" with a \"View raw\" debug action. None of these crash; none silently fall back to mock.\n- **HealthKit permission denial UX.** If the user denies HK permissions or grants partial access, the dashboard's \"Connect Health\" button must re-prompt, or — if iOS has marked the request as denied — deep-link to Settings via `UIApplication.openSettingsURLString`. The current path silently shows empty metrics.\n- **Empty states.** Every list/section in the app gets a real empty state with one-line copy and (where relevant) a primary action: dashboard before HK is connected, dashboard with HK connected but no logs yet, anomaly history with no anomalies, anomaly history with cold-start gating active, goals list with no Goal, registered meals with no meals, FNDDS not yet imported on first launch.\n- **Notification copy referencing real content.** The daily push notification body, currently \"Plan is ready,\" should reference the actual response: tomorrow's session type, anomaly count if any, and the high-protein meal target. Read from the just-persisted `DailyPushLogModel` after `runDailyPush` succeeds; fall back to a neutral default if no log exists. Match the tone in spec §6.4.\n- **Anomaly history full Signal coverage.** Goal 3 shipped two named rolling-Signal patterns (HRV-below-SWC, sleep timing). The other three deload Signals (Hooper Z, training completion < 70%, sustained low motivation) should also render as named rolling patterns when their cold-start gate from ADR-0016 is satisfied. Same UI idiom.\n- **SwiftData migration policy.** New ADR pinning the schema-versioning approach: `VersionedSchema` per major break, additive-only fields between, migration plan stored alongside each schema version. Implement the policy with one trivial migration as proof — e.g., add an optional field somewhere genuinely useful (or move an existing implicit field to a versioned schema). Explicitly *not* a refactor of all existing models — just the policy + one example.\n- **Cleanup: delete the watch UI test fixture path.** The `--hc-auto-watch-session` launch-arg path in `WatchSessionView` was a goal-3 smoke shortcut. With real-tap UI being the only real validation, delete the fixture path and the `sendUITestSessionIfRequested` plumbing. Update or remove any tests that depended on it.\n- **Real-device validation checklist doc.** New `docs/operations/real-device-validation.md` — a numbered checklist for the first real-key smoke: provision key → tap Run Coach → log session on watch → verify import → wait for 21:00 → verify notification → check token usage → exercise each empty state → exercise each error path. Not code; just the script the user runs in a single sitting before declaring goal 5 done in the wild.\n\n**Stopping condition (all four):**\n\n1. Theme A acceptance is satisfied — verified through tests with stubbed `tool_use` envelopes (no network); cache-hit telemetry rendered against fixtures; replay tool exercises a stored log against a pinned prompt version.\n2. Theme B acceptance is satisfied — verified through unit tests for error handling, empty-state previews, migration test, and a manual sweep where every error path is explicitly triggered in the simulator (or stubbed).\n3. `xbuild` clean for both iOS and watchOS schemes; `xtest` green; both simulators launched.\n4. ADRs and per-theme handoff docs committed; branch pushed; **do not merge to main.**\n\n## Branch\n\n`codex/goal-5` off `main` (goal 4 was merged; main is at the latest goal-4 commit).\n\n---\n\n## Architectural premise (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\n- Single user, two devices (iPhone + Apple Watch). No backend.\n- Claude API direct from device.\n- Health data stays on device. Only summaries leave the device.\n- iOS 26.4 + watchOS 26.x deployment, Swift 6.0, MainActor default isolation, strict concurrency.\n\n## Personal-health invariants (non-negotiable, same as prior goals)\n\n- `§6.7` rules 5/8/9: no medical advice, no chronotype-shift suggestions, no \"don't eat X\" framings, no chicken-breast recommendations.\n- `§4.7` red lines (RED-S, OTS) and `§4.2` deficit caps stay silent — they shape proposals, not user-visible alerts.\n- `§2.1` + `PROFILE.md` are facts. Don't invent.\n- Three-state missing-data convention from `§6.4`: omit / `\"no data\"` / `0`. Empty states never collapse missing into zero.\n\n## Decision freedom (same as prior goals)\n\nWide. Tool-use schema shapes, telemetry UI placement, empty-state copy, error-recovery flows, schema-versioning approach — your call from first principles within the architectural premise. Spec patches allowed for narrow gaps with `(YYYY-MM-DD: pinned during Goal 5 implementation)` marker. Glossary changes allowed if you sweep `CONTEXT.md` references and add a \"Resolved YYYY-MM-DD\" line. Stop only when a non-negotiable conflicts genuinely with what you'd need to do.\n\nThe tool-use schema decision is the highest-leverage one this goal: one tool per response shape vs a single `submit_response` tool with a discriminator. Pick from first principles, document in an ADR, commit.\n\n---\n\n## Required reading\n\nSkim, don't re-read full:\n\n- `docs/handoff/goal-4-theme-a-phases-5-6.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-4-theme-b-residuals.md` — most recent state.\n- `docs/spec-v1.md`: `§6.4` (daily push contract — the tool input schema must match), `§6.5` (weekly review contract — same), `§7.1` (stack), `§7.4` (prompt versioning — caching invariants), `§8` Phase status (now 0–6 complete).\n- `docs/adr/0007` (Anthropic client + prompt versioning — extend, don't break), `0012` (API key + Anthropic usage envelope — `AnthropicCompletion` already carries `usage`, build on it), `0016` (anomaly history cold-start — gates the new pattern UI surfaces).\n- The `claude-api` skill is load-bearing this goal. Use it for tool-use shape, prompt caching with tool definitions, and Messages API error-envelope handling. If unavailable in the session, use Anthropic's official docs and note in the handoff.\n\nIf something feels uncertain mid-implementation, re-read the relevant spec section before guessing.\n\n## Skills\n\nSame set as prior goals. At the start of each theme, write a short \"what applies here\" note in working scratch (don't commit):\n\n- `tdd` — red-green-refactor per slice. Theme A's tool-use migration is an obvious TDD candidate — assert against fixture `tool_use` envelopes before touching the live client.\n- `swift-testing-pro` — keep tests narrow; avoid SwiftData round-trips when a value-type round-trip will do.\n- `swiftui-pro` — empty states + error cards + telemetry surface are real SwiftUI work; match the existing dashboard idiom (`Form` + `Section` + `LabeledContent`). Don't introduce a new visual language.\n- `improve-codebase-architecture` — schema migration policy is the architecture-shaped piece this goal. The policy ADR matters more than the trivial migration.\n- `claude-api` — load-bearing. Apply tool-use, prompt caching with tool definitions, and the proper completion envelope shape.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Branch.** `codex/goal-5`. **Commit per slice — not as a single end-of-goal lump.** Goal 4 landed as one giant commit and the resulting thin ADRs + invisible TDD trail made the review materially harder. This goal explicitly requires per-slice commits with descriptive messages so reviewers can read the slice progression.\n2. **Slice.** Vertical slices with a clear acceptance condition each. TDD per slice. `xbuild` clean (both schemes) and `xtest` green before each commit.\n3. **ADRs for keystone decisions.** Same format as prior ADRs. Examples worth an ADR this goal:\n   - Tool-use schema strategy (per-response-shape tool vs single discriminated tool, force-tool vs auto, prompt-cache placement).\n   - Telemetry surface shape and placement.\n   - SwiftData schema migration policy + cadence.\n   - Live-AI error taxonomy + recovery rules.\n   - Empty-state copy strategy (centralized library vs per-view literals).\n\n   ADRs should explain the *why* — alternatives considered, the trade-off, the chosen path. The thin 8-13-line ADRs in goal 4 are the floor not the target; aim closer to ADR-0019's depth.\n4. **Per-theme handoff.** At end of each theme, write `docs/handoff/goal-5-theme-a-ai-robustness.md` and `docs/handoff/goal-5-theme-b-real-use-readiness.md`. Don't duplicate code, ADR text, or commit messages — reference by path/SHA. Include only: what's verified vs pending, spec gaps you hit and how resolved, glossary near-misses, what the next loop should know, which skills + OSS sections you actually used (one line each: kept / skipped / why).\n5. **Spec edits** during the run: allowed for narrow gaps with date-stamped marker. STOP and surface in the handoff for genuine non-negotiable conflicts.\n\n## API key handling\n\nUnchanged from goal 2. All tests use `MockKeyProvider`; no network calls in tests. Theme A's tool-use migration goes through the same Keychain-backed live client; usage logging in `DailyPushLogModel`/`WeeklyReviewLogModel` should keep working with the new `tool_use`-shaped responses.\n\nThe user provisions the real key post-merge. The real-device validation checklist in Theme B is the script they'll run on first real coach call.\n\n## Build commands\n\n| Command | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `xbuild` | Build for the iPhone 17 simulator (default scheme `HealthCoach`). |\n| `xbuild -s HealthCoachWatch` | Build the watchOS scheme. |\n| `xtest` | Run all iOS tests. |\n| `xtest HealthCoachTests/<Suite>` | Narrow to one suite. |\n| `XCODE_DESTINATION='platform=watchOS Simulator,name=Apple Watch Series 11 (46mm)' xtest` | Run tests on the watchOS simulator. |\n| `xtests-list` | List test classes. |\n\nAdding/removing source files inside the synchronized roots does not require pbxproj edits.\n\n## Polish to fold in\n\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §8** — update the \"Status\" preamble after this goal lands to reflect Phases 0–6 complete and the production-cut work.\n- **`docs/spec-v1.md` §7.1.1** — mark any new SwiftData models (e.g., a `RawResponseLogModel` if Theme B's invalid-JSON path adds one) as `(implemented in goal 5)`.\n- **CONTEXT.md** — only add a glossary entry if the tool-use migration introduces a domain term the user-facing parts of the app (or future goals) will reference. Don't add internal API terminology.\n- **Goal 3 leftover:** `.agents/skills/` and `.claude/skills/` directories were intentionally kept. No action.\n\n## What's deliberately out of scope\n\nThese are tempting but should wait for goal 6 (post-real-use):\n\n- Battery / background-task profiling (needs real-day data).\n- Onboarding flow polish (needs first-time-user-who-isn't-the-author).\n- FNDDS catalogue gaps (need real meal logging).\n- Most UX copy beyond the explicit Theme B items (needs to feel wrong in real use first).\n- Phase 4 RMSSD activation (needs a real Apple Watch session — already documented as deferred per ADR-0021).\n- Goal achievement flow polish, transition-mode reason analytics, weekly-review PDF export — none of these are real until the user uses the app.\n\nIf a fix obviously belongs in this goal but isn't listed above, land it. If it's speculative (\"the user might want X\"), defer it to goal 6 with a one-line note in the handoff.\n\n## Suggested first commit\n\nA short `docs/handoff/goal-5-plan.md` with your slice plan for both themes, the tool-use schema strategy you're leaning toward (with one-paragraph rationale), the schema-migration approach, and which Theme B failure-modes you're prioritizing first. Optional but useful — same as prior first commits.\n\n---\n\nThat's the contract. Skim the required reading, plan the themes, then start with whichever theme unblocks the other. Theme A's tool-use migration meaningfully reduces Theme B's `invalidJSON` failure mode, so it's a reasonable first theme — but the order is your call.\n","did you commit your work or the current state of the repo includes all your work ","A senior engineer reviewed your changes and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct.\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\n\n12 commits, real per-slice progression, ~1400 LoC focused on the load-bearing AI surface. The tool-use migration is the right call and was executed cleanly. Two moderate concerns and a few minor ones — no critical bugs (one reviewer's flag was a misread, verified below).\n\n---\n\n### Critical\n\nNone. One Critical reviewer claim was a misread:\n\n- **Schema mismatch on `recommended_action`** — Reviewer alleged required + optional Codable would silently fail. **Verified false.** `LiveCoachAIClient.swift:100` uses `.nullable(.string())` with the field in `required`, which encodes to JSON Schema as `{\"anyOf\": [{\"type\":\"string\"}, {\"type\":\"null\"}], \"required\": [...]}` (see `AnthropicClient.swift:285-286`). This is the standard \"must emit, may be null\" idiom — Claude must produce the key, value can be `null`, Swift `Decodable` maps `null` → `Optional.none`. Correct, not a bug.\n\n---\n\n### Moderate\n\n**M1. SwiftData migration policy is documented but not actually wired.**\n- Where: `Models/HealthCoachSchema.swift` defines `HealthCoachSchemaV1: VersionedSchema` and `HealthCoachMigrationPlan` with `stages: []` (empty). ADR-0028 documents the policy. The \"trivial migration as proof\" the contract asked for is the `promptInputJSON?` additive field on the log models — which is correct as a proof of the additive case but doesn't exercise the staged-migration path at all.\n- The author acknowledged this in the completion message (\"policy-pinned but not wired through a migration-plan app-launch overload\"). The first real breaking schema change will hit a cold path: the staged-migration apparatus exists structurally but has never run.\n- Why it matters: the policy claims migrations land \"alongside each schema version\" but there's no test exercising even a no-op staged migration. The first time a developer adds `HealthCoachSchemaV2`, the migration boilerplate that ought to be a paved path is going to need to be invented under pressure.\n- Fix: add a `HealthCoachSchemaV1_0_1` (or equivalent) that adds a trivial field with a no-op `MigrationStage.custom`, prove the staged path runs at app launch through an in-memory test container, then revert the example. Cost: ~40 lines + test. Doesn't need to change product behavior — purely exercises the migration apparatus once so the seam is proven.\n\n**M2. ADR depth regression carries forward from goal 4.**\n- Where: ADR-0027 (18 lines) and ADR-0028 (14 lines). Goal contract (line 178) explicitly targeted \"ADR-0019's depth\" (~23 lines) after flagging goal 4's 8-13-line ADRs as thin.\n- Neither ADR discusses alternatives in a useful way. 0027 doesn't explain why one-tool-per-response-shape was chosen over a single discriminated `submit_response` tool with a `kind` field — the schema-size trade-off, the prompt-cache implication, or the cost of force-tool vs auto. 0028 doesn't explain why per-major-break `VersionedSchema` over always-additive — what specifically breaks the additive approach. Both read as \"we did X\" rather than \"we considered X and Y, here's why X.\"\n- Fix: expand both to ~25-30 lines. For 0027: add an \"Alternatives considered\" section covering the discriminated-tool path and explicit force-tool vs auto choice; explicitly note that tool definitions live alongside the cached system block and the cache is unaffected because both are stable. For 0028: explain why additive-only is insufficient for the long arc (field-type changes, removed fields, enum value renames will all require versioned schemas), and document that goal 5 deliberately deferred wiring a real migration stage — call out M1's concern.\n\n**M3. Substantial tool-use integration test lives in `ApiKeyProviderTests.swift`.**\n- Where: `ApiKeyProviderTests.swift:44-125`. `liveAnthropicClientSendsForcedToolAndDecodesToolUseInput` is an ~80-line integration test exercising stubbed URLProtocol → forced tool-use → tool_use parse → usage decoding. It's the single most important test of Theme A's tool-use migration. It has nothing to do with API key storage.\n- Why it matters: future maintainers won't find it. A grep for \"tool\" in `LiveAIClientTests` will miss it.\n- Fix: move to either `LiveAIClientTests.swift` (consistent with existing structure) or a new `AnthropicToolUseTests.swift` (more discoverable). Pure file move — no logic change.\n\n---\n\n### Minor\n\n**m1. Test gaps in error taxonomy.** `CoachRunErrorStateTests` covers 9 paths but no `URLError(.timedOut)` case; the catch-all maps it to `.retry`, which is probably right, but verify with one test. ~5 lines.\n\n**m2. Notification copy test only exercises 1-anomaly case.** `NotificationCopyTests` doesn't cover 0 anomalies (the \"No anomalies\" branch) or plural (≥2). Implementation in `CoachNotificationScheduler` handles all three branches; tests don't pin them. ~10 lines for two additional cases.\n\n**m3. Paused Goals empty state uses plain `Text(\"No paused Goals\")` rather than `ContentUnavailableView`.** `GoalsView.swift:42-44`. Inconsistent with the main empty state at line 21. Cosmetic; would take 3 lines to align.\n\n**m4. Tool_use mixed-content edge case is non-issue.** Reviewer flagged that `firstToolInputJSON` returning `.first(where:)` could miss the tool_use block if a text block came first. Verified false: `AnthropicClient.swift:309-312` filters by `content.type == \"tool_use\"` AND the expected name, so text blocks are skipped. The edge case doesn't apply.\n\n---\n\n### What's verified to work\n\n- **Per-slice commit discipline restored** after goal 4's single-commit regression. 12 named commits with vertical-slice intent; tests land alongside code.\n- **Tool-use migration:** forced `tool_choice` with named tool, schema fidelity verified against the integration test, prompt caching unaffected (tool defs are stable, system block stable). The single highest-leverage change of this goal landed correctly.\n- **Error taxonomy:** all three failure modes from the contract mapped (network/URLError → retry; `AnthropicHTTPError` with auth/rate-limit/5xx subcases → settings link or retry; tool_use parse failure → \"view raw\" debug). Dashboard error card wires the right action per case.\n- **HK denial:** explicit `.denied` branch deep-linking to `UIApplication.openSettingsURLString`. Was silently empty before; now actionable.\n- **All 7 contract-specified empty states** rendered as real `ContentUnavailableView` sections with copy and (where applicable) primary actions.\n- **Anomaly history full coverage:** all 5 named rolling Signals (HRV-below-SWC, sleep timing, Hooper Z, completion <70%, sustained motivation) render with the same cold-start gating from ADR-0016.\n- **Notification copy** content-aware: reads tomorrow's session type, anomaly count (singular/plural), protein target from the just-persisted `DailyPushLogModel`. Falls back to neutral when no log exists.\n- **Watch fixture cleanup:** `sendUITestSessionIfRequested` and the `--hc-auto-watch-session` launch arg fully removed.\n- **Real-device validation checklist** exists at `docs/operations/real-device-validation.md`, 15 numbered steps, concrete (tap-by-tap), covers every contract-listed verification surface.\n- **Out-of-scope discipline:** zero commits touching battery profiling, FNDDS catalogue expansion, onboarding polish, or RMSSD activation. The \"what's deliberately out of scope\" guardrail held.\n\n---\n\n### Did it solve the intended problem?\n\nYes, for the items that don't require real use:\n\n- The fragile fence-strip JSON parser is gone. Tool-use is the right migration and the integration test pins the contract. This was the single most consequential piece of debt in the live AI path; it's now paid down.\n- Every contract-listed failure mode has explicit handling rather than `LiveAIClientError` strings — so when the user provisions a real key, the first auth failure, rate limit, or network outage produces a meaningful recovery path rather than a red string.\n- Empty states and HK denial paths mean the app behaves coherently before any data exists, which is the realistic first-launch state.\n- Process recovered: per-slice commits, ADRs (thin but present), honest handoffs that acknowledge deferred items.\n\nWhat it doesn't solve — and was honest about not solving:\n\n- No real Anthropic key smoke. The validation checklist is the user's job post-merge.\n- No physical Apple Watch validation (still the right deferral per ADR-0021).\n- SwiftData migration policy is documented and structurally present but never actually runs a stage (M1 above).\n\n---\n\n### Recommended pre-merge fixes (in this order)\n\n1. **M3** — move the tool-use integration test out of `ApiKeyProviderTests.swift`. 1-file move, ~5 minutes.\n2. **M2** — expand ADR-0027 and ADR-0028 by ~10 lines each to discuss alternatives + trade-offs. Restores the discipline the goal-5 contract requested; the third regression-in-a-row on this is the one process item worth addressing.\n3. **m1, m2** — two small test backfills if you care; can defer.\n4. **M1** — wire one no-op staged migration before goal 6. Defensible to merge this branch without it, but goal 6 will be easier if M1 lands first as a small follow-up commit.\n\nAfter those, this branch is in good shape. The branch represents real progress — the AI surface is now production-shaped, and the next honest gate is real-use validation. Provision the key, follow the checklist at `docs/operations/real-device-validation.md`, and let goal 6 respond to what real use reveals.","If I ask you to implement a couple of follow-up commits on this branch to fix these issues with your recommended solutions, what would they be? \n\nOne minor suggestion: even if something is minor, unlikely to happen, or an edge case, if the fix is relatively straightforward and simple, still do it. We are not measuring a bug by how likely it is to occur, but by how well we designed the system. Do not shy away from a bug just because it is unlikely to happen or its a minor issue","ok go ahead and implement these fixes, I would suggest that after these three commits, you also read all the relevant spec and handoff documents. Try to keep them up to date so that we have an accurate start; if later engineers read our docs, they should reflect the current state of this project.","so. What do you think the next goal for this project should be? I guess it depends on how we're going to use it. \n\nYou could ask me some clarifying questions, such as:\n1. Do I want to start using it personally?\n2. Do I want to polish this feature before I actually start using it?\n\nOverall, what do you think the next goal would be? Do you think I should start using it myself?"],"019e1513-ded7-7593-8ed7-d0f252e4339d":["Now that you have a good understanding of our awareness system, I'm going to present three issues that users reported related to it. I have downloaded all the relevant issue context so you don't have to go to GitHub anymore; you can just read the local files, the attached log bundles, and the issue descriptions all in the same directory.\n\nThese might represent the same problem, or they could be different parallel issues. I suggest you look at what version they are using, because we've been fixing several awareness issues over the past week. If they are using an old version where we've already fixed the problem, it's probably not a concern for us, but you should still analyze the issue.\n\nPlease follow this process:\n1. Start with the issue.md description to understand what the user is reporting.\n2. Go into their logs, as that is the source of truth for their actual COLA state.\n\nSome of the files are very large, so I suggest you avoid reading them directly. Try to only poke at the specific things we should be caring about.\n\na skill that might be helpful .claude/skills/github-issue-analyze/SKILL.md, It's not directly relevant to fixing a bug in awareness, but it does teach you some approaches in how to analyze the user's logs.\n\n\n## Awareness issue triage — three bundles ready for analysis\n\nAll bundles include `issue.md` (raw feedback body), `cola-logs.zip`, and `extracted/` with the standard layout (`logs/`, `sessions/`, `awareness/{capability-cache,index,status}.json`, `crons.json`, `env.json`, `autonomous-budget.json`).\n\n### Issue #1759 — \"心迹说管线挂了，是普遍问题吗？\"\n**Path:** `issues.local/1759-awareness-pipeline-broken/`\n\nUser saw an in-app message saying the awareness pipeline broke and wants to know whether it's a global problem (will fix itself on next release) or specific to their account (needs a manual fix). The complaint is meta: they're not just reporting a broken pipeline, they're reporting that Cola *told them* it's broken. Likely surfaces the new `awareness/status.json` failure-streak context that gets injected into the system prompt when the nightly pipeline keeps failing — worth checking whether the streak is real (actual failures in `cola-2026-05-07/08/09.log`) or stale.\n\n- **Env:** macOS arm64, v0.7.10, ~600 MB free at report time\n- **Logs:** 3 days (May 7–9), 24 subagent traces\n- **Reported:** 2026-05-09T11:06 UTC\n\n---\n\n### Issue #1764 — \"昨晚忽然弹出了前两日的心迹，质量不高，第一篇还是英文的\"\n**Path:** `issues.local/1764-late-awareness-low-quality-english/`\n\nThree distinct sub-complaints in one report:\n1. **Late delivery** — two days of awareness notes published at once\n2. **Quality** — content felt like a verbatim transcript echo, not reflective synthesis\n3. **Language** — first note rendered in English despite a Chinese-speaking user\n\nScreenshot included (`screenshot.png`, 952 KB) showing the English imprint. The cron traces in the bundle (`cron-book-reminder-*`, `cron-sync-obsidian-*`) suggest this user runs the proactive cron stack heavily — delivery scheduling and language detection in `awareness-reflect` are both candidates.\n\n- **Env:** macOS arm64, v0.7.10, ~1 GB free\n- **Logs:** 3 days (May 8–10), 28 subagent traces (multiple cron-driven)\n- **Reported:** 2026-05-10T02:21 UTC\n\n---\n\n### Issue #1769 — \"心迹崩坏啦！\"\n**Path:** `issues.local/1769-awareness-collapsed-windows/`\n\nShort, high-emotion complaint — \"Imprints fell apart!\" — no detail on what specifically broke. **First Windows report** in this batch (the other two are macOS), so platform-specific paths (file system, Sharp image processing for motif color, path normalization) are in play. The log set has a gap: `cola-2026-05-09.log` and `cola-2026-05-11.log` but **no 05-10** — either the app didn't run that day or rotation evicted it. Heavy cron user (`cron-daily-footwear-3dp-brief`, `cron-gold-miner-weekday`/`weekend`, `cron-weekly-learning-briefing`).\n\n- **Env:** Windows x64, v0.7.10, ~2 GB free\n- **Logs:** 2 days (May 9 + May 11, gap on May 10), 29 subagent traces\n- **Reported:** 2026-05-11T03:25 UTC\n\n---\n\n**Common thread to flag for the reviewer:** all three are v0.7.10, all post-date the awareness pipeline observability rollout (`docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-07-awareness-pipeline-observability-and-resilience.md`), and all three bundles ship `awareness/status.json` + `capability-cache.json` — so the new per-stage failover and per-fire `FireBrokenFamilies` set should leave concrete evidence about whether the pipeline actually failed, recovered, or got mis-classified as failed.\n\n---\n\nDO NOT CHANGE ANY CODE YET. Step back and reason about the module/feature holistically before proposing any fix.\n\n1. State the real problem and the underlying UX goal in your own words. If my framing seems off, push back before going further.\n2. Evaluate the current design against that goal — where does it fall short, and is the issue local or structural?\n3. From first principles, present 2–3 approaches with concrete tradeoffs (complexity, blast radius, UX impact, future flexibility). Recommend one and explain why.\n\nDon't patch a flawed design with another patch. Don't shy away from large-scale changes when they're justified — but be explicit about what they cost.","In terms of the DeepSeek failure, is that a transient error or is it something specific to DeepSeek that can be reproduced all the time?\n\nI feel like it's probably not an \"all the time\" error because we have about 500 users of Audience. If it had always been broken, I think we would have seen a lot more reports in the last two days.\n\nMaybe you could write a local script to verify? Specifically, could you write a simple MVP version of the exact call to see if it's failing in scripts.local/ ?","So, now that you are going to give your complete and best clean recommendation—I believe you've given me some alternatives before, but I think we should prefer maybe a hybrid or a clean architectural long-term solution—what would you recommend as a complete proposal?\n\nI think fixing the DeepSeek thing is probably the first thing we should do. I remember we have a set of errors where we should just fall back to plot models; maybe this should be one of the errors where we fall back.\n\nAnyway, just give me your best proposal at this point.","so I asked our core engineer to review your proposal, he had his agreements and disagreemens, and come up with his own polished complete proposal. I've drafted a spec based on his idea. Review it critically.\n\nFor each point:\n- If you agree: add technical suggestions, caveats, or risks worth flagging.\n- If you disagree: give reasons and a concrete alternative. If the issue is architectural rather than local, say so and propose the structural fix.\n\nWeigh technical merit and UX goals together. Challenge assumptions and propose alternatives whenever they would lead to a better outcome — don't default to politeness.\n\n\n---\n\nSpec written at `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-11-awareness-pipeline-compat-and-graduated-status.md`.\n\nStructure follows the existing spec style (problem → product decisions with alternatives → evidence → out-of-scope):\n\n- **6 product decisions**, each with chosen shape + alternatives considered and rejected\n- **§Disagreement With Prior Proposal** as its own clearly labeled section — adopts A's fingerprint + dev-test additions (and credits them), pushes back specifically on the UX-copy framing and explains the reasoning, extends the dev-test scope per your direction\n- **Evidence from all three reports** with concrete log timestamps, status.json deltas, screenshot read\n- **Out-of-scope list** + **3 open questions** for the engineering review\n\nI deliberately kept implementation phasing out of it — file paths and code locations show up only where they're load-bearing for the diagnosis (e.g. `reflection.ts:121` where the bad schema lives, `memory-cron.ts:795` where the language directive plugs in).\n\n","Based on our discussion, I have updated the spec and come up with a technical implementation plan, can you review\n\n\n---\n\n<plan>\n# Awareness Pipeline Compatibility Repair + Graduated Status Surface — Implementation Plan\n\n## Context\n\nThree v0.7.10 feedback issues filed within 48 hours all complain about 心迹/Awareness, but they are three different bugs:\n\n- **#1759 & #1769** — `awareness_finalize_day`'s top-level `Type.Union` parameter schema is rejected by DeepSeek's strict OpenAI-compat validator. The 5/7 failover machinery does not engage because the classifier doesn't recognize this error class. Users on `sota` tier resolving to `deepseek-v4-pro` get silent multi-day reflect outages.\n- **#1764** — Mid-flight episode-digest kills (laptop sleep / restart) → catch-up republishes two days back-to-back → newest-first delivery + 6h cooldown → \"前两日的心迹忽然弹出.\" Plus Opus framed a Chinese substantive note with English narrative scaffolding (`He said: <Chinese quote>`) because the reflect prompt offered English as a peer language option.\n- **All three** — When the agent is asked about awareness state, `awareness_status_read` returns raw field names (`skipped_no_activity`, `failed_unknown`, `lastSuccessfulDate=2026-04-21`). The agent paraphrases these into operational sentences (\"管线挂了\"), turning a relationship surface into an ops console.\n\nThe intended outcome is to ship the six product decisions from `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-11-awareness-pipeline-compat-and-graduated-status.md` across small, independently-shippable commits, each with TDD coverage.\n\n## Approach\n\nSeven focused commits, each RED→GREEN. Ordering is set by dependency:\n\n1. Schema reshape (root-cause fix for #1759 / #1769).\n2. `defineCustomTool` type tightening (only compiles cleanly after Commit 1).\n3a. Classifier fingerprint (additive safety net).\n3b. Multi-capability stage wiring (pre-spawn skip on subsequent fires).\n4. Reflection language directive + prompt tightening (root-cause fix for #1764's English framing).\n5a. Pure scenario classifier (`single_glitch` / `sustained_failure` / etc., reads derived facts only).\n5b. Two-axis status tool refactor consuming 5a (the substantive UX change).\n6. Teaser date anchor for >24h-old catch-up notes (root-cause fix for #1764's \"popped up last night\" framing).\n\nTests are integration-style where the unit doesn't have meaningful internal edge cases (tool execute, classifier, teaser template). Pure-function unit coverage is reserved for the scenario classifier in 5a.\n\n## Commit-by-Commit\n\n### Commit 1 — Reshape `awareness_finalize_day` with strict executor validation\n\n**Files**\n- `server/agent/tools/reflection.ts:121-194`\n- `tests/server/agent/tools/reflection-tools.test.ts`\n\n**Tests (RED first, one cycle each):**\n1. Serialized parameter schema has top-level `type: \"object\"` and no top-level `anyOf` / `oneOf`.\n2. `hasReflection: true` with valid `content` → calls `publishFinalAwarenessNote`, returns success text.\n3. `hasReflection: true` with missing/empty `content` → returns a tool-error text naming the violation; no publish call; details show no_entry-unset.\n4. `hasReflection: false` with valid `briefSentence` → records no-entry; returns the existing acknowledgement text.\n5. `hasReflection: false` with `content` present → returns a tool-error text (do NOT silently coerce to no-entry); no publish call.\n6. Existing `validateBriefSentence` rejection path still surfaces its `reason` in the tool result.\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Replace `Type.Union([Type.Object({...}), Type.Object({...})])` with a single `Type.Object({ date, hasReflection: Type.Boolean(), content: Type.Optional(...), briefSentence: Type.Optional(...) })`.\n- In the executor, branch on `hasReflection` and validate the combinatoric shape strictly. Return text content for both error cases — the cron orchestrator already consumes tool text; no SDK \"retryable\" concept needs to change.\n- Reuse `validateBriefSentence` unchanged for the no-entry path.\n\n**Commit message:** `fix(awareness): reshape awareness_finalize_day to top-level object (#1759 #1769)`\n\n### Commit 2 — Tighten `defineCustomTool` to `TParams extends TObject` + CI guard for all custom tools\n\n**Files**\n- `server/agent/tools/define.ts:6`\n- `tests/server/agent/tools/tool-schema-invariants.test.ts` (new)\n\n**Tests:**\n1. For each registered custom tool factory, the produced tool's serialized parameter schema has `type: \"object\"` at the root and no top-level `anyOf` / `oneOf`. Iterate a hand-maintained `TOOL_FACTORIES` array imported explicitly.\n2. Regex sanity check: `grep -c 'defineCustomTool(' server/agent/tools/**/*.ts` matches `TOOL_FACTORIES.length`. This catches \"someone added a tool and forgot to register it in the invariant test.\" If mismatch, the test prints both lists so the human reviewer can see which factory needs adding.\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Change `defineCustomTool<TParams extends TSchema, …>` → `<TParams extends TObject, …>` in `server/agent/tools/define.ts:6`.\n- After Commit 1 is in, all current callers compile cleanly (verified during exploration — only `reflection.ts:121` previously violated this).\n\n**Note on docs/testing.md:** This is the rare \"test a structural invariant\" case where the unit form is appropriate — there is no behavioral seam to integration-test schema shape through.\n\n**Commit message:** `chore(tools): require TObject params for defineCustomTool and assert at CI`\n\n### Commit 3a — Classify `top_level_object_tool_schema` provider-contract errors\n\n**Files**\n- `server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.ts:39-50`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.test.ts`\n\n**Tests:**\n1. The error string `Invalid schema for function 'awareness_finalize_day': schema must be a JSON Schema of 'type: \"object\"', got 'type: null'.` → `class: 'failed_provider_contract'`, `fingerprint: 'top_level_object_tool_schema'`, `affectedCapability: 'top_level_object_tool_schema'`.\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Add one entry to `KNOWN_FINGERPRINTS`: regex matching `schema must be a JSON Schema of 'type:\\s*\"object\"'.*got 'type:\\s*null'`, capability tag `'top_level_object_tool_schema'`.\n- Extend `AwarenessCapability` enum/union with the new tag.\n\n**Commit message:** `feat(awareness): classify top-level-object schema rejection as known fingerprint`\n\n### Commit 3b — Multi-capability stage failover wiring\n\n**Files**\n- `server/cron/memory-cron.ts:394-571, 649, 733, 817` (`runStageWithFailover` + 3 call sites)\n- `tests/server/cron/memory-cron-failover.test.ts`\n\n**Tests:**\n1. Reflect stage declared with `['tool_roundtrip_with_thinking', 'top_level_object_tool_schema']`; capability-cache shows `top_level_object_tool_schema` broken for the resolved identity → pre-spawn skip engages, falls straight to SAFE_FALLBACK (Opus). Verify spawn count and final outcome.\n2. Capability-cache shows `tool_roundtrip_with_thinking` broken → also pre-spawn skips (proves \"any-required-cap-broken\" semantic).\n3. No capability broken → normal spawn path (regression).\n4. Same-fire respawn: first spawn fails with `top_level_object_tool_schema` fingerprint, classifier writes capability, second attempt in same fire skipped via `FireBrokenFamilies`. (May already pass with single-cap code if the assertion is on outcome, but proves the multi-cap semantics didn't regress this.)\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Change `runStageWithFailover`'s `capability` parameter to `capabilities: AwarenessCapability[]`.\n- Pre-spawn skip lookup (lines 407-409) iterates `capabilities` and skips if **any** match the cache or `FireBrokenFamilies`.\n- Update all three call sites to pass arrays — `episode` and `memory` get single-element arrays (per Plan agent recommendation: cleaner than union type, future-proof for the next capability).\n- Reflect call site at line 817 passes `['tool_roundtrip_with_thinking', 'top_level_object_tool_schema']`.\n\n**Commit message:** `refactor(awareness): runStageWithFailover takes capability array; reflect declares both`\n\n### Commit 4 — Reflection language directive + prompt tightening\n\n**Files**\n- `server/cron/memory-cron.ts:624, 795-815` (thread `digestLanguage` to Stage 3)\n- `server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts:780-879` (`GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT`)\n- `tests/server/cron/memory-cron.test.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/prompt-blocks.test.ts`\n\n**Tests:**\n1. For a Chinese transcript, `reflectionTask` contains `Reflection language: Chinese` AND the memory-override sentence. (Mirror the existing line 372 assertion that already covers `Digest language: Chinese`.)\n2. For an English transcript, `reflectionTask` contains `Reflection language: English`.\n3. `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` no longer presents English as a peer budget option; the budget line references the directive.\n4. `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` contains the new anti-pattern line about English narrative framing inside non-English notes (structural assertion via `toContain('He said:')` or similar — not exact-string match).\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Compute `digestLanguage` once in the cron fire (already exists at line 624). Thread it into the reflectionTask builder; do not re-detect.\n- Add a directive line to `reflectionTask` mirroring Stage 1's idiom: `Reflection language: ${digestLanguage}. Write the note in this language. If <global-memory> records an explicit user preference for a different language, follow the memory instead. Quoted user words, product names, code, and technical terms stay as written.`\n- Update `GUIDE_AWARENESS_REFLECT` budget line (line 792): `100–150 Chinese characters or 60–100 English words — write in the language specified by the \\`Reflection language:\\` directive.`\n- Add anti-pattern under the existing 837-844 list (matches the spec's exact wording): `**穿错语言的叙述框架**：不要在中文条目里用英文导引语句（\\`He said:\\` / \\`She said:\\` / \\`Note:\\` 等）—— 标题、引文导句都不行。用 他/她/你 直接叙述。技术词、引用原文、品牌名保留原样。`\n\n**Per prompting-guide.md:** The anti-pattern is a negative directive, but it targets a specific observed slip (per the spec) — acceptable as a focused exception rather than a generic \"do not\" rule. Positive framing handles the budget line (\"write in the language specified by…\").\n\n**Commit message:** `fix(awareness): force reflection-stage language match to stop English framing in Chinese notes (#1764)`\n\n### Commit 5a — Pure scenario classifier\n\n**Files**\n- `server/agent/awareness-status.ts` (extend) or new `server/agent/awareness-scenario.ts`\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-scenario.test.ts` (new)\n\n**Tests (one cycle per scenario tag):**\n1. Empty daily map → `fresh_install`.\n2. `pending_today` (today scheduled, no run yet).\n3. `draft_present_today` (draft exists, not finalized).\n4. `quiet_day` (latest outcome `ran_no_entry`, no draft).\n5. `single_glitch` (`consecutiveFailureCount === 1`).\n6. `sustained_failure` (`consecutiveFailureCount >= 2`).\n7. `recovered` (recent failures + latest success).\n8. `long_silence_no_failure` (many days back since last success, no failed entries).\n9. **The #1759 trap (unit form):** classifier given `{ streakId: 'active', consecutiveFailureCount: 0, latestOutcome: 'skipped_no_activity' }` → `single_glitch`. Proves the classifier ignores `streakId`.\n10. **The #1759 trap (data-path form, integration-style):** start with fixture that has `streakId` active. Call `repairDailyPendingDraftCountBatch` to write a `skipped_no_activity` row without clearing the streak. Read derived facts. Pass to classifier. Assert `single_glitch`. This proves the actual data path that creates the divergence is exercised, not just a hand-constructed fixture.\n\n**Implementation:**\n- New pure function `classifyAwarenessScenario(facts: { consecutiveFailureCount, lastSuccessfulDate, todayDailyState, allDailyStates }) → ScenarioTag`.\n- Closed-set return type `ScenarioTag = 'fresh_install' | 'pending_today' | 'draft_present_today' | 'quiet_day' | 'single_glitch' | 'recovered' | 'sustained_failure' | 'long_silence_no_failure'`.\n- Reads only derived day facts. Does **not** read `failureStreak.streakId`.\n\n**Commit message:** `feat(awareness): scenario classifier reading derived facts (not streakId)`\n\n### Commit 5b — Two-axis status tool refactor\n\n**Files**\n- `server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts` (rewrite output + add `intent` param)\n- `server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts` (`awarenessSurfaceBlock` — keep at principle level)\n- `tests/server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.test.ts`\n\n**Tests:**\n1. Tool accepts optional `intent?: 'casual' | 'diagnostic'`; default is `casual`.\n2. `casual` mode response includes `<scenario>`, `<answer_mode>casual</answer_mode>`, `<safe_user_answer>` (non-empty in user's primary language), empty `<diagnostic_detail>`, `<do_not_say>` populated.\n3. `diagnostic` mode + `sustained_failure` scenario: `<diagnostic_detail>` populated with derived-count summary; provider/model names **not** present in the rendered string; `<suggested_next_step>` mentions the Imprints \"Report this 心迹\" affordance.\n4. `casual` mode + `sustained_failure`: `<suggested_next_step>` still populated (it's conditional on severity, not on mode), but `<diagnostic_detail>` is empty.\n5. `<do_not_say>` contains forbidden phrases: `管线`, `pipeline broken`, `compatibility error`, model names, fingerprint ids.\n6. `single_glitch` × `diagnostic`: `<diagnostic_detail>` non-empty (brief acknowledgement; first instance in N days). No model/provider names.\n7. Tool's `promptGuidelines` lists 2–3 example utterances per intent (per prompting-guide.md): casual (\"今天有心迹吗?\"), diagnostic (\"坏了吗?\", \"是普遍问题吗?\").\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Tool params: add `intent: Type.Optional(Type.Union([Literal('casual'), Literal('diagnostic')], { default: 'casual' }))`. Note: this is fine — `Type.Union` inside an `Object` field is valid for OpenAI-compat; only top-level union is rejected.\n- Build response via switch on `scenario × answer_mode`. Per-scenario copy hard-coded inline as a table (per spec open question #2 default).\n- Render XML block exactly per spec §Decision 5 shape.\n- `awarenessSurfaceBlock` keeps the \"call this tool when asked about specific dates / recent state\" principle. Tool's own `promptGuidelines` carries the casual/diagnostic discrimination examples — moment-of-action guidance per prompting-guide.md.\n\n**Commit message:** `feat(awareness): graduated status surface (scenario × answer_mode) replacing raw-field rendering (#1759 #1769)`\n\n### Commit 6 — Teaser date anchor for >24h-old catch-up notes\n\n**Files**\n- `server/agent/awareness-delivery.ts:123-148` (`SINGLE_NOTE_TEMPLATE` + age-gated wrapper)\n- `tests/server/agent/awareness-delivery.test.ts` (or wherever teaser template is currently tested)\n\n**Tests:**\n1. `noteDateAgeHours <= 24` (note dated today/yesterday at delivery time) → template unchanged from current.\n2. `noteDateAgeHours > 24` → assistant block forbids `today` / `yesterday` / `今天` / `昨天` and includes an explicit-date-anchor instruction (e.g., requires the model to reference the noteDate explicitly).\n3. Boundary: at exactly 24.0h, treated as `<= 24h` (use strict `>`).\n\n**Implementation:**\n- Extend `SINGLE_NOTE_TEMPLATE` (or wrap the PromptDecoration block builder at lines 436-447) to take a `staleCatchUp` flag derived from `noteDateAgeHours > 24` (matches the v1.1 watch-metric threshold so they align).\n- When `staleCatchUp`, append a directive: \"Note date is older than yesterday. Anchor the teaser to the date explicitly (e.g., '前两天那条…' / 'about 5/8…'). Avoid relative-time words like today/yesterday/今天/昨天.\"\n- No new logging. The existing `noteDateAgeHours` field at `delivery_selected` already exists; the watch metric is read-only post-launch.\n\n**Commit message:** `feat(awareness): require explicit date anchor for stale catch-up teasers (#1764)`\n\n## Critical Files Reference\n\n| Area | File | Key lines |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tool schema fix | `server/agent/tools/reflection.ts` | 121-194 |\n| Tool definition type | `server/agent/tools/define.ts` | 6 |\n| Classifier fingerprints | `server/agent/awareness-failure-classifier.ts` | 39-50 |\n| Failover orchestration | `server/cron/memory-cron.ts` | 394-571, 649, 733, 817 |\n| Language detection | `server/cron/memory-cron.ts` | 275-289, 624, 636 |\n| Reflection task assembly | `server/cron/memory-cron.ts` | 795-815 |\n| Reflect guide | `server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts` | 780-879 |\n| Status tool | `server/agent/tools/awareness-status-read.ts` | full file |\n| Derived counts | `server/agent/awareness-status.ts` | 264-287, 443-503 |\n| Status types | `shared/awareness-status.ts` | 45-62 |\n| Teaser template | `server/agent/awareness-delivery.ts` | 123-148, 60-62, 384, 436-447 |\n| Awareness surface block | `server/agent/prompt-blocks.ts` | 1066-1120 |\n\n## Verification\n\nPer commit:\n1. `pnpm exec vitest run <changed-test-file>` — RED before implementing, GREEN after.\n2. After each commit, `pnpm exec tsc -p server/tsconfig.json --noEmit` to catch type-level regressions (Commits 2 and 3b in particular).\n\nEnd-to-end after all commits:\n1. Run the full test suite: `pnpm test`.\n2. Manual cron smoke: run `pnpm tsx scripts/show-system-prompt.ts` after Commit 4 to inspect assembled reflection prompt with the new directive.\n3. Manual tool inspection: call `awareness_status_read` against a synthetic `status.json` fixture covering each scenario × intent to eyeball the rendered copy before merging Commit 5b. Per docs/testing.md, exact copy strings won't be asserted but should be human-reviewed.\n4. Spec doc cross-check: open `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-11-…md` and walk each Decision's \"Chosen shape\" against what shipped. Any drift gets called out in the PR description.\n\n## Out of Scope (per spec)\n\n- Catch-up policy redesign; only delivery framing changes.\n- Unconditional 24h-unannounced rule (deferred to v1.1 behind watch metric).\n- Cloud-side `ModelConfig` capability metadata.\n- Failure-streak hint copy split (current copy stays in v1).\n- Historical `failed_unknown` reclassification (spec open question 4 default: no repair).\n- Documentation updates (will be handled after technical implementation per user instruction).\n</plan>","The plan 