re follows the convention of the neighboring specs:\n\n- **Problem** — three issues with the current button (tonal, structural mis-targeting, two parallel workflows) + what we cannot lose in cleanup (debuggability of quality complaints, per #1721)\n- **Decision 1** — remove the reader button + the whole `awareness-report/` directory\n- **Decision 2** — opt-in checkbox in the standard feedback dialog; scope expanded to notes + drafts + episodes + un-redacted `briefSentence`; 3-day window matching the rest of the bundle. Includes an explicit \"why we're re-litigating 2026-05-07 § Decision 4\" section since that spec rejected the checkbox approach.\n- **Decision 3** — re-target `sustained_failure.suggestedNextStep` (recommend removing entirely; the affordance was mis-targeted)\n- **Decision 4** — auto-attach `[viewing: <date>]` to descriptions when feedback opens from the reader\n\nEngineering notes cover the concrete removal/addition surface (file list), the new `status-with-content.json` companion file (so the existing `status.json` redaction path stays untouched), bundle README updates, test changes, documentation cleanup across the three agent docs, and a rollout note recommending a pre-merge usage check on the `[reported-note: ...]` prefix.\n\nFour **Open Questions for Review** at the end give the reviewer specific things to push back on: checkbox copy, dialog visibility when no awareness content exists, whether the viewing tag should be gated on the checkbox, and whether `awarenessSurfaceBlock` should gain a one-line affordance hint.","from the settings UI perspective (for the log related section), whats going to be changed and whats the wording, express with a diagram, I assume you probably want the toggle itself to have a short label, but you likely want to add some secondary text that explains what it does.","The spec is updated per our discussion. I've done an initial implementation against it. Code-review my changes.\n\nEvaluate:\n- correctness / bugs\n- UX impact\n- performance\n- over-engineering\n- consistency with existing patterns\n- edge cases\n\nFor each issue: rate severity (critical / moderate / minor) and suggest a concrete fix with enough detail to act on. Beyond line-level review, also assess whether the implementation actually solves the intended problem.\n\nBelow is a commit summary for high-level context — review the current state of the codebase as a whole, not commit-by-commit.\n\n---\n\nAll three commits on fix/remove-imprint-report, in the chosen order (remove →\n   add → prompts):\n\n  - 68afa541 — removes the reader button + reportedNote chain + 6 i18n keys +\n  the dedicated test file. Spec landed alongside.\n  - 1e2d8a77 — adds the opt-in checkbox + collectAwarenessContentEntries helper\n   + new bundle README section + 2 new i18n keys per locale. 7 TDD slices in\n  feedback-package.test.ts.\n  - e318c0dc — drops suggestedNextStep from sustained_failure (was pointing at\n  the deleted button), adds the one quality-debug section to\n  awarenessSurfaceBlock. Two awareness-status-read tests adjusted.\n\n  Verification status: full suite at 2032 passing (was 2026 before this work —\n  net +6 tests after removing one obsolete severity-driven assertion).\n  Typecheck clean. Rendered prompt shows the new \"When the user complains an\n  Imprint felt off\" section. rg returns zero hits for any of the removed\n  symbols (reportedNote|reportImprint|ReportedNoteAttachment|AwarenessReportAct\n  ion|awareness-report|REPORT_HINT|Report this 心迹|举报这条心迹).\n\n  Per the plan, docs updates (docs/agent/awareness.md, proactive-delivery.md,\n  imprints-reader.md) are handled separately after technical implementation\n  lands. Manual smoke (open dev build, verify checkbox hides on empty install /\n   appears when notes exist, toggle on/off, inspect produced zip) is the last\n  item before merge.","Per your suggestion, I've updated the relevant files, I decied to keep the same label, but in addition to that I followed your recommendations. Please recheck.","can you fix them wait your recommended solutions"],"019e1f89-a18e-7d20-b0f5-9234208a9da4":["Before we move to production, I want to consider a real business requirement we are facing that may change how we implement our Stripe integration.\n\nOur current billing and Stripe payment system is built around a self-service model. Users find the website, create an organization, and if they like the product, they pay for seats. That is a traditional self-service SaaS model, and it is definitely something we want to support long-term.\n\nHowever, since we are in the very early phases of development, our business model is more manual than that. We don't expect many automatic users to just find the app. Usually, we already have an agreement with customers or organizations to use itell. Because these customers are not necessarily technical, it isn't very handy for them to create an organization and handle things like importing a volume.\n\nCurrently, our CEO makes the agreement, creates the organization, and fills it with necessary information (updating the title, importing volumes, and sending invitation emails to members). This creates several issues:\n\n1. Ownership Mismatch\n   The CEO is currently the owner of the organization because he created it. While he can promote members to admins, it creates a mismatch regarding who actually manages the billing.\n\n2. Trial Period Conflict\n   We offer a one-month trial, but these early organizations often run very short cycles. It might only take two weeks for learners to finish a volume. If we keep the standard trial, we may never collect any money. We probably need a way to turn this off or create a special case for these manual onboardings.\n\n3. Content Accessibility and Subscription\n   Our current model requires an active subscription before an admin can see the content. However, we don't want our CEO to pay for a subscription just to onboard a customer.\n   (a) We could use an internal plan, but that gets complicated when we want to cancel it and transition the users to a real subscription.\n   (b) The future organization owners (the real customer managers) need to see the volume to propose edits and get a feel for the platform before they require their learners to pay for seats.\n\nGiven our early-phase nature, I am thinking about how we should restructure our billing model. Please analyze this and propose:\n\n1. Suggestions for our CEO on how to improve the manual onboarding process.\n2. An updated or new model for our Stripe implementation that resolves these conflicts.\n\n---\n\nDO NOT CHANGE ANY CODE YET. Step back and reason about the module/feature holistically before proposing any fix.\n\n1. State the real problem and the underlying UX goal in your own words. If my framing seems off, push back before going further.\n2. Evaluate the current design against that goal — where does it fall short, and is the issue local or structural?\n3. From first principles, present 2–3 approaches with concrete tradeoffs (complexity, blast radius, UX impact, future flexibility). Recommend one and explain why.\n\nDon't patch a flawed design with another patch. Don't shy away from large-scale changes when they're justified — but be explicit about what they cost.\n","Before I finalize the plan, one thing I want to make clear is that our goal is not to support the CEO's current workflow. Our real goal is to support a workflow that precedes the organization, perhaps using volumes or some specific configuration. Essentially, we are creating a new organization, but I would like it to be a more automated process, possibly using a script.\n\nOnce we have an agreement with a customer, we would work on some volumes in the CMS. Once a volume is ready, we want to start a process to:\n1. Create an organization.\n2. Import the volume.\n3. Send invitation emails to ensure everyone is invited.\n\nThis process does not necessarily have to involve the CEO. While the CEO will likely want to preview the volume and be part of the invitation, we want to give organization admins or owners (or the CEO, acting as a platform owner) some time to preview the content. This trial period probably shouldn't require payment or an active subscription, though I haven't decided yet whether we should limit that preview time.\n\nAfter that, if the admins dislike the formatting or content, we can update the volume in our CMS. Once it is ready for the learners, we will prompt them to start an active subscription, likely using the same system we have now.\r\rThe point I'm trying to make is that you don't need to consider our current workflow as something we are trying to support. It is just a reflection of our current business process for customer onboarding. There are better ways to do this, such as:\r1. Bringing in more automation.\r2. Reducing the manual work required from both me as a developer and the CEO.\r3. Streamlining the process according to specific Stripe features or workflows.\r\rJust an extra comment on that. and see if that changes your position.","Can you now give me a complete proposal on your recommended solution, which is hybrid? \n\nTry to make this more of a standalone thing that anyone can review. Please structure it as follows:\n\n1. Problem definition\n2. Why you think the current approach is lacking\n3. Your suggested solution\n4. Potential caveats \n5. Why you think your solution can solve the problem (highlighting where it is strong and where it might fall short)","A senior engineer reviewed your proposal and provided critical feedback below.\n\nFor each point:\n1. Assess whether it's valid — be honest, don't agree just to agree.\n2. If valid: propose a fix (which may be better than what the engineer suggested) and explain why.\n3. If you disagree: explain from first principles why the original is correct. If a fix is simple and improves system design, I suggest you work on it rather than defer because it is “minor.”\n\nDo not change any code yet — focus on analysis.\n\n---\n\nHere's the write-up, polished as a peer review you can send.\n\n---\n\n# Review of \"Customer Launch / Provisioning\" proposal\n\n## Verdict (TL;DR)\n\nStrong proposal — we landed on the same shape (provisioning-first, script before UI, billing gate moves off content, Stripe stays for actual activation), so the broad direction is well-corroborated. I'd absorb three of your refinements that I missed in my own draft. I'd push back on one significant piece — the durable `customer_launches` entity — where I think the cost outweighs the benefit at our current stage. Combined recommendation at the end.\n\n## Where we converge\n\nWe agree on the substance:\n\n- **Provisioning is first-class**, not a CEO-acting-as-customer side effect.\n- **Script before UI** — the script is the API; UI can come later on the same primitives.\n- **Don't fake a Stripe subscription during preview.** No internal plan, no zero-dollar sub.\n- **Move the subscription gate off content reads** and onto learner-attributable writes / learner invite.\n- **Trial policy is per-org configurable**, not a global assumption.\n- **Stripe Checkout + Customer Portal remain the right tools** for activation and ongoing self-service.\n\nI'll treat these as settled and focus on the deltas.\n\n## Where you're right and I'm folding in\n\nThree points I missed or under-specified in my own draft. Yours is stronger:\n\n### 1. Explicit reviewer-permission enumeration during preview\n\nI hand-waved this. You're right that the surface needs to be decided product-side before the gate refactor:\n\n- View imported content — yes (the whole point)\n- Invite additional admins / reviewers — likely yes\n- Invite learners — no (this is the activation gate)\n- Import / generate additional volumes — open question\n- Generate preview-mode learner activity — likely no, and if yes must be excluded from cohort aggregates the same way admin rows already are\n\nTreating these as product decisions, not implementation details, is the right framing.\n\n### 2. Payload content versioning at provisioning\n\nI never addressed this. Real question: when the script \"imports volume X,\" does the org see the live CMS head, a snapshot at provisioning time, or a specific published version? If CMS edits are still landing after provisioning, the answer determines whether the customer admin's preview reflects ongoing work or a frozen reference. Needs to be made explicit — `volumeId` alone is underspecified.\n\n### 3. Auth scope and ownership semantics for the provisioning script\n\nYou flagged `platformAdminActionClient` and the risk of platform operators ending up with hidden permanent ownership of customer orgs. I touched on \"script creates with the right owner from minute one\" but didn't surface the governance concern. To be explicit:\n\n- Script authenticates as a platform-admin actor, not the customer owner\n- Customer owner is an **input** to the script (`ownerEmail`); they become owner via invite acceptance\n- Platform admins are not implicit members of provisioned orgs\n\nThis matters for audit and for not having to write an ownership-transfer flow later.\n\n## Where I'd push back: the `customer_launches` entity\n\nThis is the substantive disagreement.\n\nYou propose a durable `customer_launches` table with a six-state machine: `draft | provisioning | reviewing | ready_for_billing | active | canceled`. I'd argue this is premature at our scale and would propose deferring it.\n\n**What it gives us:**\n- Audit trail of the onboarding process itself, separate from the org\n- A place to record cancelled deals that never produced an org\n- A workflow surface for future admin UI\n- Conceptual separation between \"deal pipeline\" and \"org artifact\"\n\n**Why I don't think it pulls its weight yet:**\n\n1. **It models a sales pipeline we don't have.** At roughly 5-20 launches a year run by a CEO and an engineer, the audit context lives in Slack, email, and a `launches/acme.yaml` checked into git. The information density of a `customer_launches` row is low — most fields are either already on the org (name, slug, members) or are script inputs.\n\n2. **The six-state machine has redundancy:**\n   - `reviewing` ≡ `org.lifecycleState = preview AND learner_count = 0` — derived, not stored\n   - `ready_for_billing` isn't a state — it's the moment an admin clicks \"Activate billing\"; that's an action, not persisted status\n   - `provisioning` is transient (script runtime, ~seconds)\n   - `draft` is \"we haven't run the script yet\" — the absence of a row in `organizations`, not a row in `launches`\n   - `canceled` for pre-org cancellation is \"we never ran the script\" — silence\n\n   Collapsing the redundancies leaves `preview | active`, which is what lifecycle state on the org already expresses.\n\n3. **Parallel lifecycles drift.** A launch with `status = active` and an org with `lifecycleState = suspended` (because billing failed) is the kind of inconsistency that bites you in reconciliation, dashboards, and aggregates. Single source of truth is cheaper.\n\n4. **It's cheap to add later, expensive to remove.** If the funnel grows past ~50 launches/year and we genuinely need queries like \"show me launches stuck in review > 30 days,\" introduce it then. By that point we'll know which fields matter from operational pain, not speculation.\n\n**On the \"deal canceled before org existed\" case** — the motivating example for a launch entity — I'd argue silence is the right modeling. Cancelled deals that never produced an org don't need a row; not running the script is the cancellation. The cost of modeling cancelled deals is paid every day forever (queries, dashboards, list filters all need to handle it); the benefit is rare retrospective lookups.\n\n**My counter-proposal for the same goal:**\n\nAchieve everything `customer_launches` would give us with cheaper primitives:\n\n- **Inputs**: versioned config file in repo (`launches/acme.yaml`) — git is the audit log\n- **Outputs**: columns on the org — `provisioned_at`, `provisioned_by_actor_id`, `provisioned_from_volume_id`, `provisioned_from_config_hash`\n- **Lifecycle**: on the org itself — `preview | active | suspended`\n- **Per-launch audit**: append-only `provisioning_events` table if needed — strictly logging, no state machine\n\nThe question I'd want answered before reversing this position: **what specific query or workflow do you expect to run against `customer_launches` that you can't run against orgs + git history + an audit log?** If you can name 2-3 concrete examples, that tips toward yes. If they're speculative (\"we might want to see…\"), I'd defer.\n\n## Where I think the proposal under-uses Stripe primitives\n\nThree Stripe-specific patterns that aren't surfaced in the proposal but should be:\n\n1. **`trial_end: 'now'` on the activation checkout session.** This is the Stripe-native way to spin up a subscription with no trial. Your `trialPolicy: \"no_trial\"` config should map directly to this parameter, not a custom skip-trial code path.\n\n2. **Lazy Stripe customer creation.** Don't create a Stripe customer at provisioning. Create at activation. Keeps reconciliation clean (preview orgs simply have no mirror in Stripe — a state the recon code handles gracefully today) and matches the \"we don't owe anything until learners are billed\" mental model.\n\n3. **Stripe Quotes** as a future option. For our sales-led motion, Quotes are the most directly relevant Stripe feature (\"we agreed off-platform; here's a formal artifact you accept later, acceptance spawns the subscription\"). Heavier setup than we need initially, but the state machine should leave room to slot them in for procurement-heavy customers.\n\n4. **Subscription metadata `provisioned_via: 'script'`** so analytics / reconciliation can distinguish sales-led from self-service orgs without a join.\n\n## Synthesized recommendation\n\nCombining the strengths:\n\n### Provisioning script (`scripts/provision-org.ts`)\n\n- Inputs: `{ volumeIds, volumeVersionPolicy, orgName, orgSlug, ownerEmail, adminEmails, trialPolicy, agreedSeatCount? }`\n- Runs under `platformAdminActionClient` scope (your point)\n- Creates org in `lifecycleState = preview` with the customer owner as the row's owner via invite-acceptance flow\n- Imports volumes per `volumeVersionPolicy` (your point — explicit decision needed)\n- Sends invitations to admins/reviewers (not learners)\n- Writes audit entries: `provisioned_at`, `provisioned_by_actor_id`, `provisioned_from_volume_id`, `provisioned_from_config_hash`\n- **Does not** create a Stripe customer or subscription\n\n### Schema additions on `organizations` / `organization_billing`\n\n- `organization.lifecycleState: 'preview' | 'active' | 'suspended'`\n- `organization.provisioned_at`, `provisioned_by_actor_id`, `provisioned_from_volume_id`, `provisioned_from_config_hash`\n- `organization_billing.trial_policy: 'none' | 'standard_30d' | 'custom_until'` (your enum, slightly simplified)\n\n### Reviewer permissions during `preview` (your point — needs product sign-off)\n\nExplicit allow-list for `preview` state:\n- ✅ Read all imported content\n- ✅ Invite additional admins / reviewers\n- ❌ Invite learners (this is the activation trigger)\n- ❓ Import additional volumes (open)\n- ❌ Generate learner activity / progress\n\n### Activation flow (Stripe-native)\n\n- Customer admin clicks \"Activate billing\"\n- Server lazily creates Stripe customer\n- Generates checkout session with:\n  - Seat count (from `agreedSeatCount` or admin input)\n  - `subscription_data.trial_end: 'now'` when `trial_policy = 'none'`\n  - `subscription_data.metadata: { provisioned_via: 'script', org_id, volume_id }`\n- `checkout.session.completed` webhook flips org `preview → active`\n- Learner invitations now unlocked\n\n### Trial policy mapping\n\n| Policy         | Stripe call                   |\n| -------------- | ----------------------------- |\n| `none`         | `trial_end: 'now'`            |\n| `standard_30d` | `trial_period_days: 30`       |\n| `custom_until` | `trial_end: <unix-timestamp>` |\n\n### Deferred (not now)\n\n- `customer_launches` entity — revisit at ~50 launches/year or if specific queries demand it\n- Stripe Quotes integration — revisit if procurement-heavy customers materialize\n- Admin UI on top of the provisioning script — script-first proves the primitives\n\n## Open product decisions\n\nThese are blockers for drafting the schema migration. None is an engineering call:\n\n1. **Volume version policy at provisioning** — live head, frozen snapshot, or Payload published version?\n2. **Reviewer permission surface** — confirm the allow-list above. Specifically: can preview admins invite additional admins, and can they import additional volumes?\n3. **Preview-window expiry** — uncapped, or soft-suspend after N days to prevent stale orgs? My default would be uncapped initially; revisit if we see orgs sit indefinitely.\n4. **`customer_launches` — confirm deferral**, or name 2-3 queries / workflows that would justify building it now.\n\n## Suggested next step\n\nIf we're aligned on the synthesized recommendation, the natural next artifact is the schema migration + provisioning-script signature as a concrete RFC. That's roughly half a day of writing; it'll surface anything we glossed over in this abstract back-and-forth.\n\nIf you want to make the case for `customer_launches` more concretely, the most productive form would be a list of the queries / operational workflows you expect to need it for. That'd let us judge it on its actual return-on-complexity rather than its conceptual cleanliness.\n\n---\n\nEnd of review. Copy as-is or trim to taste.","So your response is integrated. I have now come up with a specification of how we're going to implement the feature. \n\nSpecifically, I decided that we're going to have first-class Admin UI support for this. We talked about maybe starting from a scripting version and then migrating it to the admin dashboard later, but I think we're going to need it eventually anyway. It is good for people to be able to use it in the UI, and since we already have the Admin Control Center structure, it wouldn't be that hard to integrate this provisioning feature. \n\nI decided to include it in the spec. Now I want you to critically review it and let me know what you think. Are there things you would like to revise or improve? Let me know.\n\n\n⏺ Spec written to\n  docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-13-customer-launch-provisioning.md.\n\n  What the explorers changed in the spec vs. our prior discussions\n\n  Three corrections worth flagging:\n\n  1. The subscription gate already lives in the right place.\n  checkLearnerSeatAllowed enforces billing at invitation creation, accept\n  hooks, seat changes, and SCORM provision — not in layouts. Admin content\n  reads were never gated by billing. So the \"move the gate\" framing from\n  earlier rounds was based on a wrong assumption; the new work is a single\n  lifecycle-state check at the learner-invite entry point, not a gate\n  refactor.\n  2. authClient.organization.create() forces creator = owner. Better Auth's\n   plugin doesn't expose an override. Provisioning has to bypass it: create\n   the org row directly, create invitations rows with role: 'owner' for the\n   customer, and rely on Better Auth's existing afterAcceptInvitation hook\n  to mint the members row. The invitations.role column is permissive\n  enough; only the application-level inviteEmailsSchema filters to\n  ['member', 'admin'], so a separate platform-admin-only invitation path\n  that permits 'owner' is what's needed.\n  3. Volume version policy is the existing default. Payload's\n  /volumes/versions endpoint already returns the latest version, which is\n  exactly what versionPolicy: 'published_head' means. No new version\n  infrastructure to build — just a column to capture the resolved version\n  at submission for audit.","We have formalized this into a technical plan incorporating your spec suggestions. Can you review the plan and let me know what you think?\n\n---\n\n<plan>\n# Customer Launch — Provisioning Implementation Plan\n\n## Context\n\nThis plan implements the design in `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-13-customer-launch-provisioning.md`. The platform currently couples org creation, ownership, and billing into a single self-service step. For our actual go-to-market motion (off-platform agreement → content authored in Payload → org seeded by iTELL → customer admins preview → customer activates billing → learners rolled out), that coupling forces a workaround (`attachInternalPlan`) that leaves the CEO as permanent owner, burns trial calendar time, and complicates reconciliation.\n\nThe implementation introduces:\n\n- A `preview` lifecycle state on `organizations` (no Stripe presence, learners blocked).\n- A `customer_launches` table backing a new `/admin/launches` admin surface (drafts + audit; not a workflow engine).\n- A provisioning service that bypasses `authClient.organization.create()` and writes Better-Auth-compatible rows transactionally.\n- Trial policy on the org, mapped to native Stripe Checkout parameters at activation.\n- Lifecycle awareness inside `checkLearnerSeatAllowed` so all five existing learner-onboarding paths pick up preview blocking with one change.\n- A deprovisioning path with snapshot-based audit identity preservation.\n\nSelf-service org creation and the existing `attachInternalPlan` UI remain unchanged.\n\n## TDD strategy\n\nPer user direction: focus on **business logic**, not on wrappers around external systems (Stripe, Better Auth, Payload, email) or UI.\n\n### What we test\n\n| Surface | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `checkLearnerSeatAllowed` lifecycle awareness — new `preview` reason returned ahead of existing checks | Central gate; pure-ish behavior; covers five call sites via one helper |\n| Provisioning service — config hashing, idempotency on re-submission of unchanged inputs, refusal on hash mismatch, input → org column copying, lifecycle state initialization | Orchestration logic that owns correctness of the new feature |\n| Trial policy → Stripe params mapping — pure function returning the `subscription_data` object | Highest-correctness-impact pure function; got it wrong once already |\n| Deprovisioning rules — refuses on `active`, requires slug confirmation, sets snapshot columns | Pure state-machine logic |\n| Webhook lifecycle flip — given a `checkout.session.completed` event with admin-launch metadata against a `preview` org, the lifecycle flips to `active`; without that metadata, lifecycle is untouched | Branch logic added to the existing handler; testable without invoking Stripe SDK |\n\n### What we do *not* test\n\n- Stripe API calls themselves (Checkout session creation, customer creation, subscription state). Mock at the boundary.\n- Better Auth's `afterAcceptInvitation` hook behavior. We rely on its documented contract.\n- Email rendering and delivery.\n- Payload CMS calls (volume picker reads).\n- React component rendering or form interactions.\n- Drizzle's own behavior — we don't reassert that `INSERT INTO ... VALUES ...` works.\n\n### Test conventions to match house style\n\n- Co-located `__tests__/*.test.ts` (preferred) or alongside-file `*.test.ts`.\n- DB mocked via `vi.mock(\"@/db\", ...)` (no transactional DB in tests).\n- Inline fixtures; no shared fixture directory.\n- `vi.mock` external collaborators (Stripe SDK, Better Auth API, `nanoid`/`crypto` if needed).\n- Pure-function tests where possible — no mocks at all when the logic is extractable.\n\n### TDD cadence per commit\n\nVertical slices: one test → one minimal implementation step → next test. Use `test.todo` to stub the slate of behaviors per module before working through them. Run `pnpm vitest -t \"<name>\" --run` during the inner loop; full file run before committing.\n\n## Commit breakdown\n\nFive focused commits, created as I progress (not batched at the end).\n\n### Commit 1 — Schema + lifecycle gate in `checkLearnerSeatAllowed`\n\nSmallest deployable slice. The gate change is independently valuable (a `preview`-state org existing without the gate is dangerous), so it ships with the schema that makes it possible.\n\n**Schema changes** (`src/db/schemas/`):\n- `auth.schema.ts` — extend `organizations` with `lifecycleState` (text, default `'active'`, backfilled for existing rows), `trialPolicy` (text, default `'standard_30d'`), `provisionedByActorId` (text nullable, FK → users), `provisionedFromLaunchId` (text nullable), `provisionedFromConfigHash` (text nullable).\n- New `src/db/schemas/customer-launches.schema.ts` — `customer_launches` table per spec. Two-state `status: 'draft' | 'submitted'`, snapshot columns (`resultingOrgIdSnapshot`, `resultingOrgSlugSnapshot`), deprovision fields, `configHash`, JSON columns for volume imports and admin emails.\n- `src/db/schema.ts` — re-export the new schema.\n\n**Schemas/validation**:\n- Extend application-level invitation role schemas (`src/features/organization/schemas.ts`) with a platform-admin-only variant that allows `'owner'`. Existing `inviteEmailsSchema` (member/admin only) stays as is for org-driven invites.\n\n**Gate change** (`src/features/billing/policy.ts`):\n- Extend `SeatCheckResult` reason union with `'preview'`.\n- In `checkLearnerSeatAllowed`, fetch `organizations.lifecycleState` alongside billing; return `{ allowed: false, reason: 'preview' }` *before* the existing entitlement/subscription checks if state is `'preview'`.\n- Update existing callers to handle the new reason in their error UX where they branch on `result.reason`.\n\n**Tests** (`src/features/billing/__tests__/policy.test.ts` — new):\n- Mocked `@/db`, `getOrganizationBilling`, `getLearnerCount`, plus a new fetcher for lifecycle state.\n- Test: returns `preview` reason for a `preview` org regardless of subscription/entitlement state.\n- Test: returns existing reasons unchanged for `active` orgs.\n- Test: `preview` reason short-circuits before `unlimited-seats` entitlement check (a `preview` org with bogus entitlement state still blocks).\n\n**Migration**: generate via Drizzle from the schema changes; backfill `lifecycleState = 'active'` and `trialPolicy = 'standard_30d'` for all existing rows.\n\n**Commit message theme**: `feat(provisioning): add preview lifecycle state and gate learner onboarding`\n\n### Commit 2 — Provisioning service + customer-launch CRUD actions\n\nThe heart of the feature. The service is the API; UI consumes it later.\n\n**Provisioning service** (`src/features/provisioning/service.ts` — new):\n- `provisionOrganization({ actorUserId, launchId })` — reads the launch row, computes the input hash, opens a Drizzle transaction:\n  1. Insert `organizations` row with `lifecycleState: 'preview'`, copy `trialPolicy` onto it, set `provisionedByActorId / provisionedFromLaunchId / provisionedFromConfigHash`.\n  2. For each bundled Payload volume: insert a `teams` row (direct insert into Better Auth's `teams` table, matching the schema in `src/db/schemas/auth.schema.ts:107-121`), then an `organization_volumes` row with `teamId` populated. Direct insert is a deliberate choice over `auth.api.createTeam()` to honor the transactional invariant in the spec; consistent with the existing direct-insert pattern in `syncAllLearnersToVolumeTeam` (`src/features/volume-access/team-sync.ts`).\n  3. Insert `invitations` rows: one for the prospective owner (`role: 'owner'`, `accessScope: 'all'`), one per co-admin (`role: 'admin'`, `accessScope: 'all'`). For each, also insert `invitation_volumes` rows referencing each bundled `organization_volumes` row so the existing email template at `src/features/organization/invitation-emails.ts:22-69` renders course names correctly without a template change.\n  4. Update the launch row: `status: 'submitted'`, `submittedAt`, `resultingOrgIdSnapshot`, `resultingOrgSlugSnapshot`.\n- After commit: send invitation emails via the existing `sendInvitationEmailForId` path. Email failures do not roll back; admin can resend.\n- Idempotency: if the launch row already has `submittedAt` set and the input hash matches `configHash`, the service is a no-op returning the resulting org snapshot. If the launch was submitted but hash now differs (someone edited inputs after submission — should be prevented at the UI layer but defensive), refuse with a clear error.\n\n**Server actions** (`src/app/admin/launches/actions.ts` — new):\n- `createLaunchDraft`, `updateLaunchDraft`, `deleteLaunchDraft`, `submitLaunch` — all wrapped by `platformAdminActionClient`.\n- Input schemas validated with zod; volume-imports schema requires non-empty array.\n- `submitLaunch` calls the provisioning service.\n\n**Tests** (`src/features/provisioning/__tests__/service.test.ts` — new):\n- Mocked `@/db` returning a stub Drizzle transaction builder (pattern from `write-completion.test.ts`).\n- Test: provisioning copies `trialPolicy` from launch onto the org.\n- Test: provisioning sets `lifecycleState: 'preview'` on the org.\n- Test: provisioning hashes inputs deterministically (same inputs → same hash).\n- Test: re-submitting an already-submitted launch with matching hash is a no-op (returns the snapshot, does not re-insert).\n- Test: re-submitting with mismatched hash throws.\n- Test: provisioning creates one `teams` row per bundled volume.\n- Test: provisioning sets `teamId` on each `organization_volumes` row.\n- Test: provisioning creates `invitations` row for owner with `role: 'owner'`.\n- Test: provisioning creates `invitation_volumes` rows for each owner/admin invitation linking to all bundled volumes.\n\n**Test exclusion**: email sending is fire-and-forget after commit; not part of provisioning's behavior tests.\n\n**Commit message theme**: `feat(provisioning): add customer-launch service and admin CRUD actions`\n\n### Commit 3 — `/admin/launches` UI\n\nUI on top of the actions from commit 2. No tests for UI per user direction.\n\n**New routes**:\n- `src/app/admin/launches/page.tsx` — list view: drafts (with \"Continue\") + recently-submitted launches (with link to resulting org).\n- `src/app/admin/launches/new/page.tsx` — new draft form (creates a draft on first save).\n- `src/app/admin/launches/[id]/page.tsx` — edit draft / view submitted launch.\n\n**Components** (`src/app/admin/launches/_components/`):\n- `launch-form.tsx` — the form (fields: orgName, orgSlug, ownerEmail, additionalAdminEmails, volumeImports, trialPolicy, optional agreedSeatCount).\n- `volume-picker.tsx` — multi-select Payload volume picker, reusing the pattern from `src/app/admin/public-volumes/_components/add-from-payload-panel.tsx` and the `getPayloadVolumesList()` server fetch.\n- `launch-table.tsx` — list table.\n\n**Admin hub update**:\n- Add a card to `/admin/page.tsx` for \"Customer launches\" alongside Organizations and Public volumes.\n\n**Commit message theme**: `feat(provisioning): add /admin/launches UI`\n\n### Commit 4 — Activation flow + webhook lifecycle flip\n\nWires `preview → active` through the existing Checkout + webhook plumbing.\n\n**Activation action** (extends `src/app/(portal)/org/[orgSlug]/(owner)/billing/actions.ts`):\n- `activateBilling` server action — refuses if `lifecycleState !== 'preview'`. Reads `trialPolicy` from the org, calls `ensureStripeCustomer` (existing helper), constructs Checkout params via a new pure helper `buildActivationCheckoutParams({ org, trialPolicy, seatCount })`.\n\n**Trial policy mapping** (`src/features/billing/trial-policy.ts` — new):\n- Pure function `trialParamsForCheckout(policy: TrialPolicy): Pick<SubscriptionDataParams, 'trial_period_days' | 'trial_end'>` — returns `{}` for `'none'`, `{ trial_period_days: 30 }` for `'standard_30d'`, etc. Matches the existing conditional-spread pattern in `createHostedCheckoutSession` at `src/features/billing/stripe.ts:99-122`.\n\n**Checkout metadata**:\n- Extend `subscription_data.metadata` to carry `organization_id`, `launch_id` (nullable; null for self-service activations), `provisioned_via: 'admin_launch' | 'self_service'`.\n\n**Webhook handler** (`src/app/api/stripe/webhook/route.ts:206-262`):\n- Inside the existing `checkout.session.completed` branch, after `syncSubscriptionForWebhook` succeeds, read `session.subscription_data?.metadata?.provisioned_via` (or pull from the synced subscription's metadata). If `'admin_launch'`, update `organizations.lifecycleState` from `'preview'` to `'active'` for the `organizationId`. Use a WHERE clause that requires `lifecycleState = 'preview'` so this is idempotent on webhook retries.\n\n**Tests**:\n- `src/features/billing/__tests__/trial-policy.test.ts` — pure-function tests for the three policy cases (`none`, `standard_30d`, plus a forward-compatible `custom_until` test stubbed via `test.todo`).\n- `src/features/provisioning/__tests__/webhook-lifecycle.test.ts` — given a mocked webhook handler context with admin-launch metadata, asserts the lifecycle flip happens; without that metadata, no flip. Mocks the DB and `syncSubscriptionForWebhook`.\n\n**Commit message theme**: `feat(provisioning): wire preview→active activation via Checkout`\n\n### Commit 5 — Deprovisioning\n\nCloses the loop for deals that fall through after provisioning.\n\n**Action** (extends `src/app/admin/launches/actions.ts`):\n- `deprovisionLaunch({ launchId, slugConfirmation })` — under `platformAdminActionClient`.\n- Reads the launch; refuses if no `resultingOrgIdSnapshot` (nothing to deprovision) or if the org's `lifecycleState !== 'preview'`.\n- Requires `slugConfirmation === resultingOrgSlugSnapshot`.\n- Inside a transaction: hard-delete the `organizations` row (cascade deletes `organization_volumes`, `teams`, pending `invitations`). Update the launch row with `deprovisionedAt`, `deprovisionedByActorId`, `deprovisionReason`.\n- Snapshot columns (`resultingOrgIdSnapshot`, `resultingOrgSlugSnapshot`) are preserved — they were captured at submission, not derived from the FK.\n\n**UI affordance**:\n- \"Deprovision\" button on `/admin/launches/[id]` for submitted launches whose org is in `preview`. Confirmation dialog requires typing the slug.\n\n**Tests** (`src/features/provisioning/__tests__/deprovision.test.ts` — new):\n- Test: refuses if launch is not submitted.\n- Test: refuses if org is `active`.\n- Test: refuses if slug confirmation doesn't match snapshot.\n- Test: sets `deprovisionedAt`, `deprovisionedByActorId`, `deprovisionReason`.\n- Test: leaves `resultingOrgIdSnapshot` / `resultingOrgSlugSnapshot` intact.\n\n**Commit message theme**: `feat(provisioning): add deprovisioning for preview-state launches`\n\n## Critical files\n\n### Will modify\n- `src/db/schemas/auth.schema.ts` — `organizations` column additions; new role enum is optional.\n- `src/db/schema.ts` — re-export.\n- `src/features/organization/schemas.ts` — invitation role schema for platform-admin path.\n- `src/features/billing/policy.ts` — lifecycle awareness in `checkLearnerSeatAllowed`.\n- `src/features/billing/stripe.ts` — `createHostedCheckoutSession` accepts `trialPolicy` and `launchId` for metadata. (Or call site changes if we keep the existing signature pure.)\n- `src/app/(portal)/org/[orgSlug]/(owner)/billing/actions.ts` — `activateBilling` action.\n- `src/app/api/stripe/webhook/route.ts` — `checkout.session.completed` branch for lifecycle flip.\n- `src/app/admin/page.tsx` — admin hub card.\n\n### Will create\n- `src/db/schemas/customer-launches.schema.ts`\n- `src/features/provisioning/service.ts`\n- `src/features/provisioning/__tests__/service.test.ts`\n- `src/features/provisioning/__tests__/webhook-lifecycle.test.ts`\n- `src/features/provisioning/__tests__/deprovision.test.ts`\n- `src/features/billing/trial-policy.ts`\n- `src/features/billing/__tests__/trial-policy.test.ts`\n- `src/features/billing/__tests__/policy.test.ts` (if not present)\n- `src/app/admin/launches/page.tsx`\n- `src/app/admin/launches/new/page.tsx`\n- `src/app/admin/launches/[id]/page.tsx`\n- `src/app/admin/launches/actions.ts`\n- `src/app/admin/launches/_components/launch-form.tsx`\n- `src/app/admin/launches/_components/volume-picker.tsx`\n- `src/app/admin/launches/_components/launch-table.tsx`\n- Migration file(s) under `drizzle-migrations/`\n\n## Reusable utilities (do not re-implement)\n\n- `platformAdminActionClient` at `src/lib/action-client.ts:102-109` — all new admin actions wrap this.\n- `ActionError` for surfacing messages to the client.\n- `ensureStripeCustomer` at `src/features/billing/customer.ts:15-36` — for activation.\n- `getPayloadVolumesList` (called by `add-from-payload-panel.tsx`) — for the volume picker.\n- `syncAllLearnersToVolumeTeam` at `src/features/volume-access/team-sync.ts` — pattern reference for direct-insert into Better Auth tables.\n- `sendInvitationEmailForId` at `src/features/organization/invitation-emails.ts:22-69` — for post-commit emails (works as long as `invitation_volumes` rows exist).\n- `tryInsertProcessedEvent` and `syncSubscriptionForWebhook` patterns in the existing webhook handler.\n\n## Verification\n\nPer commit:\n\n1. **Commit 1**: `pnpm vitest src/features/billing/__tests__/policy.test.ts --run` — new tests green. `pnpm tsc --noEmit` (or `pnpm build`) — typecheck passes. Existing learner-invite path in dev: with an org manually set to `preview` via SQL, try inviting a learner — should fail with `preview` reason.\n\n2. **Commit 2**: `pnpm vitest src/features/provisioning/__tests__/service.test.ts --run` — new tests green. Existing tests untouched. Manual: hit `submitLaunch` action against a draft (via a debug script if needed); verify rows are created in `organizations`, `teams`, `organization_volumes`, `invitations`, `invitation_volumes`, and the launch row is updated.\n\n3. **Commit 3**: Smoke the UI as platform admin in dev — `/admin/launches` lists drafts; create a draft; submit; check that the org appears with `lifecycleState: 'preview'` and that invitations are visible to the prospective owner on accept.\n\n4. **Commit 4**: `pnpm vitest src/features/billing/__tests__/trial-policy.test.ts src/features/provisioning/__tests__/webhook-lifecycle.test.ts --run` — new tests green. End-to-end smoke against Stripe sandbox: provision a launch, accept the owner invite, click \"Activate billing,\" complete Checkout with a test card, observe `lifecycleState` flip from `preview` to `active` and learner invites become available.\n\n5. **Commit 5**: `pnpm vitest src/features/provisioning/__tests__/deprovision.test.ts --run` — new tests green. Smoke: deprovision a provisioned-but-not-activated launch; the org row should be gone, the launch row should have `deprovisionedAt` set, snapshots preserved.\n\nFull regression: `pnpm vitest --run` (entire suite) before each commit. Stripe sandbox validation runbook (`docs/runbooks/stripe-sandbox-validation.md`) re-run is not required — the gate change does not affect existing billing paths, and the new activation path is exercised by the smoke in commit 4.\n\n## Notes / deliberate departures\n\n- **Direct DB inserts for `teams` rows**, not `auth.api.createTeam()`. The spec mandates transactional integrity; the existing `auth.api.createTeam()` is a service call and can't participate in a Drizzle transaction. The schema for `teams` (`src/db/schemas/auth.schema.ts:107-121`) is owned by Better Auth and stable; the existing `syncAllLearnersToVolumeTeam` already establishes the precedent for direct inserts into Better-Auth-owned tables.\n- **`invitation_volumes` rows for owner/admin invites** even though they implicitly access all volumes. This keeps the existing email template (`sendInvitationEmailForId`) functional without a template change. The `accessScope: 'all'` column already exists on `invitations` and continues to drive accept-time behavior; populating `invitation_volumes` is just for the email's course-list rendering.\n- **Docs are deferred** per user direction. The spec at `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-13-customer-launch-provisioning.md` is the design-of-record for now; runbooks and CLAUDE.md updates land in a follow-up.\n</plan>","The spec is updated per our discussion. I've done an initial implementation against it. Code-review my changes.\n\nEvaluate:\n- correctness / bugs\n- UX impact\n- performance\n- over-engineering\n- consistency with existing patterns\n- edge cases\n\nFor each issue: rate severity (critical / moderate / minor) and suggest a concrete fix with enough detail to act on. Beyond line-level review, also assess whether the implementation actually solves the intended problem.\n\nBelow is a commit summary for high-level context — review the current state of the codebase as a whole, not commit-by-commit.\n\n---\n\nAll five commits landed. 505/505 tests green, typecheck clean.\n\n## Summary\n\n| #   | Commit     | What                                                                                                                                                                                     |\n| --- | ---------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| 1   | `f5308272` | Schema (`lifecycleState`, `trialPolicy`, provisioning audit columns, `customer_launches` table) + lifecycle awareness inside `checkLearnerSeatAllowed`. Migration `0016_odd_zzzax.sql`.  |\n| 2   | `e17c700c` | Provisioning service: pure hash + validation + transactional row writes (org, teams, volumes, invitations) + orchestration with idempotency. Admin CRUD server actions.                  |\n| 3   | `ac3670e7` | `/admin/launches` UI (list + new + detail + volume picker + pending-invitations panel) + `resendLaunchInvitation`.                                                                       |\n| 4   | `f3ad81a9` | `activatePreviewBilling` action, shared `buildCheckoutSubscriptionData`, `trialParamsForCheckout`, webhook flip via `promotePreviewToActive` reading the synced subscription's metadata. |\n| 5   | `2e7866cc` | Deprovisioning: service with guards, action, UI dialog requiring slug confirmation. Snapshot identity preserved.                                                                         |\n\n## TDD coverage (business logic only)\n\n- 5 tests — `checkLearnerSeatAllowed` lifecycle awareness\n- 9 tests — `computeLaunchConfigHash` (determinism + normalization)\n- 6 tests — `validateLaunchInputsPure`\n- 8 tests — `runProvisioningTransaction` row shapes\n- 8 tests — `provisionOrganization` orchestration\n- 4 tests + 1 todo — `trialParamsForCheckout`\n- 5 tests — `buildCheckoutSubscriptionData`\n- 3 tests — webhook lifecycle flip (admin_launch flips, self_service doesn't, non-checkout events don't)\n- 8 tests — `deprovisionLaunch`\n\nStripe, Better Auth hooks, email delivery, Payload CMS, and React rendering are intentionally untested — that's where the user drew the line.\n\n## Verification still owed (per the plan)\n\nThe Better Auth compatibility smoke is the load-bearing manual check: provision a real launch in dev, accept the owner invite, ensure the resulting `members` row has `role: 'owner'` and the user can reach the org. That validates our direct-insert contract against Better Auth's runtime. Up to you when to run it — the unit suite is green but it can't substitute for that smoke.","Per your suggestion, I've updated the relevant files. The current uncommitted changes should now contain only the targeted updates. Please recheck.\n\n---\n\nThree focused commits landed.\n\n| Commit     | Findings | What changed                                                                                                                                                                                                                            |\n| ---------- | -------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| `bbd25194` | 1, 2, 3  | Preview guard on `createCheckoutSession`; webhook lifecycle flip propagates failures (Stripe retry contract); deprovision refuses on non-terminal `organization_billing` state.                                                         |\n| `a345c321` | 4        | Migration `0017_provisioning_system_user.sql` seeds `system:provisioning`. Provisioning anchors `organization_volumes.created_by_id` and `invitations.inviter_id` to it; actor identity stays on the `set null` audit columns.          |\n| `597c6389` | 5, 6     | New `resendLaunchInvitationForId` service: launch-scope guard, `effectiveInvitationStatus` gate, direct `expiresAt` refresh. `getOrgProvisioningContext` now joins the launch's `agreedSeatCount` into `CheckoutForm.initialSeatCount`. |\n\n518 passing tests (1 todo, pre-existing PDF env failure unrelated), typecheck clean. New tests: 1 webhook (rethrow), 1 self-service preview guard, 3 deprovision billing-state guards, 2 provision-tx system-user assertions, 7 launch-resend.\n\nStill owed for full safety: a Better Auth compatibility smoke (provision → accept owner invite → confirm `members.role='owner'`) — that's the one thing the unit suite can't substitute for. And the migration needs to run before any new provisioning attempt."],"019e225c-adf5-7e62-981e-bf5c4b9af87c":["I think we're on the same page and both specs are already updated. We're going to go ahead and implement the rules PDF case into our current Eval system, and I've come up with a technical plan for incorporating this based on the updated spec.\n\nCan you review the following plan and make necessary comments, pushbacks, or improvements?\n\n---\n\n<plan>\n# Plan: Rules-following PDF eval case (session-mode)\n\n## Context\n\nThe eval harness today treats `sample.steps[]` as independent invocations\n— each step builds a fresh sandbox and `LoopyState`. This makes it\nimpossible to test whether Loopy retains rules from Turn 1 when editing\nin Turn 4. The OGC Schedule Logic PDF case is the first concrete scenario\nthat requires real multi-turn evaluation: the agent reads a customer\nrules document in Turn 1 and must honor those rules across three later\nedit turns.\n\nThis PR adds the minimum infrastructure for session-mode evaluation\n(Loopy-only) and the first case that uses it. The full canonical\n`EvalCase` / `RunArtifact` redesign is deferred — this PR extends the\nlegacy `Sample` shape with three optional fields, leaves all existing\nsamples untouched, and introduces a parallel `invokeSession` path on\n`AgentInvoker`. The rules-case design doc\n(`application/docs/agents/eval-rules-case-design.md`) is the\nauthoritative spec.\n\n## Scope\n\n**In this PR:**\n\n- New optional fields on `Sample`: `multiTurn?: true`, `sessionAssets?`,\n  `sessionJudges?`.\n- New optional method `invokeSession` on `AgentInvoker`. Loopy\n  implements; PlanChat does not.\n- Sandbox attachment staging — new `attachments/` tmpdir subdir,\n  mounted at `/attachments/<id>.pdf` in the Loopy sandbox.\n- Runner branch on `sample.multiTurn` that routes to `invokeSession`\n  and dispatches `sessionJudges` once per sample.\n- New deterministic judge `judgeScheduleLogicRules` returning\n  `{judgement, score}` (existing `Judgement` shape, score=100 ⇔ passed).\n- New `rules` dataset key + new `rulesFollowingSamples` array\n  containing one 4-turn sample using `CambrdgeNorth_vBaseline1.0.xer`\n  and `schedule-logic.pdf`.\n- New behavioral test for `invokeSession` covering session-state\n  accumulation across turns.\n\n**Deferred (called out in the spec, not in this PR):**\n\n- Canonical `EvalCase` / `EvalCaseSource` / YAML authoring.\n- `RunArtifact` shape and projections-as-contract.\n- Token / latency / cost metrics capture (Initiative 1).\n- Per-turn schedule snapshots (we slice the commit log by turn\n  boundary instead — cheaper, enough for debugging).\n- Generic rules-engine judge (hardcode this PDF's rules).\n\n## Verified facts before implementation\n\n- Cambridge fixture: `packages/test-fixtures/data/CambrdgeNorth_vBaseline1.0.xer`\n  (note the typo \"Cambrdge\"; matches existing loader naming).\n- `A1000 Establish site access road` exists (WBS: Construction → Site).\n- `A1060 Concrete pouring` exists (WBS: Construction → Zone 1).\n  Duplicates exist across zones; A1060 is the one to use.\n- `A2400 Project complete` is the project finish milestone (no\n  successors). Turn 4's \"final client inspection\" wires into A2400.\n- `Mobilization` does **not** exist (reviewer was right; design doc\n  references must be replaced with `A1000 Establish site access road`).\n- `Planning complete`, `Construction complete`, `Commissioning complete`\n  milestones exist without successors — confirms the differential-\n  judging premise.\n- Loopy `ask` tool already supports PDFs by sandbox path\n  (`packages/loopy_planchat/src/agent/tools.ts:1324`).\n\n## Critical files to be modified\n\n| Path | Change |\n|---|---|\n| `packages/planchat/eval-judges/samples.ts` | Add `multiTurn?`, `sessionAssets?`, `sessionJudges?` to `Sample` type. Define `EvalAttachmentFixture` and `SessionJudgeSpec` types. |\n| `packages/planchat/src/eval/types.ts` | Add `'rules'` to `DATASET_KEYS`. |\n| `packages/planchat/src/eval/datasets.ts` | Register `'rules': rulesFollowingSamples`. |\n| `packages/planchat/src/eval/agent_invoker.ts` | Add optional `invokeSession?(input): Promise<SessionResult>`. Define `AgentInvokerSessionInput` / `SessionResult` shapes. |\n| `packages/planchat/src/eval/runner.ts` | Branch on `sample.multiTurn`. Dispatch `sessionJudges` once per sample after session ends. |\n| `packages/loopy_planchat/src/eval/invoker.ts` | Implement `invokeSession`: one sandbox, one collector, one `LoopyState`; loop `runLoopyAgentLoop` per turn. |\n| `packages/loopy_planchat/src/eval/sandbox_harness.ts` | Add `attachmentsHostDir` to `SandboxMounts`. Stage `sessionAssets` files into `attachments/` and mount at `/attachments`. |\n| `packages/planchat/eval-judges/judge_schedule_logic_rules.ts` | New file: differential rules judge. |\n| `packages/planchat/eval-judges/data/schedule-logic.pdf` | New file: copy from `/Users/qiushi/Downloads/2.5-Schedule-Logic.pdf`. |\n| `packages/planchat/eval-judges/rules_prompts.ts` | New file: the 4-turn sample. |\n| `packages/loopy_planchat/src/eval/invoker.test.ts` (or similar) | New test: `invokeSession` session-state accumulation. |\n\n## Implementation order (one commit per group)\n\nThe user asked for focused commits as I go, not one giant commit at\nthe end. The order minimizes review surface area per commit and\nensures the suite type-checks at each step.\n\n### Commit 1 — `Sample` shape + types\n\n- Extend `Sample` with three optional fields.\n- Define `EvalAttachmentFixture { id, hostPath, mountPath, mediaType }`.\n- Define `SessionJudgeSpec` discriminated union (initially one variant:\n  `{ type: 'schedule_logic_rules', config: {...} }`).\n- No behavior change; existing samples continue to type-check.\n\n### Commit 2 — `AgentInvoker.invokeSession` contract + Loopy implementation\n\n- Add `invokeSession?(input)` to the interface. Define\n  `AgentInvokerSessionInput` (dataset, sample, schedules, assets,\n  abortSignal) and `SessionResult` (turns, answers, edits,\n  viewGenerations, error?).\n- Loopy: extract sandbox/collector/state setup from `invoke` into a\n  shared helper. Implement `invokeSession`:\n  - Build one sandbox + collector (reusing existing helpers).\n  - Stage session assets into the sandbox.\n  - Seed one `LoopyState` from the first turn's prompt.\n  - For each subsequent turn: append `{role: 'user', content: prompt}`\n    to `state.messages`, reset `state.finished` to false, call\n    `runLoopyAgentLoop` again with the same state.\n  - Capture commit log offsets at each turn boundary (used by the\n    judge to slice edits per turn).\n  - Return `SessionResult` with per-turn answers + aggregated edits.\n- PlanChat: no `invokeSession` (the interface declares it optional).\n\n### Commit 3 — Sandbox attachment staging\n\n- Extend `SandboxMounts` with `attachmentsHostDir?`.\n- In `buildEvalSandbox` (or wherever the sandbox staging happens),\n  create `attachments/` under workdir and copy each `EvalAttachmentFixture`\n  into it.\n- Pass the host dir to `JustBashSandbox` so it bind-mounts at\n  `/attachments`. Verify a PDF placed there is readable via `ask`.\n\n### Commit 4 — Runner branch\n\n- In `runner.ts`, after building `schedules`, check\n  `if (sample.multiTurn)` and dispatch through `invoker.invokeSession`.\n- Existing `for (let stepIx = 0; stepIx < sample.steps.length; stepIx++)`\n  loop becomes the `else` branch. No changes to the per-step path.\n- After `invokeSession` completes, run each `sessionJudge` once with\n  `{before, after, edits, touchedActivityIds, touchedPrereqIds}`.\n- Per-turn judges (existing `editEffectiveSpec`, `answerDescription`)\n  continue to dispatch the same way — the multi-turn path iterates over\n  `sample.steps` to grade each turn's answer/edits against its own spec.\n\n### Commit 5 — Rules judge\n\n- New file `packages/planchat/eval-judges/judge_schedule_logic_rules.ts`.\n- Signature: `({before, after, edits, touchedActivityIds,\n  touchedPrereqIds, requiredRules}) => Judgement`.\n- Differential check (described in the design doc):\n  - For each `requiredRule`, compute `violators(before)` and\n    `violators(after)`. Failure iff `after` adds a new violator not in\n    `before`, restricted to touched entities.\n  - Predicate set: `no_sf_relationships`, `no_negative_lag`,\n    `large_fs_lag_requires_activity`, `new_activities_have_predecessor`,\n    `new_activities_have_successor`, `predecessor_drive`,\n    `successor_drive`.\n- Return `{judgement: <multi-line failure description or pass>, score:\n  failures.length === 0 ? 100 : 0}`. Score=100 maps to passed; the\n  runner's geometric-mean aggregation handles the case-level rollup.\n- Reuse `applyEditsAndReschedule` from the existing\n  `effective_edits_judge.ts` to materialize `after` from `before` + edits.\n\n### Commit 6 — PDF fixture + dataset wiring\n\n- Copy `2.5-Schedule-Logic.pdf` to\n  `packages/planchat/eval-judges/data/schedule-logic.pdf`.\n- Add `'rules'` to `DATASET_KEYS`.\n- Create empty `rules_prompts.ts` exporting\n  `rulesFollowingSamples: Sample[] = []`.\n- Register in `datasets.ts`.\n\n### Commit 7 — The 4-turn sample\n\n- Populate `rulesFollowingSamples` with one sample:\n  - `name: 'rules_pdf_multi_turn_schedule_logic'`\n  - `multiTurn: true`\n  - `tags: ['core_demo', 'rules-following']`\n  - `schedules: [{id: 'baseline', path: 'CambrdgeNorth_vBaseline1.0.xer', name: 'Cambridge North v1.0', isDefault: true}]`\n  - `sessionAssets: [{id: 'schedule_logic_pdf', hostPath: '<resolve at runtime>', mountPath: '/attachments/schedule-logic.pdf', mediaType: 'application/pdf'}]`\n  - Four steps, one per turn, prompts use exact codes (`A1000`, `A1060`,\n    `A2400`) and the mount path `/attachments/schedule-logic.pdf`.\n  - Turn 1: `answerDescription` rubric requires a PDF-specific\n    non-generic rule (PM/PE review, meeting-minutes documentation).\n  - Turns 2-4: `editEffectiveSpec` confirming entity-level outcome.\n  - `sessionJudges: [{type: 'schedule_logic_rules', config: {scheduleId: 'baseline', scope: 'new_and_touched_entities', requiredRules: [...]}}]`.\n\n### Commit 8 — `invokeSession` behavioral test\n\n- New file under the Loopy eval test directory.\n- Mocks at the boundary: the LLM (scripted to emit one tool call per\n  turn — e.g., `answer` with a fixed payload). Sandbox is real (tmpdir).\n- Behaviors tested (one assertion each, following the\n  `~/dev/marswave/cola/docs/testing.md` guidelines):\n  1. **Session state accumulates across turns**: after two prompts,\n     `state.messages` includes both user prompts and both assistant\n     answers in order.\n  2. **`state.finished` resets between turns**: after Turn 1's `answer`\n     tool flips `finished` to true, Turn 2 still runs.\n  3. **Aggregated edits include edits from all turns**: when each\n     scripted turn emits an `apply_edits` call, the returned\n     `SessionResult.edits` contains the union.\n  4. **Attachment is accessible from inside the sandbox**: a session\n     asset declared in the input is readable at its mount path via\n     `sandbox.readFile`.\n- What we do **not** test (per the testing guide): exact prompt\n  strings, internal `LoopyState` field shapes beyond observable\n  message accumulation, hardcoded model IDs, exact judge output text.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `npm run type-check` clean after each commit.\n- `npx vitest run --config vitest.determ-components.config.ts <test file>`\n  passes for the new behavioral test.\n- Run the new rules-case end-to-end against Loopy:\n  ```bash\n  cd application\n  npx dotenv -e .env.development.local -- \\\n    npx tsx packages/planchat/scripts/eval-runner.ts \\\n    --target loopy --dataset rules --case rules_pdf_multi_turn_schedule_logic\n  ```\n  Acceptance per the design doc's success criteria:\n  1. Score in (0, 100) — not trivially passing, not broken.\n  2. Judge failure output names the entity id and rule when it fails.\n  3. Pass rate ≥ 80% across 5 local runs.\n  4. Removing the PDF (clear `sessionAssets`) reliably *fails* the case\n     — confirms the test depends on rule-following, not on the PDF being\n     readable in general.\n\n## Reused functions / utilities\n\n- `applyEditsAndReschedule` from `packages/planchat/eval-judges/effective_edits_judge.ts`\n  — materializes `after` state from `before` + edits for the rules\n  judge. Same path `judgeEffectiveEdits` uses; same scheduling\n  guarantees.\n- `loadCambridgeDemo1_0` from `@planlab/test-fixtures` — fixture loader\n  for the schedule (verify the exported name; if it's\n  `loadCambridgeDemo1_0`, use that; otherwise use the canonical loader\n  for `CambrdgeNorth_vBaseline1.0.xer`).\n- `stageScheduleAsSched`, `stageSkillsDir` from the existing sandbox\n  harness — model for the new `stageAttachments` helper.\n- `newLoopyState`, `runLoopyAgentLoop` from `packages/loopy_planchat/src/agent/`\n  — the session loop reuses these directly, just with a persistent state\n  instance.\n- `judgeTextLLM`, `judgeEffectiveEdits` — used by per-turn judges\n  exactly as today; no changes needed.\n\n## Open items resolved during this plan\n\n- **Attachment mount path**: `/attachments/<id>.pdf` (top-level mount,\n  matches the existing `/input-schedules/`, `/output/`, `/skills/`\n  pattern).\n- **Per-turn snapshots**: not as snapshots; record commit-log offsets\n  at turn boundaries. Cheap; lets the judge slice edits by turn for\n  debugging.\n- **Test strategy**: one behavioral test for `invokeSession` (4\n  one-behavior cases following the testing-guidelines doc). Skip\n  testing trivial wiring; test session-state accumulation, finished-\n  reset, edit aggregation, attachment access.\n- **PR shape**: one PR, 8 focused commits in the order above.\n\n## Out of scope explicitly\n\n- Renaming any existing `Sample` field. The new fields are additive.\n- Changing how `judgeEffectiveEdits` or `judgeTextLLM` work.\n- Touching PlanChat's invoker (it omits `invokeSession`; the runner's\n  multi-turn branch is gated on `sample.multiTurn` which legacy samples\n  don't set).\n- Migrating any existing sample to `multiTurn`.\n- The `EvalCase` canonical model and YAML authoring layer. The rules\n  case is added in TypeScript-prompts shape; it migrates with all\n  other samples when Initiative 4 lands.\n</plan>","The plan updated per our discussion. I've done an initial implementation against it. Code-review my changes.\n\nEvaluate:\n- correctness / bugs\n- UX impact\n- performance\n- over-engineering\n- consistency with existing patterns\n- edge cases\n\nFor each issue: rate severity (critical / moderate / minor) and suggest a concrete fix with enough detail to act on. Beyond line-level review, also assess whether the implementation actually solves the intended problem.\n\nBelow is a commit summary for high-level context — review the current state of the codebase as a whole, not commit-by-commit.\n\nAll 8 commits landed in order. Implementation summary:\n\n**Commits**\n1. `62b5dd6` — `Sample` shape + session types (`multiTurn`, `sessionAssets`, `sessionJudges`, `EvalAttachmentFixture`, `SessionJudgeSpec`, `SessionJudgeResult`, `invokeSession` on `AgentInvoker`)\n2. `1d079d9` — `runLoopySession` helper + `invokeSession` on `loopyInvokerFactory` (no assets yet)\n3. `ce7d6030` — Attachment staging via existing `AttachmentsMount`/`AttachmentsFs`\n4. `dddca99` — Runner branch on `sample.multiTurn` with unsupported-target handling and cumulative per-turn judging\n5. `ad7d303` — `judgeScheduleLogicRules` differential judge + runner dispatch wiring\n6. `a7e4b3e` — PDF fixture + `rules` dataset registration\n7. `261ea73` — 4-turn OGC Schedule Logic sample\n8. `1aac3e0` — Behavioral test for `runLoopySession` (3 passing tests)\n\n**Type-check**: clean on each commit (two pre-existing `_citationsCjs` default-import errors in WIP `core_loop.ts`/`tools.ts` predate this branch).\n\n**Test**: 3/3 pass for `src/eval/session_loop.test.ts` once the pre-existing WIP is set aside.\n\n**Next steps for you**\n- Run the case end-to-end: `cd application && npx dotenv -e .env.development.local -- tsx scripts/agent_eval.ts --target loopy --dataset rules`\n- Acceptance per the rules-case design doc: ≥4/5 local runs pass; clearing `sessionAssets` should cause Turn 1 grounding (or downstream rule judges) to fail.\n- The pre-existing WIP CJS-default-import changes in `core_loop.ts` / `tools.ts` need a separate resolution before CI can run `loopy_planchat` tests — those aren't from this branch.","this is the authors response to your review, he is about to fix based on this, whats your opinion\n\n---\n\nAll five findings are valid. I'd refine the fix for Finding 1, broaden the refactor for Finding 3, and add one issue the reviewer didn't catch.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 1 — Required judge failure is silent (CRITICAL)\n\n**Valid.** I built `SessionJudgeResult` with a `passed` field as the spec required, then dropped it on the floor in the runner. With 5 required rules, a single hard violation gives `score = 80`; geometric-mean across 4 turns + the session judge lands around 95. The T1 gate is non-existent.\n\n**Fix — better than the reviewer's suggestion.** They proposed overloading `averageScore: 0` or adding a `note`. I'd do this instead:\n\n1. Add `passed?: boolean` to `EvaluationSampleResult` (undefined for cases without required judges, so legacy samples are unaffected).\n2. In the multi-turn branch, track `hasRequiredFailure ||= !rulesResult.passed` whenever a required session judge fails.\n3. Set `passed = !hasRequiredFailure` on the result; keep `averageScore` fractional.\n4. Add a `note: 'failed required judge: <rules>'` for human-readable summaries.\n\n**Why better.** The reviewer's \"set `averageScore: 0`\" collapses the gradient at exactly the moment we most want a gradient (regression detection of partial degradation). Overloading `averageScore` semantics also conflates \"rule failed\" with \"crash\" — currently `averageScore: 0` means \"agent execution failed before evaluation.\" Adding `passed` as a separate channel preserves both signals cleanly and matches the spec's \"binary gate + fractional score\" contract verbatim.\n\n## Finding 2 — Turn 3 passes on baseline (CRITICAL)\n\n**Valid, with one caveat.** The reviewer cites `A1070 Concrete curing` already existing in Cambridge with `A1060 Concrete pouring` as predecessor. I didn't verify this in my exploration — the explore agent confirmed `A1060` and `A1080` but not `A1070`. Either way, `nameMatches: 'curing'` is structurally too loose to fail-when-baseline-unchanged, which is what matters.\n\n**Fix.** The reviewer offered three options. Combining them gives the cleanest contract:\n\n1. Verify Cambridge's actual activity inventory for \"curing\" / \"hold\" / \"wait\" tokens before settling on the assertion name.\n2. Tighten the prompt to ask for a uniquely-named activity (\"Curing hold\" or similar phrasing the baseline doesn't use).\n3. Assert *both* edges: predecessor `Concrete pouring` AND successor matching pipe-install at A1080 (by code if `EffectivePrereqAssertion` ever gains `otherActivityCode`, by exact name today).\n4. Skip duration assertions — calendar resolution between 8h/d Standard and 24x7 is ambiguous enough that any concrete number is brittle. The rules judge's `large_fs_lag_requires_activity` predicate captures the duration intent (the agent must NOT add a 200h FS lag); the effective spec just needs to confirm an activity was wired in.\n\nThis means we accept some realism cost (the agent gets steered toward a specific name) in exchange for a test that fails reliably when the agent does nothing.\n\n## Finding 3 — Large-lag check misses edited prereqs (MODERATE)\n\n**Valid.** My implementation tracks creation events (`prereq_creation`) and `prereq_edit` events with `edit_prereq_dependency_type` / `edit_prereq_lag_hours`, but `checkLargeFsLag` only walks the `created` array. An agent that opens an existing FS link and bumps its lag to 200h via `edit_prereq_lag_hours` slips through.\n\n**Fix — broader than just `large_fs`.** The reviewer's \"evaluate after-state of every touched prereq, diff against baseline\" pattern is the right shape, and I'd apply it *uniformly* to all three prereq-targeting predicates (`no_sf`, `no_negative_lag`, `large_fs_lag_requires_activity`) rather than just patching one. Today my `no_sf` and `no_negative_lag` happen to be correct because they walk creation + edit events explicitly, but that's edit-shape-coupled — if a new edit type lands (e.g. a combined relation+lag edit), all three predicates need re-tuning.\n\nThe refactored shape: compute `touchedPrereqIds`, look up each in `after.prereqs[id]`, compare to `before.prereqs[id]`. A predicate fires when the after-state violates AND the baseline didn't violate. One central helper, three predicates over it. Consistent, edit-shape-independent, easier to test.\n\n## Finding 4 — `invokeSession` ignores the normalized `assets` param (MODERATE)\n\n**Valid.** I read `sample.sessionAssets` directly instead of consuming the runner's `assets` input. Today that's equivalent because the runner just passes `sample.sessionAssets ?? []` through, but it breaks the contract: the runner is the resolver of fixture references, and a future YAML loader's job is to materialize `assets` from frontmatter into the normalized shape *before* the invoker sees it.\n\n**Fix.** Trivial — destructure `assets` from the input shape and pass `attachments: assets` to `buildEvalSandbox`. Honors the contract and unblocks the eventual loader without rework.\n\n## Finding 5 — No direct tests for the judge (MODERATE)\n\n**Valid.** The judge is the trust anchor of the entire case. The reviewer's test list is a good starting point. I'd add three:\n\n- **Pre-existing baseline violation is exempt.** Construct a `before` with an SF prereq already present, no edits → judge returns `passed: true`. Directly tests the differential premise.\n- **Edited prereq violation is caught** (covers Finding 3's regression).\n- **Milestone exemption holds.** Create a `start-mile` activity → `new_activities_have_predecessor` does not fire on it.\n\nPlus the reviewer's seven. Cheap to write, paid for many times by every future change to the predicates.\n\n---\n\n## One additional issue the reviewer missed\n\nOnce Finding 1's binary gate is honored, the rules-case design has a contradiction: **`new_activities_have_predecessor` will fire spuriously on Permit approval (Turn 2) and Final client inspection (Turn 4).**\n\nBoth are intended as logical chain endpoints — Permit approval is the *first* activity (the prompt says \"before site work starts\"); Final client inspection is created with an explicit successor (A2400) but the prompt only weakly implies a predecessor (\"near the end\"). A correctly-following agent that does exactly what the prompt asks adds the successor edge but no predecessor, then the rules judge fires `new_activities_have_predecessor` at session end. Currently that's an 80 (still passing under broken Finding 1); once the gate is binary, every well-behaved run fails.\n\nTwo ways to resolve:\n- **Tighten the prompts.** Give both activities a natural upstream predecessor. Turn 2: \"after the existing Planning kickoff activity and before A1000.\" Turn 4: \"after the last construction activity (e.g. Commissioning complete) and before A2400.\"\n- **Drop the predicate for this case.** Remove `new_activities_have_predecessor` from `requiredRules` and rely on the broader `new_activities_have_successor` + drive predicates to catch genuinely-orphan activities.\n\nI'd pick the first — prompts are cheaper to tweak than judge semantics, and the resulting test exercises a more realistic \"rules-following + wire both edges\" behavior. But the second is defensible if we want to keep the prompts simple.\n\n---\n\nReady to apply the fixes when you give the go-ahead. Order I'd suggest: Finding 4 first (trivial, unblocks contract), then Finding 1 (smallest behavioral change for biggest correctness gain), then Findings 2 + the predecessor issue (case design), then Finding 3 (judge refactor), then Finding 5 (tests cement the refactor).","Per your suggestion, I've updated the relevant files. The current uncommitted changes should now contain only the targeted updates. Please recheck.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of the four follow-up commits\n\n**`362cd509d` — FIX-1 (Finding 4):** `invokeSession` destructures `assets` from input rather than reaching into `sample.sessionAssets`. Behavior unchanged today; contract honored for the eventual YAML loader.\n\n**`1e1d618e3` — FIX-2 (Finding 1):** Added `passed?: boolean` on `EvaluationSampleResult`. Runner's multi-turn branch tracks `failedRequiredJudges` and sets `passed = !hasRequiredFailure`. Fractional score preserved. Score column widened to 11 and prefixed with `FAIL ` when the gate fails — impossible to miss in reports. Note column also gets `failed required judge(s): <type>`.\n\n**`c43216f20` — FIX-3 (Findings 3 + 5):** Judge refactored to after-state differential. Each prereq predicate now asks `violates(after) && !violates(before)` over the touched set, independent of which edit type the agent used. Predicates extracted as exported pure functions, tested directly with hand-built minimal schedules — 22 cases pass, including the edited-FS-lag regression the previous implementation missed. Vitest config extended to pick up `eval-judges/**/*.test.ts`.\n\n**`e7edfeedc` — FIX-4 (Finding 2 + predecessor issue):** Cambridge verification confirmed `A1070 Concrete curing` already sits between A1060 and A1080 — exactly the vacuous-pass bug the reviewer flagged. Tightened:\n- Turn 2 names A2300 → Permit approval → A1000 explicitly; spec asserts both edges.\n- Turn 3 asks for a NEW activity named \"Extended curing\" (no Cambridge baseline activity matches that token); both edges asserted.\n- Turn 4 names A2380 → Final client inspection → A2400; both edges asserted.\n\nThe case now exercises the binary T1 gate without firing false positives on correct runs, and the rules judge's predicates fire on the actual rule-following decisions rather than incidental wiring choices.\n\n**Things worth knowing**\n- All commits type-check; only the two pre-existing `_citationsCjs` errors in `loopy_planchat/src/agent/core_loop.ts:3` / `tools.ts:5` remain — they predate this branch.\n- 22 judge tests pass; 3 session-loop tests pass; 8 existing `judgeEffectiveEdits` tests still pass.\n- Ready to run end-to-end: `npm run test:eval:agent:loopy -- -d rules`. The acceptance criteria now have teeth: `FAIL` prefix in the report makes T1 failures impossible to miss.","I have finished the implementation and updated it according to your suggestions. I also updated the spec to reflect the current implementation status. Additionally, I added a final section to the spec documenting some of the problems I observed while running the experiment.\n\nIt is somewhat strange that the current evaluation case is yielding a zero score, which may or may not be expected. I am reminding you to perform a more thorough analysis on this. We should distinguish between two types of problems:\n\n1. Eval Setup Problems: If there are logical errors in how we score the evaluation metrics or how we designed the eval case itself, we need to fix them.\n2. Agent Performance: If the agent is honestly scoring a zero on the case, we can make do with that for the current run. After all, this PR is not designed to improve agent performance.\n\nWe just need to confirm if we are making the right analysis and if the eval case is designed correctly. Please reread the spec regarding the rules for eval case design, paying close attention to the last section on observed problems.\n\nI suggest you run the eval case yourself so you can see the results. It should take about 12 to 15 minutes, so you will need to wait a bit for it to finish.","You can rerun it; I just updated the API keys' environmental variables.","this is the response from the implementation author, what do you think\n\n---\n\nAll three findings are valid. One refinement on F1; otherwise direction is right. My one push-back is on the scope, not the substance.\n\n## F1 — `passed` doesn't reflect per-turn failures (CRITICAL)\n\n**Valid, and I'd refine the scope.**\n\nThe reviewer is correct that today's gate only considers session-level required judges. For a multi-turn case where each turn is an explicit edit ask, per-turn `judgeEffectiveEdits` is implicitly part of the contract — failing those judges should fail the gate. Currently we get `passed: undefined` (since sessionJudges passed vacuously) with `score: 0` and no `FAIL ` prefix in reports. That's incoherent.\n\n**Where I'd diverge from the reviewer's proposal.** They suggested: \"any evaluated `editEffectiveSpec` with score `< 100` should set `passed=false`.\" If applied to *all* samples, that silently changes the gate semantics for every legacy single-turn sample with `editEffectiveSpec` — those cases haven't had a gate before, and quietly handing them one is a meaningful behavior shift unrelated to this PR.\n\n**Better:** scope the per-turn-effective contribution to the gate to **multi-turn samples only**. Single-turn samples retain current optional semantics; they can opt in later by declaring a session judge or by an explicit `required: true` flag (a future spec change). For the rules case specifically — a multi-turn case where the gate's whole point is \"did the agent make the requested edits\" — this gives the right answer without expanding the gate's scope across legacy cases.\n\nAlso: only `judgeEffectiveEdits` should contribute, not `judgeTextLLM`. LLM judges are noisier (rubric phrasing, model nondeterminism) and a Turn 1 grounding miss isn't worth flipping `passed` in the same way a missing schedule edit is. Note format the reviewer suggested looks right: `failed required judge(s): turn 2 effective_edits, turn 3 effective_edits, turn 4 effective_edits`.\n\n## F2 — Use stable task IDs for endpoints (MINOR but real)\n\n**Valid, applies directly.** Cambridge has 13 \"Concrete pouring\" / \"Pipe installation and welding\" activities; `resolveEndpoint`'s \"first match wins\" semantics make `otherNameExact` order-dependent. With current iteration order it might land on Zone 1, but that's an implementation detail of `Object.values()`, not a guarantee. The agent's actual commit edge points to a specific `activityPreId` — the assertion should match by ID, not name.\n\nThe reviewer gave verified task_ids:\n- `A2300 task_187914` (Project start — Turn 2)\n- `A1000 task_187786` (Establish site access road — Turn 2)\n- `A1060 task_187792`, `A1080 task_187794` (Concrete pouring + Pipe installation in Zone 1 — Turn 3)\n- `A2380 task_187918`, `A2400 task_187920` (Handover/Project complete — Turn 4)\n\nI'd verify these once via xer-reader before committing the change (small belt-and-suspenders since the reviewer was already in the fixture). Then replace `otherNameExact: '...'` with `otherActivityId: 'task_...'` in all three turns' specs. Cleanly removes the ordering dependence.\n\n## F3 — Thin session artifact (MINOR but high payoff)\n\n**Valid; same instinct I had earlier in this session.** When you asked \"is this an eval bug\" I had to read verbose stderr to count tool calls per turn and couldn't tell which tools. The reviewer hit the same wall and worse — they had to infer \"js-exec timed out\" from answer text. The structured data is right there on Loopy's side: `result.turns[i].toolCalls` is an array of `{toolName, args, durationMs, ...}`. The invoker just doesn't project it into `session.json`.\n\nAdding this is ~15 lines: collect a `loopyTurns: Array<{index, finishReason, durationMs, toolNames: string[]}>` projection (no full args — those can be large and contain sensitive content) and write it next to the existing fields. Future diagnosis becomes `jq '.loopyTurns[] | select(.finishReason != \"stop\")'` instead of a workdir hunt.\n\nIf we want to add per-tool detail (bash command, exit code) the way the reviewer suggested, the invoker can also tee Loopy's tool-execution records — but that's a more invasive collector change. The minimal version (tool names + timing + finish reason per loop turn) closes 80% of the gap.\n\n## What I'd push back on\n\n**The \"tiny sandbox smoke check\"** (\"`bash: js-exec -c 'console.log(1)'` in the session setup path\"). The reviewer framed this as \"before trusting the 0 as purely model behavior\" — but that's a debug-time concern, not a routine-run concern. If F3 lands, the next zero-score diagnosis takes 30 seconds: open `session.json`, see `toolNames: ['ask', 'bash', 'bash', ...]`, see no `commit_edits`. The smoke check would add startup latency for every run when the diagnostic affordance does the job after-the-fact. I'd defer it.\n\n## Recommended order\n\n1. **F3 first.** Better instrumentation. Pays for itself on every future diagnosis. Tiny change, no behavior impact.\n2. **F1 next.** Gate fix. Multi-turn-only scope as proposed. Changes report output for the rules case (FAIL prefix will now show, which is honest).\n3. **F2 last.** Endpoint tightening. Verify task_ids first, then replace.\n\nThe reviewer's \"js-exec timed out\" observation is interesting context but it's agent-runtime work, not in scope here. Worth flagging in a sidecar issue/note for whoever owns Loopy's tool layer.\n\nWant me to go through them in that order?","ok go ahead and implement the fix","just updated the keys, can you recheck","go ahead and break the current uncommited to a few commits, two files might have some ad hot workarounds to the eval to work locally with cjs, you can leave them","commit this as well application/docs/agents/eval-improvements.md\n\n\n\n","what do you think a good branch name for this would be, it grows more than just docs","just renamed, can you looked at the current uncommited, I feel like we should restore those workarounds to a clean state, but document the workarounds somewhere (and maybe fix it in the future) so next time if we need to run eval locally we know how to do it","It suddenly occurred to me: could it be because it runs into the GS sandbox failure? Could it be because we haven't been starting the local ingest server?","So basically, you think that the eval can just be run independently without anything (like no need to pnpm dev) to start the application or start the Inngest server?\n\nIf we're running standalone, which is our current setup, is our description of the agent's behavior accurate? I feel like the symptom we find—where the agent repeatedly fails to hit the sandbox—is actually a runtime failure. It seems like a setup issue and not an agent issue.And if you want to write some temporary scripts to verify that, you're free to do that.","Do you have any suggestions for getting the local sandbox working? Is it because we lack certain API keys, requires additional setup, or is there an error occurring? Is this something we can make work locally?","Can you rerun the eval case? You may want to do a minimal test first to make sure that the sandbox local runtime is working, and then rerun the eval case. \n\nI want to see a more accurate score for the agent's work on the PDF rules case.","I just updated the API keys so you can rerun it.","Let's update the 10.3 spec and the stale section within it. Let me know when you're ready to rerun the eval case, as I'll be updating the API keys again.","you can rerun now, run it in the backgroud maybe, before that you can commit the current changes"]},"composer-auto-context-enabled":false,"sidebar-collapsed-groups":{},"app-shell:right-panel-width:v2:/local/:conversationId":0.33771484375,"heartbeat-thread-permissions-by-id":{"019e061c-02a8-7d30-bce2-6e0899b3018b":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approvalsReviewer":"user","sandboxPolicy":{"type":"dangerFullAccess"}},"019e0b07-18eb-71e3-a438-602b5414df3c":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approvalsReviewer":"user","sandboxPolicy":{"type":"dangerFullAccess"}},"019e0b10-cde3-7e61-89d9-13b8fe592e28":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approvalsReviewer":"user","sandboxPolicy":{"type":"dangerFullAccess"}},"019e0b65-8e06-7810-ba2f-2137eae8725e":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approvalsReviewer":"user","sandboxPolicy":{"type":"dangerFullAccess"}},"019e0d7c-dcce-7403-a8ec-a5b64b21aea6":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approvalsReviewer":"user","sandboxPolicy":{"type":"dangerFullAccess"}},"019e0d7d-c804-7bc0-aab7-e36458255c1b":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approvalsReviewer":"user","sandboxPolicy":{"type":"dangerFullAccess"}},"019e0e8e-0022-7a82-9c88-cf277141e72c":{"approvalPolicy":"never","approval